<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BaseClosings     10-26 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Base Closings,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Already Trying to Protect Home-District Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ink was barely dry on the military
base-closing law signed by President Reagan this week when 17
senators began trying to make sure their home-district bases are
spared at the expense of others.
   The senators, from Northeastern and Midwestern states, claimed
that the Sunbelt region has a disproportionate share of military
installations and therefore should suffer the most cuts.
   The senators said in a letter Tuesday that a Pentagon-appointed
commission should consider ``regional inequities'' as it decides
which bases to close.
   Reagan had signed the base-closing bill just one day earlier. It
authorizes the Defense Department to close unneeded military bases
to achieve savings of up to $5 billion per year.
   A 12-member commission is authorized to make the decisions and
report on is conclusions by Dec. 31. Congress may veto the entire
list but cannot act to protect individual bases, as it often has in
the past.
   ``We wish to prevent the further entrenchment of regional
inequities stemming from the location of existing military
facilities,'' said the letter from members of the Northeast-Midwest
Senate Coalition.
   The letter was addressed to Abraham Ribicoff, a former senator
from Connecticut who co-chairs the Defense Secretary's Commission on
Base Realignment and Closure.
   Jim Abbee, spokesman for the base closing commission, laughed and
said, ``So what's new?'' when told about the senators' letter. Abbee
said he would not comment further until he had seen a copy.
   The senators said in their letter that Sunbelt states already
enjoy an advantage in numbers of bases.
   The letter pointed to a report by congressional conferees on the
base-closing bill that said geography should ``be carefully weighed
during the commission's deliberations leading to its closure and
realignment recommendations.''
   However, that provision was dropped before the legislation was
given final approval.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci will have until Jan. 15 to
accept or reject the list of recommended base closings.
   Signing the letter were the two senators each from Pennsylvania,
New York, New Jersey, Illinois, Maine, Michigan and Massachusetts,
and Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., and Richard
Lugar, R-Ind.
</TEXT>
