<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Chile     10-26 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Chile,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Eases Policy Toward Chile</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is preparing to
support a loan request by Chile in the Inter-American Development
Bank, indicating a policy shift that State Department officials say
reflects improved human rights performance in that country.
   The bank was expected to take up Chile's request for a $35
million loan for rural road repair today.
   The administration has invariably abstained on such requests in
recent years as evidence of its displeasure toward the policies of
the country's military government.
   According to the officials, Chile's human rights record has
improved substantially in recent months, with the lifting of a
15-year old state of emergency in August and a national plebiscite
held three weeks ago.
   Chilean voters denied President Augusto Pinochet an additional
eight-year term and open elections are scheduled for next year.
   Until recently, the administration had frequently criticized
Chile on grounds that it was one of only a handful of hemispheric
countries that had not moved toward democratic rule.
   The only exception to the administration's policy of abstaining
on Chilean loan requests involved projects that offered direct
benefits to the poor. The pending request before the IADB does not
fall into that category.
   The State Department officials, insisting on anonymity, said the
U.S. decision to support the road repair loan does not mean Chile
can count on U.S. backing for future loan requests.
   Those votes will be based on Chile's future human rights record
and on the viability of the project for which financing is sought.
   Abstentions cast by American delegates to the IADB and other
international financial institutions on Chilean requests usually
were symbolic because Chile was able to count on enough support from
other bank members to ensure approval of its applications.
   The United States is the principal contributor to the IADB, which
was set up 30 years ago to promote development in Latin America.
   The administration policy to abstain on most Chilean requests
generally was supported by Congress, which enacted a statute a
decade ago barring the executive branch from assisting countries
engaging in ``gross and consistent'' human rights violations.
   Chile was never placed in that category but the administration
decided to show disapproval over the situation in Chile through the
abstention policy.
   There are a number of other impediments to the restoration of
normal relations between the United States and Chile. For more than
a decade, Congress has barred military aid and training to Chile as
well as bilateral economic aid.
   The officials said no decision on lifting any of these sanctions
is expected this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
