<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0051EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra     10-26 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Accuse North Of Commiting `Classic Fraud'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver L. North and his co-defendants
perpetrated ``a classic fraud on government'' when they diverted
profits from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to help arm the Nicaraguan
rebels, prosecutors said.
   Responding to North's contention that he did not defraud the
government, prosecutors said the four Iran-Contra defendants created
a ``secret slush fund'' for activities ``outside the normal channels
of governmental accountability.''
   By overcharging Iran for weapons in the arms-for-hostage
transactions, North and the others undermined President Reagan's
initiative to free Americans held in Lebanon by pro-Iranian groups,
independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh said in pleadings filed
Tuesday.
   North and former national security adviser John M. Poindexter
``chose to advance their private, unauthorized ends at the cost of
putting at hazard the ends they were supposed to be pursuing,
including that of saving the lives of the Americans held hostage in
Lebanon.''
   North, Poindexter and arms dealers Albert Hakim and retired Air
Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord are charged with conspiring to
defraud the government and theft by diverting more than $14 million
in arms-sale profits to a criminal ``enterprise'' that secretly
financed the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   North's lawyers contended in pleadings filed Oct. 11 that there
was no fraud or theft because the government didn't own the weapons
after they were sold to Secord and Hakim, who acted as middlemen in
the transactions.
   But Walsh said the alleged scheme ``constitutes a classic fraud
on the government.''
   ``The thrust of the fraud is the breach of the public trust:
Poindexter's and North's discharge of their official duties (e.g.,
execution of the Iran initiative) was driven by a concealed and
wholly improper motive _ a desire to generate a slush fund for use
in financing unauthorized activities designated by them.''
   Prosecutors said North, a retired Marine lieutenant colonel,
``exploited his position to exact from Iranians a high selling
price, while concealing from the government the nature of the price
spread and his control over the excess profits.''
   ``The goals of establishing improved relations with Iran and
potentially securing the release of American hostages held by groups
sympathetic to that country were undermined and put seriously at
risk by the conspirators' private motive to charge prices well in
excess of what otherwise might have been charged in order to secure
additional profits,'' the prosecution said.
   ``Defendants Secord and Hakim agreed to hold funds generated by
North and to apply them to purposes selected by North and Poindexter
outside the normal challenges of governmental accountability,''
prosecutors said.
   Secord and Hakim ``reaped lucrative profits from the money North
steered to them'' as middlemen in the transactions, prosecutors said.
   Prosecutors said they were not required to show that the
defendants' activities undermined Reagan's effort to free the
hostages. ``It is enough that it was reasonably foreseeable that
they would have that effect, as it clearly was.''
   No date has been set for the trial of North, the first of four
trials ordered by U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell.
</TEXT>
