<DOCNO> AP881026-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0051EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CastleberryRecall     10-26 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Castleberry Recall,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Food Company Recalling Cans Of Corned Beef Hash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Castleberry's Food Co. said Tuesday it is
recalling 2,161 cases of canned corned beef hash because part of one
day's production was improperly cooked.
   Only 35 cases actually are believed to be involved, but the
company is recalling the entire day's production of the product from
Sept. 21 ``to be on the safe side,'' said Dick Lamb, director of
personnel.
   The corned beef hash is packaged in 7.5 ounce single serving cans
with pull-tops. The product is sold primarily in vending machines,
but some is sold through convenience and grocery stores.
   Castleberry's described as possibly non-sterile the product in
cans under the code numbers 2J81CBV4 and 2J81CBV3. The food was
distributed in Georgia, North Carolina, South Carolina, Alabama, New
Jersey and Michigan. Of the more than 2,000 cases involved in the
recall, 36 cases were distributed in Georgia.
   Consumers who have 7.5-ounce cans of the hash with either of the
codes on the bottom of the cans were asked to return the product to
the store where it was purchased for a refund.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
