<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Grain-China     10-26 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Grain-China,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Buys More US Wheat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private exporters have sold China an additional
400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices for shipment
in December, according to the Agriculture Department.
   The sales, equal to about 14.7 million bushels, were handled by
six companies: Cargill Inc., 50,000 tons; Continental Grain Co.,
110,000; Richco Grain Co., 40,000; Louis Dreyfus Corp., 120,000;
Bunge Corp., 40,000; and Mitsubishi International Corp., 40,000.
   Melvin E. Sims, general manager for the department's Foreign
Agricultural Service, said Tuesday the sales were part of 2 million
tons of wheat authorized on Aug. 18 under the Export Enhancement
Program.
   Although no selling prices or other details were announced,
recent prices of wheat at farm points have averaged around $3.84 per
bushel, indicating a U.S. farm value of about $56 million.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat.
   The program enables exporters to sell wheat and other designated
commodities to specified countries at reduced prices in order to
meet foreign competition. The exporters then collect free government
surpluses of grain or other products as bonuses, or subsidies.
   Sims said the bonuses due the six exporters for the latest deal
averaged $21.12 per ton of wheat, or about 58 cents per bushel.
   China has an additional 560,000 tons of U.S. wheat available
under the Export Enhancement Program, he said.
</TEXT>
