<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--MutinyTrial     10-26 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Mutiny Trial,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fisherman Accused Of Mutiny Pleads Guilty To Lesser Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fisherman charged with mutiny for
shooting the captain of a fishing boat while at sea because he
wasn't allowed to eat some of the day's catch has pleaded guilty to
a lesser charge.
   Fredesvina Avila-Iscoa, 32, also had been charged with assault
with intent to commit mutiny and a firearms violation for shooting
Capt. Michael Palacio after an argument aboard the M-V Daniel J.
   He pleaded guilty Monday in U.S. District court to assault with
intent to commit bodily injury with a weapon and faces five to 20
years in prison and a fine up to $250,000.
   The original charges carried a maximum sentence of 35 years in
prison and $750,000 fine.
   Prosecutors said the argument broke out July 23, about 250 miles
offshore, when Avila was told not to eat fish the captain had caught.
   Avila shot Palacio in the leg with a 9 mm pistol after the
captain refused to feed him other provisions and threatened to
withhold his pay, according to witnesses.
</TEXT>
