<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister Menachem Begin broke his
customary silence to telephone his successor, Yitzhak Shamir, and
wish him a happy birthday.
   Shamir, running for re-election in the Nov. 1 elections,
celebrated his 73rd birthday Tuesday with a surprise party at his
office.
   Aides prepared a cake decorated with iced flowers and the
traditional Jewish blessing ``May you live until 120'' as well as a
special wish that Shamir serve ``another four years'' as Israel's
prime minister.
   Since Begin resigned without explanation in 1983, he has been a
virtual recluse, emerging from his Jerusalem home only to attend
annual memorial services for his late wife, Aliza.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version of the following item moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terry Bradshaw says a 33-year-old softball
injury created more anxiety than the countless injuries he sustained
during his 14 years as a National Football League quarterback.
   Doctors discovered Monday that the old injury was to blame for
chest pains that have plagued the CBS-TV football commentator in
recent weeks. The diagnosis came amid a report by a Pittsburgh TV
station that the scar matter doctors found was a tumor.
   Bradshaw, 40, said Tuesday from his suburban Dallas home that he
was about 7 years old when he was hit by a softball, breaking his
sternum. He first noticed chest pains Oct. 11, prompting him to
undergo tests.
   ``Not knowing what's wrong is the thing that drives you crazy,''
Bradshaw said. ``I've worried myself sick these past few weeks.''
   Bradshaw led the Pittsburgh Steelers to an unprecedented four
Super Bowl championships during an NFL career that ended in 1983.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old boy who was nearly killed six years
ago in a fire set by his father met with Edward I. Koch but resisted
the mayor's attempts to coax him back to New York.
   David Charles Rothenberg, whose plight was depicted Tuesday night
in the ABC-TV movie ``David,'' remains disfigured by the burns he
suffered March 2, 1983, when he was left in the flaming Buena Park,
Calif., motel room.
   His father, Charles Rothenberg, said he wanted to kill his son
and himself because he feared his ex-wife wouldn't let him see the
child again. But the older Rothenberg fled the fire. Rothenberg
pleaded guilty and comes up for parole next year.
   ``Can you really get used to California?'' Koch asked the boy, a
former New York resident, during a visit Tuesday at City Hall.
   ``I am,'' answered David, a drummer in a junior high school band
in Anaheim.
   Koch predicted the boy would get bored with California.
   ``You don't want orange juice. You want seltzer,'' the mayor told
him.
   ``They have seltzer in California,'' David answered.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mathias Rust, the West German
pilot who landed in Red Square last year and spent 14 months in
prison for violating Soviet air space, wants to return to visit
Moscow legally, a magazine reported.
   The weekly Goldenes Blatt said Tuesday that Rust, 20, had been
denied a visa by the Soviet embassy in Bonn and now plans to write
directly to Mikhail Gorbachev.
   ``I wanted to visit Red Square and see the city's sights with my
mother. Other than the court and the cell, I saw little of Moscow,''
Rust said.
   Rust caused a major shakeup of the Soviet military leadership
after he flew his single-engine Cessna to the Kremlin unhindered on
May 28, 1987.
   Rust was convicted of illegally entering the Soviet Union,
violating international flight rules and malicious hooliganism, and
sentenced to four years. He was released Aug. 4.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Australian novelist Peter Carey, who won the
coveted Booker Prize for fiction, says he wished he had been more
optimistic about his chances of receiving the award.
   ``If I'd known I was going to win, I think I would have taken a
bit more trouble with my handwriting,'' he said Tuesday as he stared
down at his notes of an acceptance speech.
   Five judges announced the $26,250 prize for Carey's love story
``Oscar and Lucinda.'' The winner came from 102 books published in
Britain during the past 12 months.
   The Booker Prize is administered by Book Trust, an educational
charity promoting books, and is sponsored by Booker, an
international food and farming business.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Songwriter Sammy Cahn has won five
Oscars and an Emmy, but he says one of his biggest thrills will be
performing at an Atlantic City casino this weekend.
   ``When I get to Atlantic City, I'm going to laugh so loud at the
marquee,'' said Cahn, 75, whose songs include ``Love and Marriage,''
``High Hopes,'' and ``Call Me Irresponsible.''
   ``To see my name in a place where so many performers have come to
sing my songs. Do you know what a kick that will be?''
   Cahn's excitement also may be due to the fact that although he's
been in show business 60 years, he's only been performing for about
15 years.
   ``I always wanted to be a performer, but when I started out,
vaudeville was phasing out,'' said Cahn.
   ``When I get on stage, I have a most unique show, and when I
finish, they stand up and cheer,'' Cahn said. ``Not because I
finished, but because it's a miracle.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An undisclosed illness forced rock star
Rod Stewart to cancel a concert here about 50 minutes after it was
scheduled to start.
   At 8:20 p.m. Monday, a member of Stewart's road crew announced to
the audience of about 9,100 at the Met Center that the singer was
ill.
   ``He can hardly talk,'' the aide told the audience. He said
Stewart had consulted with a doctor before the show.
   The concertgoers filed out of the stadium peacefully, but many
were disgruntled.
   The concert's producers said they will try to reschedule the
performance.
</TEXT>
