<HEAD>Music, Automaking Superstars Meet Backstage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One made ``Bad.'' The other makes
``Ram'' pickup trucks. And Michael Jackson and Lee Iacocca had a
similarly brief exchange of words when the pop superstar met the
Chrysler Corp. chairman.
   Iacocca met Jackson backstage shortly before the singer performed
Monday night at the Palace of Auburn Hills. The meeting was set up
after one of Jackson's attorneys wrote to Iacocca.
   ``Michael had read Lee's book (`Talking Straight') and, you know,
Michael is mentioned in the book,'' Chrysler spokesman John Guiniven
said. ``There was a mutual interest in the meeting.''
   But Guiniven said he had no idea what the two said to each other.
   In ``Talking Straight,'' Iacocca defended the $20.5 million he
made in 1986 through salary and stock options, writing: ``$20
million sounds more like Michael Jackson's income for a weekend than
the annual pay of a guy who can't carry a tune in the shower.''
   Iacocca's estimate was off the mark if Monday night's show was
anywhere near Jackson's standard. Net income from the concert was
$125,000, an amount Jackson donated Sunday to the Motown Museum,
honoring the Motown Records label to which he and his brothers were
signed in 1969.
</TEXT>
