<DOCNO> AP881026-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TrappedWhales 2ndLd-Writethru a0782 10-26 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trapped Whales, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0782,0763</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Ships Arrive, Begin Breaking Ice</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with progress of Soviet
icebreaking, quotes from rescue commanders. Deletes outdated matter
and picks up 14th graf pvs `Gary Hufford....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BARTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARROW, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Soviet ships arrived and one began
pounding through ice Tuesday in an effort to free two gray whales
trapped off the northern Alaska coast for nearly three weeks.
   The Admiral Makarov started breaking ice almost immediately after
the vessel arrived near Point Barrow. By evening, the ship had made
substantial progress and was expected to continue working through
the night, with its companion cargo vessel, the Vladimir Arseniev,
clearing away the shattered ice.
   The Soviet ships flew the flags of both the Soviet Union and the
United States in a symbol of international cooperation. The rescue
effort, called Operation Breakthrough, also has involved Eskimos
with chain saws and an unusual vehicle called an Archimedes screw
tractor acting in concert.
   ``It's very nice to work together to do something good between
two people,'' said Alexander Patzevich, chief officer of the Admiral
Makarov.
   U.S. Coast Guard Capt. Joseph McClelland Jr. called the effort
``terrific'' and was optimistic the whales would be freed.
   ``With the wind going the way it is, it couldn't be better,'' he
said.
   Biologists reported the whales were in good condition.
   They moved around a shoal through which they had refused to pass
earlier, and by Tuesday night they were about two miles from an open
lead, or pathway, through the ice and 2 miles beyond the site at
which they and another whale were found.
   Rescuers, meanwhile, received one bit of good news about the
jumbled mass of ice.
   They discovered that a pressure ridge apparently was not anchored
to the sea bottom as initially was feared. A pressure ridge is where
two opposing ice masses meet.
   ``It appears that most of the ridge has a current running through
it, making it easier for the icebreakers to work,'' said Ron Morris,
a biologist with the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
   The California gray whales must get through the tangle if they
are to reach the nearest completely open water, 200 miles away in
the Chukchi Sea.
   Gary Hufford, with the National Weather Service, said he and
another ice expert were working on the pressure ridge Monday when
they had some unwelcome company _ a polar bear. A helicopter pilot
landed the aircraft between the whales and the bear, which caused
the animal to leave.
   ``It's something to remember. There are not only whales out
there,'' Hufford said.
   The whales were stranded about 100 yards offshore nearly three
weeks ago by shifting ice about 13 miles northeast of Barrow. A
third whale disappeared Friday and is presumed dead.
   Biologists reported a setback late Monday when the whales balked
near a shoal and retreated about a half-mile toward shore.
   Craig George, a biologist with the North Slope Borough, said the
whales overnight remained well back from a series of new breathing
holes that had been cut toward the ice ridge. They apparently were
spooked by the shallow water.
   There is about 12 feet of water over the 125-yard-wide shoal,
George said. The whales had been spending most of the time in water
17- to 25 feet deep.
   The turnaround came after rescuers switched tactics Monday. They
connected a series of breathing holes to form a single open channel
some 600 yards long. Eskimos used long poles to guide the miniature
icebergs toward the rear of the slot.
   Initially, the strategy worked. But when the channel behind them
was nearly filled, the whales reversed course, struggling up for air
by poking their way through the large slabs of ice and thick slush.
   That setback offset earlier excitement about the performance of
the Archimedes screw tractor, a 12-ton machine that smashes up to 18
inches of ice as it moves along on pontoons shaped like augers.
   It leaves a slushy path 14-feet wide in its wake. Technicians
were building a rake of sorts Tuesday, designed to follow along in
the channel behind the big auger. The rake is supposed to shunt the
slush down and under the adjacent ice, officials said.
   Biologists said they also were considering ``Plan C,'' a
last-ditch possibility that they may have to airlift the animals to
open water. Withrow said it was a last resort because the whales
could be injured.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
