<DOCNO> AP881026-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CampaignCelebrities Bjt   10-26 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Celebrities, Bjt,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hollywood Stars, Sports Heroes Add Glamour to Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What do you do when your presidential candidate
is a bit too boring, lacking the star quality that sends crowds into
a frenzy? You cast your gaze on Hollywood and search the sports
arenas for the celebrities who can inject a little glamour into your
campaign.
   Robert Redford. Cher. Charlton Heston. Morgan Fairchild. John
Elway. Don Johnson.
   Aides to Democrat Michael Dukakis and Republican George Bush _
definite runners-up in the glamour category _ have enlisted the help
of Hollywood's box-office draws and sports' superstars to attract a
crowd, liven up a stump speech and capture a few more precious
seconds on the evening news.
   When Dukakis delivered a speech denouncing the Reagan
administration's environmental record to a college audience in New
Brunswick, N.J., he was accompanied by actor, director and
environmentalist Robert Redford.
   The blond-haired star of such movies as ``Butch Cassidy and the
Sundance Kid,'' ``Downhill Racer,'' ``The Candidate'' and ``Legal
Eagles'' drew squeals and cheers from the large crowd on the Rutgers
University campus.
   Redford also delivered a line that made every network news
program.
   ``Hello everybody, I'm Dan Quayle,'' joked Redford, whom Quayle
has been said to resemble.
   Redford continued his effort to help Dukakis, appearing at a
toxic landfill in Aurora, Colo., a once-heavily polluted river in
Seattle and other stops around the nation.
   ``I'm a citizen just like you are,'' Redford told the crowd in
Seattle earlier this month. ``Being an actor doesn't mean you lose
your citizenship.''
   At the Republican National Convention, the GOP had actor Charlton
Heston intone the Pledge of Allegiance in a voice many believe is
what God sounds like. It worked as delegates chattering and moving
about on the convention floor paused to join the ``Ben Hur'' and
``Ten Commandments'' star in reciting the pledge.
   Even before Bush and Dukakis had secured the nominations, the
campaigns were using celebrities.
   Tennis star Pam Shriver, in her job with the Bush campaign,
called members of Bush's ``1139 Club,'' which included current and
former party officials selected as delegates to the convention. The
number 1,139 was the total needed to win the GOP nomination.
   Through a questionnaire, the campaign determined delegate
background information such as birthdays, personal interests and
issues of most concern.
   ``It's an effort to create a national Bush family,'' said David
Sparks, who served as Bush's chief delegate counter.
   Ms. Shriver, who was assigned three or four delegates to keep in
touch with, was available to discuss both the vice president's
campaign and how to improve a cross-court volley.
   Former New York Giants and Minnesota Vikings quarterback Fran
Tarkenton, now an Atlanta businessman, has served as honorary Bush
campaign co-chairman in Georgia where he is recruiting businessmen.
   ``We need to get off the seats of our pants,'' Tarkenton said
last month in announcing his plans.
   But involvement in the political process doesn't always draw
praise. When Penn State football coach Joe Paterno agreed to deliver
a seconding speech for Bush at the GOP convention, the state's
Democratic Gov. Bob Casey criticized Paterno, questioning whether a
state college coach should take on such a high-profile political
posture.
   Paterno, who coached his football team to a national championship
two years ago, gave the speech anyway.
   Fifty celebrities, including Ms. Fairchild, Cher, Gregory Peck
and Hollywood's ``Brat Pack'' star Rob Lowe, chose to help the
Democratic cause by traveling to cities in California, Oregon and
Washington for a voter registration drive.
   Meanwhile, some of their compatriots in the Los Angeles area met
for the traditional Hollywood political event _ a fund-raiser with
the candidate. Television producer Norman Lear held the celebrity
fete last month for Dukakis, with ``Miami Vice'' star Johnson, actor
Burgess Meredith, comedian Chevy Chase and actress Goldie Hawn in
attendance.
   Some superstars, however, get involved without knowing it.
   Republican vice presidential candidate Dan Quayle received Denver
Broncos quarterback John Elway's autograph and jersey during the GOP
candidate's stop in Colorado.
   The team's treasurer and chief financial officer made the
presentation _ unbeknown to Elway.
   ``I'm glad (Quayle) got it, instead of Dukakis, because I'm going
for Bush,'' Elway said when informed of the gift.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
