<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Arms-Inspections     10-26 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms-Inspections,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Decides Dispute Over Inspections Needed Under Strategic
Weapons Treaty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has resolved a dispute between
the State and Defense Departments over how much on-site inspection
should be sought in negotiations with the Soviet Union on a treaty
to reduce long-range nuclear missiles, according to a report
published today.
   The New York Times says the president chose a plan backed by the
State Department. Civilian Defense Department leaders had argued in
favor of a far broader verification proposal.
   Under the proposal chosen, a list of sites would be agreed upon
at which each side could conduct short-notice inspections, The Times
says. Each country would be given the right to conduct snap
inspections at these designated sites, mainly those used to make
rocket motors for solid-fuel missiles, said the newspaper, citing
unidentified administration officials.
   Each country also would have the right to request quick
inspections of any facility in the other's territory, but if the
facility was not on the list of designated sites, the request could
be denied.
   The party that rejected the inspection would be required to
explain its reasons and to take action to alleviate the other side's
concerns over possible cheating, The Times said.
   The newspaper said the plan was generally supported by the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, the Central Intelligence Agency and the Arms
Control and Disarmament Agency as well as the State Department.
   The treaty banning intermediate-range nuclear missiles, ratified
by both countries, provides for short-notice inspections of missile
sites and stationing inspectors at one missile assembly plant in
each country.
   U.S. and Soviet strategic arms negotiators are expected to recess
their talks in Geneva in mid-November and not resume them until next
year.
</TEXT>
