<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ZZZZBest Bjt   10-26 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ZZZZ Best, Bjt,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Whiz Kid Testifies He Was Frightened Into Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fallen whiz kid who made and lost millions
in carpet cleaning admitted at his securities fraud trial he was so
desperate to keep the business afloat he stole his grandmother's
jewelry.
   Barry Minkow, seeking to dispel his image as a corrupt business
prodigy, testified Tuesday that he was a frightened little boy
manipulated by extortionists.
   ``I didn't know what to do,'' said Minkow, who admitted he
perpetrated a multimillion-dollar swindle that defrauded investors
of about $25 million. ``I was in the 11th grade. I had a lot of
trouble sleeping. I knew I was in a lot of trouble.''
   Minkow, now 22, took the stand as the first defense witness and
told jurors how his youthful ambition led him to form the ZZZZ Best
carpet cleaning company at age 16 in his parent's garage.
   But he said he could not have done it without a $1,600 loan from
a man he portrayed as his Svengali, Daniel Krowpman.
   ``He was my idol,'' Minkow told jurors. ``He was everything
because he had money; he had build. He had everything I didn't have.
... He was nice to me. He was like the father I never had. I loved
him.''
   But Minkow blamed all his troubles on Krowpman, a co-defendant
who has pleaded guilty to verifying false ZZZZ Best invoices.
   Minkow portrayed Krowpman as a 230-pound weight lifter and loan
shark with a retinue of muscular thug enforcers. He said Krowpman
once tried to sexually molest him.
   For his $1,600 loan, Minkow said Krowpman demanded $200-a-week
payments plus half the company's profits.
   Later, he testified, another co-defendant, Tom Padgett, demanded
10 percent of the profits for a loan he provided. Minkow said
Padgett was ``a Nazi'' who defamed Minkow's Jewish heritage.
   ``I felt like I was taking money from the devil,'' said Minkow.
   He said the pressures for loan shark payments drove him to steal
his grandmother's jewelry, and ``I bounced checks everywhere.''
   ``I had to pay Krowpman,'' he said. ``That was first. Everything
else was second. I went from bank to bank. Nothing else mattered.''
   Once, he said, he spoke of calling the police, and Krowpman
threatened him.
   ``What did he say would happen?'' asked Minkow's lawyer, David
Kenner.
   ``He'd kill me,'' Minkow replied in a near whisper.
   During pauses in his testimony, Minkow alternately chewed on his
fingernails and bit chunks out of a Styrofoam cup.
   The prosecution has portrayed Minkow as a shrewd con man who
knowingly defrauded investors and banks out of about $25 million.
   Kenner has said that Minkow would prove he committed crimes under
duress, fearful he would be killed by Krowpman and other
mob-connected figures.
   But U.S. District Judge Dickran Tavrizian barred any mention of
organized crime connections Tuesday, saying that ``guilt by
association is not permitted.''
   Minkow began his testimony by admitting in a halting, soft voice
that he had committed the crimes with which he is charged. He
frequently paused and cast his eyes downward as he made his
admissions.
   Asked by Kenner whether he had made false claims for his
now-defunct business, Minkow replied: ``It's true. I made those
claims and they were all lies.''
   Minkow is charged with 57 counts, including securities fraud,
credit card fraud and mail fraud. Ten of his 12 co-defendants,
including Krowpman and Padgett, pleaded guilty. Accountant Norman
Rothberg is on trial with Minkow, accused of taking a bribe to cover
up ZZZZ Best's frauds.
   The trial began in August.
</TEXT>
