<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     10-26 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKEMAH, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor's dog, Pumpkin, earned a junior
policeman's badge for scaring a fleeing suspect onto the roof of an
abandoned house and standing guard until help arrived.
   ``The police chief had some junior police badges, these stick-on
deals they give to kids,'' said Fred Amos, mayor of this central
Oklahoma town. ``He put one on top of her head and made her an
official police dog.''
   Pumpkin helped capture 19-year-old David Scott Huffman on
Tuesday, who bolted from the Okfuskee County courthouse while being
arraigned on charges of unlawful possession of a motor vehicle and
feloniously carrying a firearm, according to Sheriff Roy Nichols.
   Amos and his son heard the report of Huffman's escape over a
police scanner, and the mayor saw Huffman run into an abandoned
house.
   ``I sent my dog in ahead,'' Amos said. He said Pumpkin chased
Huffman, who was hiding in an upstairs utility room, onto the roof.
   ``He sat out there on the roof, and the dog sat there on the
ground and watched him like a squirrel in a tree,'' Amos said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAGINAW, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stubborn government computer finally
coughed up a Social Security number for 13-year-old Jeanette Wicker
after confusing her for months with her twin sister, Jeanelle.
   Tom and Millie Wicker sought Social Security numbers for the
twins, and obtained one for Jeanelle without difficulty.
   But because the girls' first names begin with the same five
letters and they share the same middle initial, the Social Security
Administration computer wouldn't acknowledge that Jeanette existed.
   Mrs. Wicker submitted five applications for Jeanette. The
situation turned serious when Wicker, a General Motors Corp.
repairman, was threatened with the loss of insurance coverage for
Jeanette unless he could produce the number.
   William T. Clynes, district manager of the Social Security office
in Saginaw, untangled the mystery after being contacted by the
Saginaw News.
   ``We had to manually input the information to get the computer to
recognize it was Jeanette, not Jeanelle, who needed a number,''
Clynes said. ``Those names are just too close in spelling.''
   Clynes apologized to the family. ``No one should have to come
down here five times,'' he said. ``Hopefully, it will never happen
again.''
</TEXT>
