<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DietFraud     10-26 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Diet Fraud,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Court Orders Diet Patch Promoters to Stop Advertising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Tuesday ordered the
promoters of EuroTrim Diet Patches to stop their national
advertisements, which feature Michael Reagan, the president's son,
the U.S. Postal Service announced.
   The order will remain in effect until the promoters can produce
scientific evidence demonstrating that the diet patches actually aid
in weight reduction, said Steve Schneringer, a postal inspector in
Pasadena, Calif.
   The Postal Inspection Service opened an investigation of EuroTrim
in August and participated in a U.S. Justice Department suit filed
Sept. 26 that alleges the diet patch is worthless.
   The principal defendants named in the suit operated Twin Star
Productions of Scottsdale, Ariz., and Ameuro Sciences International
of Thousand Oaks, Calif.
   Michael Reagan, who was not named as a defendant, said he was
nothing more than a hired actor in the promotion of the product, the
Postal Service said. Reagan was a talk show host in a 30-minute
video promotion for EuroTrim, which was released nationwide, the
Postal Service said.
   Reagan, who lives in suburban Los Angeles, did not immediately
return a telephone call Tuesday evening seeking comment.
   Promoters claim that a diet patch placed on a user's wrist emits
electrical impulses that dull the appetite.
   Dr. Ernst J. Drenick, an obesity specialist who is on the
University of California, Los Angeles faculty, testified that there
is no scientific value to EuroTrim's claims.
</TEXT>
