<DOCNO> AP881026-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0205EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     10-26 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stealth to be Rolled Out Nov. 22</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force will roll out its ``Stealth''
bomber on Nov. 22, but the first official public viewing may not
completely lift the veil from the plane.
   The Pentagon said Tuesday the B-2 bomber will be rolled out at
the government-owned plant in Palmdale, Calif., and that the plane's
first flight will likely occur soon afterward.
   Defense Department spokesman Dan Howard said, however, he
``wouldn't be a bit surprised'' if the Air Force limited the guest
list for the ceremony as well as the ``aspects'' _ or viewing angles
_ from which the new plane was viewed.
   Some aspects of the technology are still highly classified, he
indicated.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Castleberry's Recalls Hash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Castleberry's Food Co., Augusta, Ga., is
voluntarily recalling 51,985 cans of corned beef hash in six states
because 912 cans did not go through the required heat processing.
   The recall affects suspected products in Alabama, Georgia, North
Carolina, South Carolina, Michigan and New Jersey, the Agriculture
Department said Tuesday. Officials said the suspected corn beef
could contain food poisoning organisms, including some that could
cause botulism.
   The product, Castleberry's Single Serve Canned Corned Beef Hash,
is packaged in 7{-ounce cans with pull tabs and is sold mostly in
vending machines.
   The products are identified by the code numbers 2J81CBV3 or
2J81CBV4 on the bottom of the cans. The USDA inspection mark shows
Est. 195.
   Lester M. Crawford, administrator of the USDA's Food Safety and
Inspection Service said no illnesses have been reported, but that
consumers should ``avoid tasting the products and to return them
immediately to the establishment where they were purchased.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Competition Under Way for Design of Korean War Monument</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Battle Monuments Commission is
seeking proposals in a national design competition for the recently
authorized Korean War Veterans Memorial in Washington.
   Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard announced the competition on behalf
of the commission Tuesday, saying any U.S. citizen at least 18 years
of age would be eligible to submit a proposal. Interested parties
must write to the government to request rules and registration forms
and be certified as a contestant by Dec. 1.
   Once certified, each contestant will have until May 1 to submit a
design for the memorial, which is to be constructed near the Lincoln
Memorial.
   Those interested in submitting a design should write to: Korean
War Veterans Memorial Design Competition, P.O. Box 17045, Baltimore,
Md. 21203-7045.
</TEXT>
