<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Political Bags,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father, Son Team Sends Political Message Via Paper Bags</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENICIA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owners of a chain of discount stores
are sending a political message home with their customers _ on
grocery bags. Their message _``Don't Vote.''
   Ned Roscoe and his father, John, are pitching the anti-voting
message in an effort to get their customers involved in community
affairs.
   ``Don't Vote: It Only Encourages Them!'' says the Roscoes'
message in the printed blue and black text that appears on thousands
of recyclable paper sacks used in the family's 97 Food & Liquor
stores in Northern California.
   ``Voting doesn't improve a situation. Hard work does,'' says the
message, which Ned Roscoe contends is meant to encourage people to
think for themselves.
   ``When we did it, we knew the idea was going to be unpopular,''
said Roscoe, 28.
   ``We just believe in greater personal freedom.''
   The Roscoes, who began handing out the bags almost two weeks ago,
have received four complaint calls.
   Benicia is about 25 miles northeast of San Francisco.
</TEXT>
