<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0220EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen     10-26 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Gets TV Time Courtesy Of Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREAT FALLS, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' presidential campaign
plans to take the unprecedented step of buying television time for
his running mate, Lloyd Bentsen, as part of its final pre-election
push.
   The campaign has purchased a five-minute block of time on the CBS
television network on Sunday night and will probably air a spot that
Bentsen tapes late today in Los Angeles, said Tad Devine, who
coordinates Bentsen's campaign for Dukakis.
   ``We want to take full advantage of all the assets we have,''
said Devine, mentioning Bentsen's high ratings from the public,
especially when combined with the low ratings given his Republican
counterpart, Dan Quayle.
   ``The combination of the two is really very powerful,'' he said.
   Bentsen lately has been attacking the Republicans for negative
campaigning and what he calls a character assassination of Dukakis.
   ``The kind of campaign these Republicans are waging would tear
the heart out of a democracy,'' he told a rally Tuesday night in
Great Falls, Mont.
   The Republicans started right after the Democratic convention
with a smear campaign ranging from claiming Dukakis was mentally ill
to saying that his wife, Kitty, had burned the flag _ ``All
outrageous lies'' _ Bentsen said.
   Bush campaign ads saying that Dukakis would weaken the U.S.
military were untrue, he said, as was their claim that Dukakis
planned to take guns away from sportsmen.
   Bentsen has been receiving enthusiastic responses from the crowds
where he speaks. More than a thousand people packed the courtyard
Tuesday night rally in a casino hotel in Great Falls and cheered
wildly as Bentsen spoke in front of an enormous American flag and
all of the state's top elected Democrats.
   But in the national news he has been working in the shadows of
the two presidential candidates, said his press secretary, Mike
McCurry.
   Increased television exposure, including a planned appearance on
the ``CBS Evening News'' tonight and the paid time on Sunday night,
could help deliver that message to more of the electorate, he said.
   ``I think he wants to say something about the campaign and the
quality of the campaign,'' McCurry said. ``I think there will be a
concentrated effort to make people aware of the broadcast,''
including some paid advertising, he said.
   Never before has a campaign bought network time for its vice
presidential candidate and less than a week ago the campaign was
leaning against such a move, Devine said. But the plan fit in with
the overall effort by Dukakis to seek maximum exposure in the final
two weeks of the campaign, he said, noting that Dukakis' own
television schedule was heavier than Bentsen's.
   Bentsen stumped through the Dakotas and into Montana on Tuesday.
The states have only 10 electoral votes between them. But the
Democrats contend they have a good shot at South Dakota and Montana
especially, and those states could make the difference in a close
election.
   From states with the fewest electoral votes, Bentsen was flying
today to California, which at 47 has the most clout in the Electoral
College.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881026-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0142EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland     10-26 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government-Opposition Talks in Doubt Over Participation of
Activists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist authorities insisted on yet
another preliminary meeting with Lech Walesa before round-table
talks with the opposition can begin, but the Solidarity chairman
refused.
   The dispute arose Tuesday when the government said it wanted to
discuss its objection to two Solidarity delegates to the talks,
which authorities agreed to in August in return for an end to
Poland's worst labor unrest in seven years.
   Walesa said in a telephone interview that he would not agree to
the government's demand that he meet today with Interior Minister
Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak on the matter.
   ``I will not allow any personnel changes,'' he said. ''It could
be a precedent, a dangerous precedent for the future.''
   A statement issued later by Solidarity national spokesman Janusz
Onyskiewicz ruled out any change in the banned free trade union
movement's delegation but expressed hope that the long-awaited talks
could begin.
   Poland's planned economy is in crisis, with wages lagging far
behind consumer prices, which the government raised by an average of
40 percent earlier this year.
   A communique issued by the official PAP news agency after the
ruling Politburo's weekly meeting Tuesday said the government was
firmly committed to the talks and expressed hope that ``remaining
controversies will be quickly removed in the course of preparatory
talks.''
   The squabble began when government spokesman Jerzy Urban said a
fourth preparatory meeting between Walesa and Kiszczak was
``indispensible'' for the talks to begin.
   The government objects to two people proposed by Solidarity to
participate and wants clarification on whether the two _ advisors
Jacek Kuron and Adam Michnik _ agree to accept the leading role of
the communist party, Urban said.
   He said Walesa and Kiszczak should meet today, and if they
settled their differences the talks could begin Friday.
   Urban charged that Solidarity's ``stubbornness'' was preventing
the talks from beginning, but said the Friday date did not represent
an ultimatum and the government would be willing to meet later,
assuming questions about participation and other technical matters
were resolved.
   Walesa said he had not given up hope for the talks to bring about
``understanding and the implementation of pluralism,'' but he said
another meeting with Kiszczak was unnecessary.
   Urban said the government has problems with the participation of
Kuron and Michnik because the two don't respect Poland's
constitutional order, which guarantees the communist party's leading
role.
   ``If Jacek Kuron and Adam Michnik really wish to participate in
the conciliation process, it would be no problem for them to
publicly declare that they respect and will respect the
constitutional order,'' he said.
   Kuron declined comment. A telephone call to Michnik's home went
unanswered.
   In a first meeting with Kiszczak on Aug. 31, Walesa agreed to
bring a halt to a wave of strikes after being guaranteed that the
talks would address the reinstatement of Solidarity, the only
independent labor movement ever allowed in the Soviet bloc.
   The opposition has demanded that the talks lead to the
legalization of Solidarity, which was outlawed after a December 1981
military crackdown.
   But Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski said Friday he opposes
such a move until the economy is healthier and changes in the system
allow political demands to be vented outside of trade unions.
   The government said Monday a specially built round table capable
of seating more than 50 people had been set up at its Jablonna
Palace in suburban Warsaw in readiness for the talks.
   Invited to attend the talks in addition to Solidarity are
representatives of the powerful Roman Catholic Church, official
trade unions and government-approved social groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881026-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0151EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Salvador-Rights     10-26 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Rights,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amnesty: Death Squad Assassinations Up Sharply Last Two Years In
Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The revival of death squads in El Salvador has
resulted in the assassination of hundreds of suspected government
opponents during the past two years, Amnesty International said
today.
   The re-emergence of death squads, usually made up of troops and
police, coincides with the armed forces' open opposition to the
policies of President Jose Napoleon Duarte, the London-based human
rights organization charged.
   Members of the clandestine death squads customarily wear plain
clothes, use unmarked trucks or vans with tinted windows, and often
dump mutilated victims on the roadside ``as a means of terrifying
the population,'' it said in a report.
   Some victims are shot from passing cars in daylight in front of
witnesses, while others are seized from their homes or in the street
and ``never heard of again'' or turn up in notorious ``body dumps,''
the report said.
   The death-squad killings ``are routinely carried out by regular
units of the armed forces which include the military and the
security services, and by special intelligence units that
incorporate civilian gunmen under their supervision and control,''
it said.
   Since early 1987, victims have included trade unionists, human
rights workers, returned refugees and members of the judiciary
attempting to establish responsibility for human rights violations,
the report said.
   Abductions and attacks have often occurred near police or
military installations ``or under the gaze of uniformed security
personnel who made no effort to intervene,'' it said.
   The squads intimidate opponents by publishing ``death lists'' in
newspaper advertisements and delivering coffins to the homes of
intended victims, the report said.
   Dumped bodies frequently are found decapitated, dismembered,
strangled or showing marks of rape or torture, such as burns and
machete wounds, it said.
   Military authorities abducted and summarily executed tens of
thousands of suspected leftists in the late 1970s and early 1980s,
but the killings dropped off sharply after Duarte's U.S.-backed
civilian administration came to power in 1984, the report said.
   The government says the killings are the work of extremists who
act independently and cannot be apprehended, but Amnesty
International's report said ``evidence gathered over many years from
a wide range of sources points to security force responsibility.''
   A lava bed 12 miles north of El Salvador called El Playon, where
skeletons of bodies devoured by birds of prey were common in the
early 1980s, fell into disuse until an unidentified body was found
there in January, the report said.
   Bodies also are again being dumped at a site known as the Devil's
Doorway at Panchimalco, 12 miles southeast of the capital, the
report said.
   In 1987, an average of 12 bodies a month ``showing death
squad-style mutilations'' were found dumped along roadsides, it said.
   It said Tutela Legal, a Roman Catholic human rights group in San
Salvador, estimates as many death squad-style disappearances and
killings occurred in the first quarter of this year as in all of
1987.
   Amnesty International gave no estimate of the number of
death-squad killings over the last six months.
   Other deliberate killings have been falsely ascribed by armed
forces' spokesmen to clashes with opposition forces, the report said.
   Amnesty International said renewed death-squad killings ``have
occurred as the armed forces high command has expressed open
opposition'' to Duarte's policies, including his negotiations with
leftist guerrillas.
   The assassination a year ago of Herbert Anaya Sanabria, president
of the Salvadoran Human Rights Commission, ``was widely interpreted
as an attempt to hamper these negotiations,'' the report said.
   It said reports this summer that Duarte is terminally ill with
cancer have been ``another factor affording the armed forces even
greater control over counter-insurgency policies.''
   The 9-year civil war has killed an estimated 65,000 people, most
of them civilians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
