<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WrittenSentence     10-26 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Written Sentence,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Man to Write In Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man who hit a police officer was
ordered jailed for a year and has to write a sentence as part of his
sentence: ``People do not have to put up with a jerk like me.'' One
hundred times a day for each day behind bars.
   As part the sentence for 19-year-old Steven R. Sommer, Circuit
Judge Michael Hoover stayed a 3{-year prison term and placed him on
five years' probation.
   ``It just seemed to me at the time that if I put this kid in
prison, he was going to come out one tough case,'' Hoover explained
in an interview Tuesday.
   The judge said Sommer's self-image may change if ``he has to
suffer the humiliation of being treated like a miscreant junior high
schooler'' by having to write the sentence a total of 36,500 times.
   Sommer, who kicked out a squad car window and was subdued by four
officers after being stopped for a traffic violation, pleaded guilty
last month to a felony battery charge.
   Hoover noted during Monday's sentencing that Sommer had shown no
remorse. He said he believed prison would offer little chance of
rehabilitation for someone who would probably tell fellow inmates he
had been convicted of ``beating up a cop.''
   ``My basic concern was not to reinforce the image he had of being
a tough you-know-what that people had to put up with or suffer the
consequences,'' the judge said Tuesday.
   Sommer was stopped Jan. 31 by Roger Watral, Marathon assistant
police chief, for speeding. Watral testified during a preliminary
hearing that Sommer became upset and used vulgar language when the
officer told him he was speeding.
   The officer said he smelled alcohol on Sommer's breath and later
saw a can of beer in the car.
   Sommer refused three times to do what the officer asked him to do
and ``made a mockery out of the field sobriety test,'' Watral
testified.
   When the officer tried to put handcuffs on the 6-foot-tall
Sommer, the man jerked his arm back, hitting the officer across the
lower lip, and kicked him in the groin, Watral said.
   Three other officers had to be called in to subdue Sommer,
authorities said.
   Sommer pleaded guilty to battery in exchange for the state
dropping charges of resisting arrest and causing criminal damage to
property. He was also cited for drunken driving as a third-time
offender and fined $1,331.
</TEXT>
