<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Malaysia-Deaths     10-26 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Malaysia-Deaths,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Villagers Pray To Ward Off Spirits They Believe Killed Kids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 3,000 villagers in northern
Malaysia prayed together to seek protection from the evil spirits
they believe caused the mysterious deaths of 13 children this month,
a newspaper reported today.
   Villagers hung pamelo leaves and lemon grass on their front doors
to ward off the evil spirits they believe also caused 50 other
children to be hospitalized, the Star daily reported from Baru
Timah, about 120 miles north of Kuala Lumpur.
   They also lit three giant incense sticks and offered food as they
chanted prayers at the village marketplace.
   The mysterious ailment surfaced Oct. 15, and the government has
launched a probe to determine what is afflicting the children. Four
medical experts from Singapore flew to Malaysia Tuesday to help in
the investigation.
   The children vomited blood and experienced diarrhea and fever,
and may have been hit with food poisoning, said Martin Joseph, a
physician with Ipoh Government Hospital, where most of the deaths
occurred.
   Seventeen noodle factories in the area have been ordered closed
because many of those stricken had eaten noodles. People in the area
have switched to bread, the paper said.
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad visited nine children who remain
hospitalized Monday and said the government was doing its best to
determine the cause of the deaths.
</TEXT>
