<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0315EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PumpkinRipper     10-26 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pumpkin Ripper,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slasher Destroys Huge Pumpkin; Reward Offered For Seeds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANNOCKBURN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reward is being offered for the great
pumpkin slasher, a vandal who destroyed what was billed as the
Midwest's largest gourd and took its valuable seeds, authorities
said.
   The pre-Halloween prank has dumbfounded residents of this upscale
suburb north of Chicago, where the 354-pound pumpkin was on display
at the posh Bannockburn Green Retail Center.
   The slasher cut the pumpkin and made off with half of it and all
the seeds.
   ``Someone did a very clean job of it,'' Enid Pesmen, property
manager of the center, said Tuesday.
   She bought the pumpkin for $200 from a grower in Nekoosa, Wis.,
to use as a Halloween promotion at the center. It was to replace the
center's annual pumpkin giveaway, canceled this year because of the
drought, said center spokeswoman Susan Hill.
   The grower, Gary Keyzer, won the Midwest Pumpkin Weigh-Off
contest earlier this month with the mammoth pumpkin, and agreed to
part with it if the seeds were returned to him, Ms. Hill said.
   The center had planned to keep the pumpkin on display outdoors
until Halloween, then offer it to bakeries to make pies for the
hungry, Ms. Hill said.
   But during the weekend, the slasher struck. Workmen found the
remains of the pumpkin Saturday night.
   Mrs. Pesmen said she has no idea who might have pulled such a
stunt.
   ``I assume they really wanted the seeds,'' she said.
   She has offered a reward of about $100 for return of the seeds,
but has little hope of finding the thief.
   ``I don't know how we're going to find someone with half a
pumpkin and seeds,'' she said.
   The mystery may not be identified until next growing season, if a
patch of giant pumpkins crops up in Bannockburn.
   ``That's what we're going to be on the look-out for,'' Ms. Pesmen
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
