<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Inches Down Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar inched down against the Japanese yen
Wednesday, while share prices rose on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 126.80 yen, down 0.07 yen from Tuesday's
close of 126.87 yen. Opening at 126.67 yen, the currency moved
between 126.64-126.85 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
139.95 points Tuesday, gained another 199.11 points, or 0.73
percent, to close at 27,620.60.
   The market's main index was up 99.51 points shortly after trading
began and continued to rise throughout the morning session.
   The positive environment for stock investment, including
prospects for lower interest rates and declining oil prices,
outweighed investors' concerns over negative factors such as the
Recruit stock scandal, a Daiwa Securities trader said.
   Recruit Corp., an information-related conglomerate, is at the
center of a political scandal involving a subsidiary's offering of
unlisted shares at bargain prices to senior Japanese politicians and
other figures.
</TEXT>
