<DOCNO> AP881026-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Guard     10-26 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Guard,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Loses Appeal Challenging Federal Authority Over National
Guard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has rejected Democratic
presidential candidate Michael Dukakis' attempt to use his power as
governor to block a Massachusetts National Guard training mission in
Central America.
   The 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals issued a one-sentence order
Tuesday affirming a May 6 decision by U.S. District Judge Robert
Keeton, who upheld federal supremacy over the National Guard.
   ``Having examined the briefs of the parties ... and having had
the benefit of oral argument, we affirm the judgment on the basis
stated in the district court's well-reasoned opinion,'' the appeals
court said.
   Dukakis sued in January to block the assignment of 13 public
relations specialists in the Massachusetts Guard to Honduras and
Panama for two weeks in May because of his opposition to Reagan
administration policies in the region.
   In his presidential campaign, Dukakis has denounced the
administration for its ``failed and illegal'' policy of supporting
Nicaraguan rebels, and he said sending Guard troops to the region
was an attempt to intimidate Nicaragua.
   Dukakis, who was campaigning Tuesday in California and Colorado,
had no immediate comment on the appellate decision. A press aide,
Steven Crawford, said the governor was disappointed that the court
chose not to uphold the ``important principle'' of state authority.
   State Attorney General James Shannon, who represented Dukakis in
court, said he would wait until another federal appeals court rules
in a similar challenge before deciding whether to appeal to the U.S.
Supreme Court.
   John Bolton, chief of the civil division in the U.S. Justice
Department, said he was pleased by the ruling: ``It represents the
complete vindication of the administration's position.''
   After Keeton issued his ruling in May, Dukakis appealed but did
not try to stop the Massachusetts troops from participating in the
exercises, which involved road-building.
   In his decision, Keeton explicitly upheld the constitutionality
of the Montgomery Amendment, a 1986 act of Congress that says
governors may not decline such assignments ``because of any
objection to the location, purpose, type or schedule of such
activity.''
   ``At issue in this case is the constitutional status of the
modern National Guard,'' Keeton wrote, framing his question in terms
of competing clauses in the U.S. Constitution that divided control
over the new nation's militia between the federal government and the
states.
   Lawyers for the U.S. Justice Department argued that the ``Army
Clause'' in the Constitution gives Congress the ultimate say over
the nation's entire military apparatus. They described Dukakis'
position as ``a dagger aimed at the heart of national defense.''
   The Massachusetts' attorney general's office, representing
Dukakis, had claimed that the ``Militia Clause'' reserved power to
the governors over training the militia.
   Assistant Attorney General Douglas Wilkins stressed the
``original intent'' of the Constitution's framers, arguing that
state control over the ``militia'' was essentially undisturbed by
the many reorganizations of the nation's military.
   Minnesota Gov. Rudy Perpich, joined by Massachusetts and nine
other states, challenged the law last year in U.S. District Court in
St. Paul and lost. The case is now on appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881026-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0411EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Nancy     10-26 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Nancy,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Lady Calls For Punishment of Wall Street Bankers Who Use
Cocaine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Reagan has called for an all-out
domestic war on drug users, saying Wall Street bankers who use
cocaine should be punished along with dealers, smugglers and
Colombian drug kingpins.
   America _ not foreign drug producers _ bears responsibility for
its narcotics problem, the First Lady said in a speech Tuesday at
the United Nations.
   Each American drug user, she said, ``is an accomplice to every
criminal act, every murder, every terrorist attack carried out by
the narcotics syndicates.''
   ``To get serious about stopping illegal drugs,'' Mrs. Reagan
said, ``that means confronting all those citizens who use drugs.''
If the United States cannot choke off the demand for drugs, she
said, there is little hope of halting production and smuggling.
   ``It is often easier to make strong speeches about foreign drug
lords or drug smugglers,'' she said, ``than to arrest a pair of Wall
Street investment bankers buying cocaine on their lunch break.''
   Mrs. Reagan made the comments in a speech to the U.N. Third
Committee on Social and Humanitarian Affairs. In 1985, she and other
first ladies addressed an international conference against drug
abuse at the United Nations when she sounded her anti-drug slogan:
``Just Say No.''
   In his eight years in office, President Reagan has advocated a
war on drug producers in Latin America and elsewhere, as well as the
interdiction of drugs smuggled into the United States.
   But the U.S. administration has been criticized for its dealings
with Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel Noriega, indicted in the
United States for drug trafficking, and for not cracking down on
governments that allow domestic drug production.
   In her speech, Mrs. Reagan emphasized the need for police to
arrest and for courts to punish all drug users. It is as important
to stop drug use in the United States, she said, as it is to stop
coca-growing in Peru, processing in Colombia and shipping through
the Caribbean.
   ``It is the United States alone which bears responsibility for
its own drug problem,'' she said. ``While most of the illegal drugs
are imported, the drug users are home-grown.''
   ``If we lack the will to fully mobilize the forces of law in our
own country to arrest and punish drug users, if we cannot stem the
American demand for drugs,'' Mrs. Reagan said, ``Then there will be
little hope of preventing foreign drug producers from fulfilling
that demand.''
</TEXT>
