<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0425EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AnneFrankAuction     10-26 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Anne Frank Auction,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anne Frank Letters Sold At Auction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH J. HARPAZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two women who were pen pals with Anne Frank and
her sister have sold the correspondence at auction for $150,000 and
plan to use the money to retire and to fund an organization for
Christian missionaries.
   The anonymous buyer, who also paid a 10 percent fee to the
auction house, will give the letters to the Simon Wiesenthal Center
in Los Angeles, according to The New York Times.
   The women had hoped the buyer would put the letters, which are in
English, in a setting where they can be viewed publicly.
   ``We enjoyed them for 48 years, and we're just hoping that maybe
the world will get to see them,'' said Betty Ann Wagner.
   Miss Wagner and her sister Juanita wrote to Anne and her sister,
Margot, in 1940 at the suggestion of a teacher in their
then-hometown of Danville, Iowa. At the time, Anne and Juanita were
11; Margot and Betty Ann were 15.
   Anne and Margot sent back two photographs, a postcard and two
letters describing their life in Amsterdam, Holland. Margot wrote
that ``having a frontier with Germany and being a small country we
never feel safe.''
   The Wagners wrote back, but never heard from the Franks again.
   A month after the letters were sent, Germany invaded the
Netherlands. The Franks, who were Jewish, went into hiding in the
attic of a house in Amsterdam but were later discovered and sent to
concentration camps. Anne's diary, published in 1952, carries a
poignant account of their life in hiding.
   ``We'd worried about her during the war, but never dreamed she
was suffering,'' said Miss Wagner, reached at her home in the Los
Angeles area.
   She added that she and her sister, who also lives in California,
hope to visit the house in Amsterdam where the Franks hid.
   After the war, the Wagners wrote to the Franks again. Anne's
father replied to say that he was the only one in his family to
survive the war.
   Rhonda Barad, director of the Wiesenthal center's eastern region,
said the letters would be exhibited at a new museum in Los Angeles
when it is completed next year.
   ``We wanted the letters,'' said Barad, whose organization is
named for the famed Nazi hunter. ``The focus of the center is to
teach tolerance and that's what Anne Frank's diary and her life
represent.''
   Miss Wagner said she plans to donate part of the money from the
sale to Wayfarer Ministries, a non-profit organization she founded
nine years ago to help Christian missionaries around the world.
   The auction house, Swann Galleries, had predicted that bidding
would exceed $30,000 but could not estimate how high it would go
because nothing written by Anne Frank had ever been auctioned before.
   Among the bidders was actress Whoopi Goldberg, one of hundreds
who participated in the auction by telephone.
   Also sold at the auction were several Marilyn Monroe autographs,
including her certificate of conversion to Judaism, which took place
just before her marriage to playwright Arthur Miller. The
certificate was bought by a private collector for $7,000, said Will
Bennett, a Swann spokesman.
   A handwritten letter of condolence from Emily Dickinson to the
husband of a friend who died was on the auction block as well,
bringing $8,000 from a dealer.
   Seventy-six pages of handwritten notes by Thomas Edison brought
$32,000. Edison compiled the manuscript, which concerns his travels,
jobs and inventions, for use by his official biographers, Bennett
said.
   A collection of correspondence from Greta Garbo was bought by a
collector for $9,500, Bennett said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881026-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0435EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Steinberg     10-26 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinberg,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opening Arguments Delivered in Lisa Steinberg Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A once-respected defense lawyer committed
``depraved murder'' by beating his illegally adopted 6-year-old
daughter and doing nothing to save her life, a prosecutor said in
the attorney's murder trial.
   Assistant District Attorney Peter Casolaro made the opening
statement Tuesday as Lisa Steinberg's biological mother, Michele
Launders, sobbed in the courtroom's front row.
   The girl's death nearly a year ago drew national attention and
made her a symbol of the plight of abused children.
   ``As Lisa Steinberg lay unconscious, the defendant did absolutely
nothing,'' Casolaro said, adding evidence showed prompt medical care
would have saved the child's life.
   Joel Steinberg's ``failure to act constituted depraved murder,''
Casolaro said.
   Steinberg, 47, is charged with second-degree murder in the death
of the child he took illegally at birth from Ms. Launders, then an
unmarried Long Island teen-ager. He has denied ever hitting Lisa.
   Casolaro said ``graphic and grotesque'' evidence and testimony
would prove Steinberg murdered Lisa, who was found unconscious at
the Steinberg apartment in Greenwich Village early Nov. 2, and died
three days later.
   The first-grader had bruises on her chest, legs, arms and neck,
and head injuries caused by ``blunt-force trauma'' when she arrived
at the hospital, Casolaro told the state jury. Police officers
noticed Steinberg's bleeding knuckles, he said.
   Steinberg's attorney, Ira London, said in his opening that the
evidence would not support a murder charge and called on the jury to
acquit his client.
   ``It will not be proven in this case that Lisa Steinberg was
murdered, nor will it be proven that Lisa was a battered child,''
London said. ``Lisa was neither sullen or withdrawn. She was a
vital, active and engaging child until her death.''
   Steinberg has said Lisa became sick the night of Nov. 1 after
eating and that the bruises on her back and chest resulted from his
efforts to revive her after she fell unconscious.
   No help was called for Lisa until after 6:30 a.m. on Nov. 2,
court records show.
   London on Tuesday attacked Hedda Nussbaum, Steinberg's longtime
live-in companion, who Judge Harold Rothwax called ``the single most
important witness in this case.''
   Ms. Nussbaum has an agreement with the district attorney's office
to testify, although she has told prosecutors she did not see
Steinberg strike Lisa the day she fell unconscious.
   Ms. Nussbaum was charged in Lisa's death, but was never indicted
and the charges will probably be dropped, the district attorney's
office said. After her arrest, she underwent surgery and psychiatric
treatment for injuries allegedly inflicted by Steinberg.
   London called Ms. Nussbaum ``delusional'' and pointed out that
she had spent the last year in a mental hospital.
   ``Undoubtedly, you will hear witnesses refer to Hedda's
self-destructive romance with satanic cults, her sadomasochistic
behavior outside the home and her involvement with pornography,''
London said.
   Casolaro painted Ms. Nussbaum as another victim of Steinberg.
   ``He exploited her weakness of mind and her emotional problems,''
the prosecutor said. ``The defendant beat and broke Miss Nussbaum
until she had become nothing more than his willing servant.''
   One of the trial's first witnesses, paramedic John Filangeri,
testified that Ms. Nussbaum was in such bad shape the night of the
death she appeared to be ``70 to 80 years of age.'' Ms. Nussbaum is
46.
   Police Officer James Botte, the first person to arrive at the
apartment and see the unconscious girl, testified the home was
dirty, unkempt and dark when he arrived.
   A 16-month-old boy, Mitchell, was found in the apartment sitting
in a dirty diaper and tethered to a playpen, authorities have said.
The boy was also illegally adopted, and now lives with his
biological mother.
   The trial is to resume Thursday.
</TEXT>
