<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Freeman     10-26 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Freeman,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Best-Selling Novelist Cynthia Freeman Dies at 73</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Best-selling novelist Cynthia Freeman, who
wrote her first book when she was 50 and went on to write eight
other romances that have been translated into 33 languages, has
died. She was 73.
   The former interior decorator, whose full name was Beatrice
Cynthia Freeman Feinberg, died of cancer Saturday at the University
of California Medical Center.
   Freeman published ``A World Full of Strangers'' in 1975, an
instant best seller about a family of Jewish immigrants in her
hometown of San Francisco.
   Her eight other romance novels, which include ``Fairytales,''
``The Days of Winter,'' ``Portraits,'' ``Come Pour the Wine,'' and
``Seasons of the Heart,'' have sold more than 20 million copies.
   Freeman, who dropped out of school in the sixth grade and was
taught by her immigrant parents, audited classes at the University
of California, Berkeley.
   ``I didn't register but I took every course I wanted and I got a
very liberal education for free,'' she said.
   Freeman married Dr. Herman Feinberg when she was 18. He died in
1982.
   Her most often-quoted saying was, ``I say, `Don't worry about
life after death: worry about life after breakfast.'''
   Survivors include a son, Sheldon Feinberg of Danville and her
father, Albert C. Freeman of Atherton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
