<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms, Hail Pound Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Intense thunderstorms, hail and damaging winds pounded
north-central and northeast Texas today, and snow fell on parts of
the Great Lakes region.
   Wind blew the roof off of a home near Newcastle, Texas, and tore
down tree limbs at Woodson, Texas. Hail as big as softballs fell in
north-central and northeast Texas.
   The thunderstorms extended eastward into southwest Arkansas and
northern Louisiana. Thunderstorms also developed over south-central
Oklahoma.
   Cold westerly winds flowing across the warm waters of lakes
Ontario and Erie produced lake-effect snow along their eastern
shorelines. A snow advisory was posted for the east lakeshore
counties of Ohio, and a lake snow advisory was in effect for New
York counties east of both the lakes.
   Lake-effect snow also fell over parts of upper Michigan, and
light snow dusted southeast lower Michigan.
   A cold front pushing through the Pacific Northwest generated
light rain and fog in parts of Washington state.
   Fog also shrouded the Pacific Coast from Southern California to
Washington. A dense fog advisory was in effect for parts of the
Northern California coast.
   Today's forecast called for continued scattered rain and snow
showers in the Great Lakes region, the upper Ohio Valley and
northern New England; showers and thunderstorms over east Texas and
the lower Mississippi Valley; rain showers over the northern Rockies
and the Pacific Northwest, with rain heaviest over north-central
Montana; and fair to partly sunny skies elsewhere.
   Highs were predicted in the 30s over upper Michigan and northeast
Minnesota; the 40s and 50s from Washington state to northern
Montana, and from the northern Plains and upper Mississippi Valley
to the Great Lakes, the Ohio Valley, and the middle and northern
Atlantic Coast states; the 80s over southern and central Florida and
the southern half of Texas; 80 to 95 degrees in the desert Southwest
and inland valleys of California; and the 60s and 70s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 16
degrees at Grand Forks, N.D., to 78 degrees at Corpus Christi,
Texas, Naval Air Station.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 55 fair; Boston 41 fair; Buffalo 36 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 50 fair; Cincinnati 28 fair; Cleveland 36 partly
cloudy; Detroit 35 cloudy; Miami 71 fair; New York 40 partly cloudy;
Philadelphia 41 fair; Pittsburgh 36 cloudy; Portland, Maine 38 fair;
Washington 43 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 19 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 69 cloudy; Denver
41 fair; Des Moines 31 fair; Indianapolis 28 fair; Kansas City 37
fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 26 fair; Nashville 47 cloudy; New Orleans
58 fair; St. Louis 41 partly cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 56 fair; Anchorage 23 partly cloudy; Las Vegas
60 fair; Los Angeles 61 hazy; Phoenix 75 fair; Salt Lake City 45
fair; San Diego 63 cloudy; San Francisco 53 cloudy; Seattle 50 foggy.
   _Canada: Montreal 41 cloudy; Toronto 37 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
