<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SaudiAssassinated     10-26 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Saudi Assassinated,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saudi Arabian Diplomat Assassinated In Front Of Ankara Apartment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lower-ranking diplomat at Saudi Arabia's
embassy was assassinated on the steps of his apartment building,
Ankara Gov. Saffet Arikan Beduk said today.
   Beduk said Abdulgani Bedawi was shot to death by unknown gunmen
Tuesday night in front of his apartment building in affluent Cankaya
district. Bedawi, who was returning from the office, died instantly
from shots to the head and chest, Beduk said.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility.
   Saudi Arabian Ambassador Abdulaziz Khojah said the ``killing
could not possibly be a result of personal conflict or for
burglary.'' He said, however, that the embassy had received more
than 100 threatening letters written in Turkish during the spring
holy pilgrimage season.
   ``I don't believe the Turks have anything to do with the incident
even though the letters were in Turkish,'' Khojah said without
elaborating.
   Saudi Arabia restricted the number of Moslems who could visit the
country during the pilgrimage season this year according to each
Moslem nation's population.
   The decision was taken as a security measure after last year's
riot by Iranians during the pilgrimage to Mecca that claimed the
lives of more than 400 Iranians.
   Saudi Arabia broke diplomatic ties with Iran in April. The Saudi
government then announced that the decision had several reasons,
among them the clash in Mecca and a subsequent attack on the Saudi
embassy in Tehran.
   Khojah said Bedawi worked as a telex operator in the embassy. The
envoy confirmed that he was working under diplomatic status, with
the title of second secretary. Bedawi had been appointed to his job
six years ago.
</TEXT>
