<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSGloves     10-26 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Gloves,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Despite Leaky Gloves, AIDS Infection Unlikely Through Skin Contact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors and nurses face a one-in-a-thousand
risk of catching AIDS when they get infected blood or other body
fluids on their skin, even though gloves they wear for protection
often leak, studies found.
   ``Gloves have been leaking for years, we've been wearing them and
we haven't found a lot of infections in hospital employees'' exposed
to AIDS, hepatitis B and other viruses, said Jane
DeGroot-Kosolcharoen, an infection control nurse at Middleton
Memorial Veterans Hospital in Madison, Wis.
   Three studies conducted by DeGroot-Kosolcharoen and researchers
in Massachusetts and Florida found leakage in more than half of some
of the brands of gloves tested. One study was conducted as an
eighth-grade science project by a student whose father is an
infectious disease expert.
   The studies found wide variations in leakage rates for various
brands of latex and vinyl gloves, but tended to show sterile
surgical gloves less leak-prone than non-sterile examination gloves,
and latex less leak-prone than vinyl.
   A fourth study concluded blood, sputum, urine and other body
fluids of AIDS patients gets on the skin of health care workers
``far too frequently,'' with about one-quarter of a group of 770
hospital employees getting AIDS-tainted liquids on their skin.
   But the chance of one such exposure infecting a person with the
virus for acquired immune deficiency syndrome is no more than 1.1 in
1,000, said Barbara Fahey, an infection control specialist who
performed the study at the National Institutes of Health Clinical
Center in Bethesda, Md.
   A related study by NIH epidemiologist David Henderson found
health care workers face a one in 250 chance of catching AIDS from a
single instance of being jabbed by a contaminated needle, and a one
in 300 chance of being infected if virus-tainted liquid comes in
contact with their mucous membranes.
   ``There really is a risk we all have to swallow. It's a bitter
pill,'' Henderson said Tuesday during the 28th Interscience
Conference on Antimicrobial Agents and Chemotherapy.
   However, the NIH studies showed health care workers got
AIDS-tainted fluids on their skin far more often than they contacted
such liquids through their mucous membranes or needle injuries.
   Researchers at the conference said hospital workers should check
gloves for holes before using them, then wash their hands after
removing gloves.
   DeGroot-Kosolcharoen said recommendations for health care workers
to wear gloves to protect themselves from AIDS and other viruses
caused a nationwide glove shortage and that ``manufacturers have had
difficulty supplying enough gloves without compromising quality.''
   She performed water-leak tests on 2,400 gloves from 24 brands of
gloves. In a second test, the gloves were donned by researchers and
dipped in blood they donated.
   Of the 24 brands, only four didn't leak at all. They were sterile
latex gloves. Up to 52 percent of gloves in some brands leaked,
DeGroot-Kosolcharoen said.
   Average leak rates for water and blood, respectively, were 1.1
percent and 1.1 percent for sterile latex, 9 percent and 9.5 percent
for sterile vinyl, 14 percent and 9 percent for non-sterile latex,
and _ most leaky _ 17.7 percent and 10.3 percent for non-sterile
vinyl.
   University of Massachusetts Medical Center infection control
research director Helen Rosen Kotilainen tested 1,200 vinyl and
1,750 latex non-sterile examination gloves from seven brands.
   Water-leak rates for ranged from 4 percent to 28 percent for
vinyl brands and from 0 percent to 6 percent for latex brands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881026-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0700EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Algeria     10-26 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Algeria,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Will Not Allow Rival Political Groups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Chadli Benjedid has rejected
transition to a multi-party democracy as part of political reforms
announced after bloody riots earlier this month.
   In a communique issued by his office Monday night, Benjedid said
the ruling party, the National Liberation Front, would become more
democratic and party officials would be made more accountable to the
rank and file.
   The communique said the party had to ``listen more atentively to
the people to understand their concerns''
   The unrest, spurred by Algeria's economic crisis, began with
demonstrators protesting food shortages and rising prices.
   The party, which has ruled the country since independence from
France in 1962, was already unpopular and has been silent since the
disturbances, which left 159 people dead and 154 injured, according
to official figures.
   Unofficial estimates at the time put the number of dead at 400 or
more.
   The communique said, ``a multi-system cannot be established with
groups who seek power and privileges under the facade of democracy.''
   However, the communique said, rejuvenation of the ruling party
does not exclude the possibility that eventually there could be a
pluralistic system.
   It said there will be elections to most party posts and
non-members could run for election to popular assemblies.
   The measures are to be put before a party congress in December
and then to a referendum next year.
   In another referendum next week, Algerians will vote on a plan to
make the prime minister answerable to the National Assembly.
</TEXT>
