<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MarcosArraignment     10-26 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos Arraignment,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcos Lawyers Ask For Honolulu Arraignment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for Ferdinand Marcos cited his ailing
health in asking officials to move the deposed Philippine
president's arraignment on federal racketeering charges from New
York to Honolulu, a Marcos attorney says.
   Marcos and his wife, Imelda, were indicted Friday on charges they
plundered more than $100 million from their homeland to buy real
estate and other properties in New York. They are to be arraigned
Monday in New York.
   John Bartko, Marcos' San Francisco-based attorney, said attorneys
sought the Honolulu arraignment because of the 71-year-old Marcos'
poor health and the simplicity of the proceeding.
   ``Basically, all they are required to do is show up and enter a
plea, which in this case, of course, would be not guilty,'' said
Bartko. ``Considering Mr. Marcos' poor health and the fact that it
would be a very long trip and require numerous medical personnel, we
hope to have the site changed.''
   Marcos has been treated for a variety of illnesses during his
exile in Hawaii, including chest pains and an eye ailment. He and
his wife, Imelda, fled to Honolulu in February 1986 after a
civilian-military revolt ended his 20-year rule.
   Bartko said he hoped to know by Thursday or Friday whether the
change would be granted.
   U.S. officials here said the Marcoses would incur all costs of
the trip and that they did not require federal law enforcement
escorts.
</TEXT>
