<2ND_LINE>PM-Name-Calling,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Challenger Promises to Stop Name-Calling in Oregon Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCIO, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A candidate for secretary of state said there
would be no more name-calling in his campaign one day after calling
his opponent a ``fairy queen.''
   John Sheppard said his comment about Oregon Secretary of State
Barbara Roberts at a news conference was aimed at her opposition to
a ballot issue but was misunderstood.
   The measure would repeal Gov. Neil Goldschmidt's executive order
barring state agenices from discrimination based on sexual
preference. Repeal supporters say Goldschmidt's order grants
homosexuals special protection, even though it also applies to
heterosexuals.
   Sheppard had called Goldschmidt a ``bozo'' for issuing the order,
and said Monday that if ``Goldschmidt is the chief bozo, Barbara
Roberts can be crowned the fairy queen.''
   On Tuesday, Sheppard promised, ``You won't see any of that
again.''
   Sheppard, a Republican, said the comment was ``not the choice of
words I would have used,'' claiming he was reading from a news
release written by his campaign manager. Sheppard, however, declined
to apologize for the remark.
   Roberts, a Democrat, said Sheppard's comment represented a ``new
low'' in Oregon political campaigns.
