<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru a0538 10-26 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0538,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Papers Publish Letter to Anderson</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to clarify, say Anderson is not known to
read Arabic. Picks up 6th graf pvs ``The newspapers also...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanese newspapers today published a
letter from a committee of journalists marking the 41st birthday of
American hostage Terry Anderson.
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, is the longest-held of the 14 foreign hostages held in
Lebanon. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   The journalist, held by a pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem faction
calling itself Islamic Jihad, or Holy War, turns 41 on Thursday.
   ``Your colleagues in the United States and throughout the world
salute you today on your birthday,'' said the letter published by
seven of Lebanon's 11 Arabic-language daily newspapers.
   Although the letter was sent to the newspapers in English, they
only published a translation of it in Arabic. Anderson is not known
to read Arabic.
   The newspapers also published a photograph of American country
music star Hank Williams Jr. receiving a bracelet from Anderson's
sister, Peggy Say.
   The bracelet carries Anderson's name and the date of his
abduction. Williams signed a birthday card for Anderson, as did
other stars before the Country Music Association Awards show began
in Nashville, Tenn. on Oct. 10.
   The papers that published the letter included Al-Haqiqa, the
mainstream Shiite Amal militia's main daily publication. Amal is
locked in a power struggle with the pro-Iranian fundamentalists who
include Anderson's kidnappers.
   Amal leader Nabih Berri, who also is justice minister in the
predominantly Moslem Cabinet of Lebanon's dual government, has
denounced the kidnapping of foreigners as an ``unforgivable crime.''
   The letter to Anderson said: ``Those of us on the Journalists
Committee to Free Terry Anderson, as well as thousands of others
throughout our profession, pay tribute to you for honoring
throughout your career the highest standards of journalism.
   ``We respect your commitment to truth and fairness in your
coverage of Lebanon, your partisanship towards none, your respect
towards all,'' the letter added.
   ``Yet we also honor you today as a man of dignity and courage in
the dark places of privation. All free men and women who live by the
pen share this morning in your captivity,'' it said.
   ``As you mark your 41st birthday, your fourth in incarceration,
we join our hearts with yours in yearning for your freedom. We greet
you, we salute you and we encourage you,'' the letter said.
   In addition to Anderson, the 13 foreigners missing in Lebanon are
eight Americans, three Britons, an Italian and an Irishman.
</TEXT>
