<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Anti-US 1stLd-Writethru a0509 10-26 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Anti-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0509,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Government, Anti-U.S. Protests Flare Anew</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with 13 students arrested,
protest in Seoul. Pickup 9th graf pvs, ``The radicals...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chanting anti-government and anti-U.S.
slogans, radical students today threw firebombs and rocks at three
government buildings and a U.S. cultural center, police and news
reports said.
   About 100 students directed their attack on the U.S. Information
Service building in the southern city of Taegu, police and the U.S.
Embassy said. It was the third attack on U.S. offices in two weeks.
   The embassy said in a statement that the assailants threw stones
and firebombs, which did not explode, and dispersed police guarding
the center. The students fled when police reinforcements arrived and
fired tear gas, it said.
   There were no injuries, but windows at the center were broken,
and a USIS car and two other cars in the parking lot were damaged,
the embassy said.
   Yonhap, the South Korean news agency, said assailants also
firebombed a police building near the center, shattering 10 windows.
   The agency said bands of students carrying firebombs and clubs
also attacked a government party building and a government
prosecutors' office in downtown Taegu, smashing windows and
destroying two cars.
   Police said 13 students were arrested. One student was
hospitalized after he cut his wrist with a knife and jumped off a
fourth-floor office to a safety net on the ground when police
charged into the prosecutors' building, which had been seized by 10
students, police said.
   Yonhap said students were demanding the arrest of former
President Chun Doo-hwan, who is under parliamentary investigation
for alleged corruption.
   Also today, two cars were burned in southern Seoul when 250
students hurled firebombs in a brief street protest demanding Chun's
arrest.
   The radicals also demand the withdrawal of about 42,000 U.S.
troops stationed in South Korea under a mutual defense pact,
contending the presence of U.S. troops hampers unification of the
Korean peninsula, which has been divided since 1945.
   Police have tightened security around the U.S. Embassy, cultural
centers and other American government facilities because of the
current anti-U.S. campaign, which has been on the rise since the
Olympic Games ended Oct. 2.
   On Oct. 14, students injured 13 policemen and razed a police bus
in a firebomb attack on a U.S. cultural center in the southern city
of Kwangju.
   About 21 students hurled firebombs at a U.S.O. building near
downtown Seoul on Friday, a week after a U.S. soldier and three
Koreans were injured in a group fight involving dozens of American
soldiers and Koreans near U.S. military headquarters in southern
Seoul.
</TEXT>
