<2ND_LINE>PM-Lotto Winners,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sisters To Split $31.5 Million _ Ex-Husband Picked Numbers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Miss Snipes as second reference is cq, per her preference.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two sisters who work in the same factory
will share a $31.5 million lottery jackpot, despite the fact that
neither one selected the six winning numbers.
   Mary Ellen Snipes and Maxine Johnson said the winning numbers
were selected by Miss Snipes' ex-husband, Lewis Snipes, who chose
the numbers from the stub of her last paycheck. He also bought the
10 tickets on behalf of the sisters.
   Snipes, who was at a news conference with the sisters Tuesday,
was asked if he would get any of the money.
   ``That's still in question,'' he said.
   He and his ex-wife were asked if they were going to get married
again.
   ``No way,'' she replied.
   But she did say she remained close to Snipes, thanked him for his
role in her winning _ and said he would get some of the money.
   The women, both assembly line leaders at a Riviera Beach
electronic components company called Solitron Devices, will share
$1,576,743 a year, before taxes, for the next 20 years. The total
prize is the third-largest since the Florida lottery began early
this year.
   ``We always go in together,'' Miss Snipes said.
   The sisters, who live in the southeastern Florida farming
community of Indiantown, took the day off from work to file their
claim.
   Miss Snipes said she plans to keep working and would build a
``dream house'' with her new wealth.
   Mrs. Johnson said she didn't know what she would do with her half
of the money and was unsure whether she would keep her job. But she
said she would keep working at least until Nov. 2, when the first
lottery check is expected to arrive.
   Both women declined to give their ages, but said they were
grandmothers.
   The winning numbers were 3, 11, 14, 15, 27 and 40.
</TEXT>
