<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0849EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vatican-Poland     10-26 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vatican-Poland,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sources: Poland Would Like Diplomatic Recognition From Vatican</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Polish government is willing to make
concessions to the Roman Catholic Church in hopes of obtaining full
diplomatic recognition from the Holy See, Vatican sources said today.
   At recent talks at the Vatican, the Polish government presented a
revised version of a longstanding proposal that would offer the
church greater freedoms and rights, said the sources. They spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   They said no decisions were made and further negotiations are not
expected before January.
   The sources, familar with the Vatican's Eastern European policy,
said the Polish government for some time has been seeking to
re-establish formal relations, which were broken when the Communists
took power after World War II.
   The government proposal is believed to include legal guarantees
for the church; agreement to allow lay Catholic groups; and promises
to end restrictions on the Catholic press, such as in the supply of
newsprint.
   One source said the proposals weren't contingent on the granting
of full recognition but that it is known the government would
welcome the gesture from the Vatican.
   It is believed that such a move by the Vatican would bolster
Polish leaders in their attempt to deal with internal dissent.
   However, some Vatican officials are skeptical about such a move
at this time. And Polish-born Pope John Paul II has stressed the
need to make such relations ``credible'' in the eyes of the Polish
people and the world.
   Poland's Roman Catholic bishops have long sought a statute for
the church to protect it from the whims of various leaders.
   The church has traditionally played an important role in Poland
and supported the Solidarity labor movement, which was outlawed
after the government declared martial law in December 1981.
   Church representatives have been invited to attend talks with the
government and political opposition. Those talks were agreed to in
August by the government in return for labor leaders ending strikes
across the country.
   The start of the talks have been snagged by government objections
to two delegates proposed by Solidarity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
