<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Larson     10-26 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Larson,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Animator Eric Larson, One Of Disney's `Nine Old Men,' Dead At 83</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARNOLD STAPLETON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eric Larson, who helped bring to life such
classic Walt Disney cartoon characters as ``Pinocchio'' and ``Snow
White and the Seven Dwarfs'' during an animation career spanning 50
years, has died at 83.
   Larson died Tuesday at his home in suburban La Canada-Flintridge
of a blood illness known as myelodystlastic syndrome, said his
brother, Bland Larson.
   For decades, he was one of a closely knit group of artists hired
by Disney himself, who called the animators his ``nine old men.''
   In addition to ``Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs,'' which was
Diseny's first full-length animated film, Larson worked on
``Cinderella,'' ``Alice in Wonderland,'' ``Fantasia,'' ``The Three
Caballeros,'' ``Lady and The Tramp,'' ``One Hundred and One
Dalmatians,'' ``The Jungle Book'' and ``Sleeping Beauty.'
   The artist and his wife, who died in 1975, had no children of
their own, but Larson delighted millions of others with such
characters as Figaro, the kitten in ``Pinocchio,'' said another
brother, Peter Larson.
   ``That was his personal favorite,'' Larson said Tuesday. ``He
talked about Figaro a lot.''
   ``The kids and animals he drew, those were his children. And he
spent a lot of time with them,'' his brother said.
   Larson was born in Cleveland, Utah, and graduated from the
University of Utah. He was hired by Disney in 1933 to work on ``Snow
White and the Seven Dwarfs.''
   His final film credit was for ``The Great Mouse Detective'' in
1986.
   In the last few years before his retirement two years ago, Larson
also served as the Disney studio's training director.
   ``You can argue that Disney had better animators, but no one was
more concerned with passing on the legacy than Eric,'' said one of
his students, Andreas Deja, an animator on the hit movie ``Who
Framed Roger Rabbit.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
