<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-US     10-26 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-US,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philippines Denies Soviet Access To Shipyard Near U.S. Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government refused Soviet access
to a shipyard next to Subic Bay Naval Base because of U.S. fears the
Soviets would spy on the American facility, an official said today.
   ``Our policy is not to allow (the Soviets)'' access to the
Philippine Shipyard and Engineering Corp., the government's news
agency quoted Manuel Yan, undersecretary of foreign affairs, as
saying.
   ``They are allowed to repair ships in other shipyards but not
there,'' Yan added.
   He noted that the Philippines had rejected previous Soviet
requests to use the shipyard, which is on Subic Bay, next to the
American facility. Yan did not say when the Soviets last made such a
request.
   U.S. officials in Washington said last week the Soviets had asked
to use the shipyard.
   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said they
were worried Manila might grant the request because the shipyard is
losing money and because of dissatisfaction over recent negotiations
on the lease covering U.S. military bases in the Philippines.
   Last week, the two countries signed an agreement under which the
United States will pay $962 million in military and economic aid for
use of the bases in 1991 and 1992.
   Philippine officials wanted up to $2.3 billion a year for use of
the six bases.
</TEXT>
