<HEAD>Supreme Soviet Presidium Opens Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Soviet Presidium, the nation's top
executive body, met today to set the agenda of a parliamentary
session expected to pass the 1989 state budget, the Tass news agency
reported.
   The parliamentary session is scheduled Thursday in the Kremlin.
   In addition to the budget, the 1,500 lawmakers are expected to
approve the state economic and social development plan for next
year, a key document designed to translate Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
reformist ideas into practice.
   In a brief dispatch, Tass said Gorbachev was chairing the meeting
of the Presidium.
   ``Questions linked with the 11th session of the U.S.S.R. Supreme
Soviet, scheduled to open Thursday, are under consideration,'' it
said, without providing details.
   On Oct. 1, a special session of the Supreme Soviet elected
Gorbachev, the general secretary of the Communist Party, to the post
of Presidium chairman, or Soviet head of state.
