<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Territories     10-26 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Territories,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Strike After Misreading Leaflets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians misread a date on smudged
underground leaflets and went on strike by mistake today in parts of
the occupied territories and Jerusalem.
   Seven Arab youths were reported shot and wounded, meanwhile, in
clashes between stone-throwers and Israeli troops today in the
occupied territories.
   Strikers closed most businesses and schools and paralyzed
transportation in much of the occupied Gaza Strip. Most Gazan Arabs
who work in Israel stayed home, according to Arab reports.
   Some stores in Arab east Jerusalem and parts of Hebron, a city in
the occupied West Bank, also were closed, but transportation was
operating normally in both places.
   In parts of the West Bank, young people who normally enforce
strikes visited merchants on Tuesday to explain that the strike was
supposed to be on Saturday, Oct. 29, not today, Oct. 26. The figures
for nine and six look similar in Arabic writing, and smudged
printing on some of the leaflets caused the confusion.
   The leaflets were issued by the United National Leadership of the
Uprising, which regularly orders strikes as a tactic in the revolt
against Israeli rule of the territories captured in the 1967 Middle
East war.
   At least 303 Palestinians and six Israelis have been killed
during the uprising, which began Dec. 8. More than 7,000
Palestinians have been wounded, according to the Israeli government.
   In Nablus, the West Bank's largest city, three Palestinian
teen-agers were shot today in three separate stone-throwing
confrontations, hospital officials said. A 20-year-old man also was
admitted to a hospital after he was shot during a clash in the
Tulkarem refugee camp, the officials said.
   In the Gaza Strip, two 15-year-old boys were shot with plastic
bullets in separate clashes with soldiers in the Sabra neighborhood
of Gaza City and in the Jabaliya refugee camp, Arab reporters and
hospital officials said. Israeli troops have begun using the plastic
bullets because they are less apt to kill.
   An 18-year-old man was wounded in the leg with a plastic bullet
when troops opened fire in Rafah, hospital officials said.
   The Israeli army said it could not confirm the reports of
shootings.
   Also today, the army imposed curfews on seven Gaza refugee camps
and a neighborhood of Gaza City. Troops wrecked five Palestinian
houses in the Gaza towns of Khan Yunis and Rafah as part of their
effort to put down the revolt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
