<DOCNO> AP881026-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0930EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Yugoslavia     10-26 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republic's Leaders Quit in Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cabinet of one of the country's
six republics resigned during a debate over its crackdown on an
anti-government protest, news media reported today.
   The resignation in the southern republic of Montenegro came
Tuesday after the republic's Parliament opened debate on whether its
government and presidency overstepped authority in using police to
put down the demonstation earlier this month, the reports said.
   The Montenegrin government said it was stepping down after five
of its 20 members, including Interior Minister Lazar Djodjic, lost a
vote of confidence during the parliamentary session, the Belgrade
daily newspaper Politika said today.
   The government decided to submit its collective resignation
because it ``could not operate in the complex situation'' in which
five ministers lost the vote, Politika quoted Premier Vuko
Vukadinovic as saying. The nine-man presidency, however, won a vote
of confidence Tuesday.
   The Parliament, after its 12-hour session late Tuesday, postponed
consideration of whether to accept the government's resignation and
reconvened today, Belgrade news media reported.
   At least 10 people were injured and 12 arrested earlier this
month in Titograd, the capital of Montenegro, when police used tear
gas to disperse demonstrators protesting falling living standards.
   Yugoslavia is suffering its worst economic crisis with 217
percent annual inflation, 15 percent unemployment and steadily
declining living standards.
   The Titograd demonstrators were also demanding an end to what
they view as persecution of the minority Slav population by ethnic
Albanians in the neighboring province of Kosovo.
   The economic and ethnic issues have combined to give rise to
unrest and calls for an overhaul of Communist Party leadership
across Yugoslavia in recent months. Leaders in Vojvodina, the
nation's other province, were forced out earlier this month. Both
Kosovo and Vojvodina, though nominally autonomous, are partly
controlled by the republic of Serbia.
   The decentralized system of government and a collective federal
presidency were devised in the late President Josip Broz Tito's 1974
constitution to prevent one republic from gaining sway over the
others, but it has resulted in an ineffective government by
compromise.
   In recent months, Serbia began to work on plans to amend its
constitution to strengthen control over Kosovo, where ethnic
Albanians make up nearly 90 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
