<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Greece-Ship     10-26 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Ship,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Captain Gets Six-Day Delay To Prepare Defense</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELENA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PIRAEUS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A magistrate today delayed the hearing of
the captain of an Italian freighter accused of manslaughter in the
collision of his vessel with a Greek cruise ship carrying 486
British tourists.
   The hearing before an investigating magistrate was set for next
Tuesday.
   Capt. Flavio Caminale, 45, of Genoa, Italy, made the request
during a hearing at a Piraeus court, citing problems with
translating statements by witnesses from Greek into Italian.
   ``I'm innocent, but we must have more time to prepare everything
that's needed,'' Caminale said. ``It's a question of translation.''
   Investigating Magistrate Telemachus Flesouras granted the
request, but ruled Caminale must remain in detention.
   Two Greek sailors died, and a 14-year-old British girl and a
teacher are missing after Friday's collision between the 6,300-ton
cruise ship Jupiter and and the 5,500-ton freighter Adige outside
Piraeus harbor.
   Caminale was arrested after the collision.
   He faces charges of manslaughter through negligence, causing
serious injuries, causing a shipwreck and ignoring shipping
regulations.
   If convicted, he could be jailed up to five years.
   Caminale maintains his ship was at a standstill when the Jupiter
headed directly for his ship. He said the Jupiter swung around to
avoid a collision but struck the Adige.
   Greek officials say the Adige was approaching the Jupiter and was
unable to reverse in time. The Adige, which suffered minor damage,
was impounded during an official inquiry.
</TEXT>
