<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0948EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CocaineDeaths     10-26 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cocaine Deaths,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Detectives Investigating Three Deaths With Possible Cocaine Link</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Homicide detectives are investigating the deaths
of three people who died after injecting possibly contaminated
cocaine that they had all bought in the same place, authorities said.
   In addition, officials are trying to determine whether the death
of a fourth man, and the illness of a fifth, are linked to the
others.
   ``All five knew each other and two of them said they all bought
cocaine at the same place (on the Houston waterfront),'' said Roger
Whidmeyer, spokesman for Ben Taub Hospital.
   He said ``a very educated guess'' is that the cocaine was heavily
laced with boric acid, adding, ``There's some coke out there that's
playing Russian roulette.''
   Cocaine sometimes is cut with other substances so dealers can
sell more of the illegal drug.
   Boric acid is a white cystalline compound and is used as a mild
antiseptic, to manufacture cements and enamels, and to kill roaches.
Experts say it also can cause cardiovascular shock.
   Those who died apparently had injected the drug, and two of them
told doctors they thought they had gotten ``some bad cocaine,''
Whidmeyer said. They complained of tremendous dehydration, heart
palpitations and nausea.
   ``They were scared,'' he said.
   Two of those taken to Ben Taub died Monday and the third died
during the night _ all unofficially from cardiac arrest and renal
failure, Whidmeyer said. The fourth person died Monday at another
hospital.
   Autopsies were being performed on the four victims, and the fifth
man was in stable condition late Tuesday at Ben Taub, he said.
</TEXT>
