<DOCNO> AP881026-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0949EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pakistan-Bomb     10-26 0134</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-Bomb,0138</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb in Horse-Drawn Taxi Injures 16 in Pakistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAHORE, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb planted in a horse-drawn taxi
exploded today in a crowded market of Pakistan's second largest
city. Police said 16 people were injured, four critically.
   The mid-afternoon blast sent screaming shoppers running in panic
as a cloud of smoke hung over the market on a road that rings this
ancient walled city, witnesses said.
   Police said the blast was caused by a plastic, timed device
hidden in a wooden box in the horse cart. The taxi driver was among
those critically injured.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility.
   Pakistan has over the past two years suffered scores of terrorist
bombings, which authorities have usually blamed on agents of
neighboring Afghanistan's Marxist government. Pakistan supports
Afghanistan's anti-government guerrillas.
</TEXT>
