<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Appointment     10-26 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Appointment,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Appoints Former Revolutionary Guards Head As Military
Adviser</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hashemi Rafsanjani, Iran's parliament
speaker and acting military commander-in-chief, today appointed the
former head of the Revolutionary Guards as his military adviser.
   Tehran Radio, monitored in Nicosia, said the appointment of
Mohsen Rafiq-Doust came in a letter to him from Rafsanjani.
   It quoted the letter as saying Rafiq-Doust would advise
Rafsanjani on ``military and logistic industry affairs and matters
pertaining to the organization of the combatants.''
   Rafiq-Doust was appointed in November 1982 as Minister of the
Revolutionary Guards, who comprise elite fighters devoted to Iran's
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   He was dismissed in September after a no-confidence vote at the
Majlis, Iran's parliament.
   Rafiq-Doust had been blamed by several parliament members for a
series of battlefield defeats in the war with Iraq earlier this
year. Iran accepted a U.N. cease-fire in the 8-year-old war in July.
   The truce began Aug. 20.
   A staunch supporter of Khomeini, Rafiq-Doust had organized
security for the revolutionary leader's return home from exile in
February 1979 to overthrow Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.
</TEXT>
