<DOCNO> AP881026-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1040EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-HamadiTrial     10-26 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hamadi Trial,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hamadi's Lawyers Demand Evidence Held By U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense lawyer for confessed TWA
hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi said today he has asked a court to halt
Hamadi's trial until evidence in the United States can be checked.
   ``We have asked that no new witnesses be heard until we can see
all evidence on Hamadi held by the United States,'' said attorney
Hans-Burkhardt Steck, who is defending Hamadi against air piracy and
murder charges.
   Steck said in an interview he has ``also asked the court to hire
an American defense attorney, at the court's expense, to view the
material.''
   ``The FBI has said it has tons of material,'' related to the
case, Steck said, referring to earlier court testimony by FBI agent
Gary Noesner.
   Frankfurt's Abendpost newspaper reported today the chief trial
judge, Heiner Mueckenberger, turned over the defense request to U.S.
officials. The newspaper quoted the judge as saying: ``It is a
legitimate request for the defense to view evidence.'' Hamadi's
trial began July 5.
   Mueckenberger could not be reached for comment on the report.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, has admitted taking part in the
hijacking of the TWA jetliner on June 14, 1985, but he denied
killing U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem after the Athens-to-Rome
flight was diverted to Beirut. Stethem was the only fatality during
the hijacking, in which 39 Americans were held hostage for 17 days.
   Noesner testified he is convinced the FBI provided the Frankfurt
court all U.S.-obtained evidence relevant to Hamadi's trial. He also
invited Hamadi's defense lawyers to prepare a list of evidence they
felt could be missing and promised: ``I'll do all I can to see that
you get it.''
   The material gathered by the FBI includes news media video films
and tape recordings, some of which had been subpoened by a federal
grand jury in Washington, said Noesner.
   He said the FBI accumulated voluminous amounts of material on the
hijacking case, ``some of which applies to other ongoing
investigations,'' which Noesner said he was not authorized to turn
over to the Frankfurt court.
   In addition to Hamadi, three other men _ identified by U.S.
Justice Department sources in Washington as Hassan Ezzeddine, Ali
Atwa, and Imad Mughniyan _ are sought in connection with the
hijacking.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881026-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0462 10-26 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0462,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Urges Florida Voters to Help GOP Capture Senate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with Quayle speech; picks up pvs 7th graf
bgng, Quayle also; DELETES last 3 grafs to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle declared today that Republican
George Bush has virtually claimed an election victory in Florida,
and urged Sunshine State voters to underscore their support by
helping the GOP regain control of the Senate.
   Quayle, who is Bush's vice presidential running mate, asked
Florida voters to give Bush ``a partner in the U.S. Senate'' by
electing Republican Rep. Connie Mack III, who is locked in a close
race with Democratic Rep. Buddy MacKay to succeed retiring Sen.
Lawton Chiles, a Democrat.
   ``I know that Florida is going to vote for George Bush on Nov.
8,'' Quayle told a fund-raising breakfast for Mack in a state
considered safe for Republicans in the presidential contest.
   He said he had talked to Bush on Sunday, and the vice president
told him, ``Would you please give one message to not only Connie
Mack but the entire state of Florida, and that is George Bush needs
Connie Mack in the U.S. Senate.''
   Even though the Republicans are given little, if any, chance of
capturing Senate control, Quayle noted the president's difficulties
in dealing with a Congress dominated by the opposition party.
   ``When you're in the minority, the majority controls the gavel.
They're able to set the agenda in Congress,'' he said.
   It was the first time that Quayle had diverted his campaign
schedule to lend his support in a Senate race. But he also took the
occasion to take another swipe at Bush's presidential rival,
Democrat Michael Dukakis.
   Quayle said Dukakis' statement at the Democratic convention that
the 1988 election is about competence rather than ideology marked
``a closing chapter in liberalism in this country.''
   ``They said right up front, folks, we don't want to talk about
it,'' the Indiana senator said. ``They don't want to talk about
their ideas.''
   After the fund-raiser, Quayle toured a Honeywell plant where
components for the space shuttle and Trident missile systems are
manufactured.
   In Stone Mountain, Ga., on Monday, Quayle said Dukakis is
actively encouraging his campaign surrogates to dish out ``political
sludge'' against the GOP ticket.
   Quayle also was campaigning in Miami's Little Havana Cuban
community and Fort Lauderdale before heading to North Carolina, and
later in the week to New Jersey, New York and Pennsylvania.
   In response to a new CBS News-New York Times poll that showed
Bush with a 13-point lead over Dukakis, Quayle said, ``The race is
not over. It's a good sign. It's a positive development. Who knows
what will happen in these last two weeks.''
   The vice presidential candidate also said: ``We are confident we
are going to win, but we're not overconfident.''
   Quayle was answering abortion questions again on Tuesday in his
plane to Tampa, Fla.
   The Indiana senator was asked about a comment the previous day in
which he said that he hoped if his wife were raped and became
pregnant, she would elect to have the baby and not have the abortion.
   Asked if that wasn't a pro-choice stance, he said: ``It's her
choice, I told her what I would like but it's her choice. I can't
tell my wife what to do in that situation.''
   ``She would have that choice'' under the law as it is now
written, he said.
   He added that he does not, however, support that law and favors
allowing each state to determine its own guidelines on abortion.
   In another interview, Quayle told a persistent young reporter
from a children's news program he would rather she had a baby than
abort the fetus if she became pregnant through her father.
   ``That's a difficult question and one that does not have an easy
answer, but my answer would be yes,'' Quayle told an 11-year-old
reporter for ``Chidren's Express'' during a bus tour of Illinois
last week.
   The question-and-answer session was broadcast Tuesday on the CBS
Evening News. The children's show is broadcast on public television.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
