<DOCNO> AP881026-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   10-26 0934</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0978</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout
the nation.
   Oct. 23
   The Wenatchee (Wash.) World on child care:
   A heretofore groggy corporate America is finally waking up to the
depth and breadth of the child care issue. That's because valuable
employees (many of them women) are increasingly weighing child care
options as they decide where to work. ...
   The issue is getting its first serious governmental attention as
the reality sinks in that more and more households are inevitably
going to be two-worker situations. Recognition of that fact at the
private corporate level is no doubt helping to spur government
interest.
   Just one thing: While all these efforts to create better
situations for children (and parents) are laudable, we need to keep
in mind that families who decide to have one parent stay home to
raise the kids themselves (and thereby sacrifice that second income)
ought not to be penalized in any way by tax write-offs or tax
increases which are not equitably applied.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct 21
   The Oak Ridger, Oak Ridge, Tenn., on the Department of Veterans
Affairs:
   Ronald Reagan campaigned in 1980 on a theme of getting big
government off the backs of the American people. Part of that
campaign included proposals to abolish the two newest Cabinet
departments, Energy and Education.
   Those plans have long since been dropped and the departments are
flourishing bureaucracies.
   The Senate recently gave final approval of a new Department of
Veterans Affairs, in effect elevating the Veterans Administration to
Cabinet status.
   Each time a Cabinet department is added it means new, and often
duplicated, expense. And with the new status, the departments begin
to grow far beyond their previous bounds.
   Of course, in an election year it's not likely that anybody would
oppose creation of a Department of Veterans Affairs. That might
smack of being anti-veteran.
   What we are likely to see is a new tangle of rules and
regulations as the bureaucrats carve out their niches in the new
department.
   And veterans, like non-veterans, will help foot the bill through
taxes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 23
   Aberdeen (S.D.) American News on the privilege of voting:
   People who lose their voices to laryingitis are handicapped. If
the silence persists, they visit a doctor.
   In the same way, voters who shun the ballot box are handicapped,
since they have little, if any voice in our democracy. What is
disturbing is that many people are not seeking a cure to this
handicap.
   George Bush or Michael Dukakis will make headlines next month by
winning the presidency. The entire U.S. House and one-third of the
Senate faces election.
   Yet almost half of the people of voting age _ about 75 million _
will stay away from the polls on Nov. 8.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 24
   The Meridian (Miss.) Star on new terrorist demands:
   New threats by the Islamic Jihad ... have turned the nation's
attention _ at least momentarily _ from the president's race and
back to the crisis in the Middle East. Perhaps there is a connection.
   If the terrorists are fishing for a deal with one or the other of
the candidates or President Reagan, himself, they are in for a
disappointment.
   The United States cannot afford to make deals with terrorists. It
would only lead to additional terrorist acts _ perhaps more
kidnappings. ...
   Vice President Bush ... (and Michael) Dukakis ... have joined
President Reagan in vowing that there will be no concessions to the
Islamic Jihad or to those who hold ... Americans hostage.
   There can be none.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 19
   Bridgeton (N.J.) Evening News on separating education and
religion:
   The Woodstown School Board has a problem ... as a group of
parents seeks the ouster of a teacher .... they say attempted to
teach religion when she advised her pupils that celebrating
Halloween was ... the work of Satan.
   That same First Amendment that bans the teacher from advocating
any religious belief in the classroom ... grants her the right to
opinion and to express it in public if she so wishes, but she may
not express it in the classroom where she might influence children
of others who hold different beliefs. ...
   Halloween ... , the night before All Saints Day in most Christian
churches, only in relatively recent times ... was thought of as a
joke.
   After all, in the old Scotch prayer book, a littany read at the
service ... said ``From ghoulies and ghosties and things that go
bump in the night, Dear Lord, deliver us.''
   But whatever your beliefs of Halloween may be, you are ... not
entitled to force them on me. That is the reason why school prayer
has been banned.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 19
   Statesman-Journal, Salem, Ore., on health hazards and nuclear
plants:
   Researchers will try to determine whether as many as 20,000
people who lived near Washington's Hanford Nuclear Reservation in
the 1940s and early 1950s were contaminated by radioactivity.
   Thousands of people ... contend that radioactive emissions from
the plant through the years have caused an unusual number of rare
cancers, miscarriages and other health problems. ...
   This new search ... is a continuation of the saga of a federal
government that for nearly a half-century has operated its nuclear
weapons plants with reckless disregard for the safety of its workers
and the safety of people living in the region. ...
   (Neighbors of nuclear-weapons plants) should be told ... fully of
the dangers they face. ... They have the right to know ... from the
people who are supposed to be protecting them.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
