<DOCNO> AP881026-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   10-26 0905</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0953</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: protecting them.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 25
   Portland (Maine) Press Herald on banning plastic firearms:
   No one is manufacturing all-plastic firearms _ yet. But the
technology is available and it's only a matter of time.
   Given that prospect, Congress acted prudently last week in
approving a ban on firearms capable of evading detection by metal
detectors or X-ray machines.
   The measure is a necessity. It bans the manufacture, importation,
sale, shipment or possession of any firearm containing less than 3.7
ounces of stainless steel, exclusive of parts and magazines.
   Without this sort of legislation it would be possible for
terrorists and other criminals to smuggle concealed weapons through
detection devices at airports or courtrooms.
   With it, the job of law enforcement officials is enhanced. ...
   The measure is a sensible one. Far better to confront the problem
now, before undetectable plastic firearms are on the market and on
the street.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 25
   Los Angeles Times on the presidential campaign:
   If the opinion polls are right, neither George Bush nor Michael
S. Dukakis has come remotely close to inspiring any appreciable
number of his fellow citizens. ...
   Some of that is due to the two relatively colorless
personalities. A lot more has to do with the deplorable and even
contemptible quality of their campaigns.
   This has been without doubt the nastiest and most cynical contest
for the White House in recent memory, and _ worse _ the most devoid
of substance. ...
   The cynicism behind these negative strategies derives from the
obvious calculation that voters will be swayed by misrepresentations
and lies because they are too stupid or uncaring to know any better.
...
   Probably no campaign in the 20th Century ... has done less to
illuminate the likely decisions that the next president will be
forced to make. ...
   We don't know who the winner will be on Nov. 8. It's clear
already that the American people are the losers.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 25
   The Phoenix Gazette on U.S. supporters of Israel:
   The scalps of senators and congressmen who defied its wishes hang
from the belt of the American Israel Public Affairs Committee
(AIPAC). It is that powerful.
   The Washington-based Israeli lobby does not always get what it
wants, but it gets it frequently enough to prompt Jeffrey Record, a
senior research fellow at the Hudson Institute, to remark that AIPAC
knows no Israeli act for which there is not an exculpatory
explanation or mitigating excuse.
   ``The prevailing view at the committee's headquarters,'' he said,
``seems to be that all Americans, Jews and gentiles alike, should
keep still and simply fork over whatever amount of military and
economic assistance Israel demands. To express an opinion critical
of how Israel uses its virtually blank checks from the United States
is to commit the unpardonable sin of meddling in the internal
affairs of a sovereign state.''
   Albeit slowly, friends of Israel who do not share AIPAC's myopic
passion are waking to the fact that the lobby does not always speak
for all American Jews.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 19
   Hannibal (Mo.) Courier-Post on taxes:
   We believe businesses and individuals ought to be treated equally
by the IRS, with everyone paying their fair share under the law.
   If businesses cheat on their taxes, they should face the same
consequences that individuals do now.
   The IRS should require the same information from businesses and
use it to gain those revenues now lying uncollected.
   We doubt if a more aggressive tax collection policy alone will
solve the federal government's deficit problems. Sterner measures
may be required.
   But it would clearly be a step in the right direction.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 19
   The Daily Oklahoman, Oklahoma City, on the stock market crash
anniversary:
   A year after the worst stock market crash in U.S. history, the
nation is prosperous and most of its citizens are living well.
   A Media General-Associated Press poll finds that while Americans
are wary of Wall Street, they are optimistic about the economy and
their personal finances.
   A look at what has transpired since Oct. 19, 1987, helps explain
the upbeat mood.
   The stock plunge of 508 points did not spark a recession, as some
had feared. Instead, the country's longest period of peacetime
growth stretched into its 71st month. ...
   This is a time when both consumers and producers can appreciate
the resilience of the economy.
   It is also a good time to remember that protectionist trade
policies and tax increases were blamed for the Great Depression of
the 1930s _ a mistake that must not be repeated.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 20
   Sherman (Texas) Democrat on Nancy Reagan's borrowed clothes:
   Good grief, another Nancy flap. In a feat of journalistic
enterprise, Time magazine collected 300 photographs of the first
lady wearing clothes ... and learned that she's been borrowing glad
rags from couturier friends for years.
   And she failed to report this nefarious activity on her White
House financial-disclosure forms since 1982.
   When judging a so-called Crime of the Century it's wise to ask:
Who got hurt? In Nancy's clothing caper, nobody. ...
   By now the first lady should know that she can't please the catty
correspondents on the Nancy Watch.
   If she bought the clothes she wears, they'd call her extravagant.
If she bought a few dresses and wore them often, they'd declare her
a frump. Because she borrowed, they imply she's a crook.
   She ought to invite them in and serve unsweetened lemonade.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
