<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   10-26 0896</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0937</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: unsweetened lemonade.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 25
   The Greenville (S.C.) News on racism and the presidential race:
   Gov. Michael Dukakis, lagging in the presidential campaign polls,
has brought Jesse Jackson back into the limelight to say ... Vice
President George Bush has been using ``race conscious'' tactics to
create an unfavorable opinion of Dukakis among white voters.
   It is widely agreed that Dukakis sent Jackson practically
underground after the Democratic nominating convention because
Jackson had become a racially divisive personality whose further
rhetorical exertions could not increase the vote already assured the
Dukakis-Bentsen ticket, but probably would drive undecided voters to
the Bush-Quayle ticket. ...
   The point of Jackson's re-emergence isn't racial fairness. It's
to rekindle lagging interest of his own supporters for ... Dukakis.
And what better way than to accuse the Bush campaign of racism?
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 25
   The Albuquerque (N.M.) Tribune on approving new drugs:
   The U.S. Food and Drug Administration has taken an overdue step
to make new drugs available more quickly to people with
life-threatening diseases.
   The federal agency said it will short-circuit the lengthy drug
approval process in order to get promising new medications faster to
patients suffering such deadly illnesses as AIDS and cancer.
   This could shorten by several years the period between the time a
potentially beneficial drug is discovered and the time it is made
generally available to patients.
   The move is welcome news for many people whose lives are hanging
in the balance.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 24
   The Gadsden (Ala.) Times on civil rights protection:
   Congress enacts the laws that the rest of us must live by, but
Congress itself sometimes is exempt from these laws.
   A case in point is civil rights protection. Employers everywhere
are prohibited from discriminating against their employees on
grounds of race, religion, age or gender.
   But not Congress. Congressional employees have no such
protection. ...
   But cannot Congress give its employees somewhat the same
protection all other employees have short of bringing them under the
civil rights acts? Yes, and to its credit the House is now moving to
do just that.
   The House is creating a special office to handle complaints of
this nature. The arrangement calls for mediation and remedies, with
a separate panel designated to handle appeals from either side.
   If handled properly this plan will provide adequate protection
for House employees. The Senate unfortunately has shown no
indication that it will follow the House's lead.
   Public pressure in time, however, could change that.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 20
   Charleston (W.Va.) Daily Mail on PAC money:
   Don't hold your breath waiting for Congress to clean up its
political action committees. At last count 228 representatives and
49 senators ... had PACs of their own.
   These personal PACs are built from campaign contributions, then
passed out to colleagues. That's how power is built these days.
   Two years ago, Jim Wright passed out a whopping $387,000 through
his PAC. Small wonder he became House speaker. He was surpassed by
Tony Coelho of California, who passed out $567,000 on his way to
becoming House majority whip. ...
   In the 1985-86 re-election cycle, Rep. Charles Rangel of New York
made a donation to Rep. Thomas Luken of Ohio, who donated it to Rep.
Bill Richardson of New Mexico, who donated it to then-Rep. Harry
Reid of Nevada, who donated it to Rep. Frank McCloskey of Indiana,
who donated it to candidate Thomas Ward of Indiana. Ward spent the
money and lost his race.
   Maybe it's time that the people who gave money to Rangel, only to
see it end up in the hands of Ward, smarten up and demand a new
system of campaign finance.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 24
   Jamestown (N.Y.) Post-Journal on the new trade bill:
   With the president's signature fresh on a new trade bill, a lot
of Americans may think that our trade worries are over.
   That's not so, and the next president of the United States had
better be prepared to face up to economic realities come January.
   The trade deficit is still running out of control despite a few
months of showing improved statistics. The Economic Policy Institute
reported this month that the failure of the United States to close
its huge trade deficit cost the country as many as 5.1 million jobs
last year. ...
   The next administration has a huge job awaiting it _ and the
trade deficit is yet another topic neither candidate wants to
address during the campaign.
</TEXT>
