   Oct. 25
   Indianapolis Star on media treatment of Sen. Dan Quayle:
   There are those who would suggest that the news media have been
unfair to Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana, the Republican vice
presidential candidate. But the significant point is that the latest
person to say it is Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
   The coverage ``has not been a fair characterization of him,''
Kennedy said in a speech at the Associated Press Managing Editors
convention in Boston last week.
   ``Most of his colleagues would say he does a lot better in
give-and-take in the Senate,'' said Kennedy. ``I've worked with him,
and he does a better job on the (Senate) floor.'' ...
   Kennedy said that in the 1988 presidential campaign the media and
politics are dangerously intertwined, a point with which few
open-minded people would disagree.
   Kennedy deserves high credit for doing what he can to set the
record straight about Sen. Quayle.
