<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Israel 7thLd-Writethru a0576 10-26 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Israel, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0576,0738</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Warplanes Hit Palestinian Targets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with PLO spokesman warning of Israeli
ground assault, new casualty report, PLO commander killed. TRIMS. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes today attacked
Palestinian guerrilla bases in southern and central Lebanon. Police
said at least six people were killed and 40 injured near Sidon.
   Nine more people were missing and feared dead in the rubble of at
least 30 buildings destroyed near the southern port city of Sidon,
police said.
   The Israeli air raids were the third and fourth on Lebanon since
a suicide car bomber killed eight Israeli soldiers a week ago.
   Also today, Israeli gunners and allied militiamen fired mortars
and howitzers at leftist Lebanese factions allied with the
Palestinians in and around the southeastern town of Mashgara, police
said. A PLO spokesman said Israeli troops were preparing for a major
ground assault in southern Lebanon.
   Those killed near Sidon included Col. Mustafa Daoud, commander of
a 1,000-man militia attached to the Fatah guerrilla faction of the
PLO.
   The wounded included Col. Mohsen Hallak, commander of the
Palestine Liberation Organization's 1,000-strong Beit al-Maqdes
batallion and officers of Force 17, the PLO's security apparatus,
police said.
   Reporters saw 20 people lying on the ground, apparently dead or
wounded.
   Four fighter-bombers thundered in from the Mediterranean sky west
of Sidon at 11 a.m., a police officer said, to stage ``one of
Israel's heaviest air assaults, if not the heaviest, this year.''
   They fired 12 rockets into the refugee camp of Mieh Mieh and the
nearby Ein el-Dilb hill on Sidon's southeastern outskirts in three
sorties spaced over eight minutes, police reported.
   At 2:30 p.m., Israeli warplanes attacked pro-Syrian Palestinian
guerrilla bases just south of Beirut in suburban Khalde and Aramoun
and in hills above the coastal towns of Damour and Naameh, police
said. Damour and Naameh are located midway on the coastal highway
between Beirut and Sidon.
   Casualty reports from those attacks were not immediately
available.
   Syrian anti-craft batteries near Beirut airport and Aramoun
opened up at the Israeli planes, but no hits were claimed, police
said.
   Describing the damage near Sidon, a police spokesman said, ``At
least 30 buildings within a radius of 150 yards in Mieh Mieh's
central square were pulverized. Many victims, ``including a family
of six members, are still buried in the rubble,'' said the
spokesman, who demanded anonymity.
   ``It's a massacre,'' said Abu Yasser, the Palestine Liberation
Organiztaion military commander of the Sidon region who uses only
his nom-de-guerre. ``Plenty of people are buried in the debris.''
   ``It was so swift that we couldn't look up at the sky to fire
back at the planes,'' said a guerrilla who identified himself only
as Abu Khaled.
   ``We were stunned, motionless. No one even dared to go to the
rescue until a half-hour after the raid ended,'' he said.
   Targets belonging to PLO chairman Yasser Arafat's mainstream
Fatah guerrilla group in Mieh Mieh and Ein el-Dilb took the brunt of
the attack. Most of them were one-story houses, police said.
   Two command posts of the Marxist Popular Front for the Liberation
of Palestine and the Moscow-oriented Democratic Front for the
Liberation of Palestine also were flattened, police said. Israeli
said the targets had been used as bases for launching attacks
against Israel.
   In Israel, the military command confirmed the raids on the Sidon
area, the hills above Damour and the bluffs just above Beirut,
saying the jets scored accurate hits and returned safely to base.
   Israeli gunners and allied militiamen of the South Lebanon Army
today fired mortars and howitzers at leftist Lebanese factions
allied with the Palestinians in and around the southeastern town of
Mashgara, police said.
   They said the shelling could precede a ground thrust by the
Israeli army and the SLA north of Israel's self-designated security
zone in south Lebanon. Pro-Syrian leftists guerrillas are entrenched
in the Mashgara region.
   In Baghdad, Bassam Abu Sharif, spokesman for Arafat, said Israeli
troops were massing inside the six-to-10 mile wide security zone in
preparation for a large-scale attack on Lebanese and Palestinian
forces in Sidon.
   ``The information we received from the area today indicates that
are large-scale offensive is imminent,'' said Abu Sharif. He accused
the United States and Syria of supporting the Israeli action.
</TEXT>
