<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Uganda-PriestKilled     10-26 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Uganda-Priest Killed,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dutch-Born Priest Shot Dead, Home Looted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen robbed and killed a Dutch-born
Roman Catholic priest when he returned to his house with medical
supplies for his mission hospital, another priest said today.
   The Rev. Cornelious Spil, 44, who had been in Uganda for 17
years, was fatally shot Saturday night by five men in military
uniform, said the Rev. Zonneveld James.
   James, of the Bwasale Mission Hospital in Iganga district, 110
miles east of Kampala, said three men had rifles.
   ``No sooner than Father Cornelius returned than the armed men
surrounded him as he got out of his car,'' James said. ``They forced
him into his house and demanded the keys for the safe where the
money was kept. The attackers also helped themselves to the
medicine, clothes and money.''
   They shot Spil as they fled, James said.
   Spil had bought the medical supplies at Jinja town, 40 miles east
of Kampala.
   James believed the raiders were criminals and not members of
armed groups fighting President Yoweri Museveni's government.
   Museveni, who waged a five-year guerrilla war against civilian
President Milton Obote's government, seized power in February 1986.
   At least eight groups have waged guerrilla battles against his
government and often raided civilians for food, clothes and medical
supplies.
</TEXT>
