<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CampaignTV 2ndLd-Writethru a0463 10-26 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign TV, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0463,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Releases Four New Ads; Bush Commercial Says Rival Misled
the Nation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf, The new, to UPDATE with Bush ad starting
Wednesday night</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis promises families and
workers he's ``on your side'' in four new television ads playing to
his party's strengths, while Republican George Bush alleges in
another spot that his rival misled 62 million Americans.
   The new Dukakis ads were scheduled to begin airing Thursday in
spot markets around the country, said spokeswoman Lorraine Voles.
The new Bush ad began airing Wednesday night, also in spot markets.
   The Bush spot, the latest development in a series of tit-for-tat
distortion charges, says the Massachusetts governor ``deliberately
misled'' 62 million Americans when he denied during the televised
Oct. 13 presidential debate that he raided his state pension system
to balance the budget.
   Quoting The Wall Street Journal as saying ``it is indisputable''
that Dukakis shifted the money, a narrator concludes: ``And Michael
Dukakis says George Bush is running a campaign of lies? Michael
Dukakis is unbelievable.''
   Dukakis and Bush each are running a mix of positive and attack
ads, concentrated most heavily in pivotal states like California,
Texas and Ohio.
   One of the new Dukakis ads shows an elderly couple on a bench in
an urban park. A voiceover says: ``Imagine a place where people can
grow old without being made to feel like a burden. Is that too much
to expect? As president, Michael Dukakis would be on your side. To
those who would cut Social Security, he'll say never. And he'll back
full cost-of-living adjustments.''
   Another shows children on a playground and says: ``Imagine a
place where children come out to play without fear of drugs or drug
dealers. Is that too much to expect? As president, Michael Dukakis
will be on your side. He'll declare a real war on drugs. Double the
number of drug agents and slash aid to countries that allow drug
traffic.''
   The other two spots talk about stretching two paychecks ``for the
life one paycheck used to bring'' and vow to ``take on the toughest
foreign competition and make America number one again.'' All four
ads end with the tagline: ``Dukakis-Bentsen. The best America is yet
to come.''
   The Dukakis campaign announced two more network appearances for
its candidate _ an interview with Dan Rather on the CBS Evening News
on Thursday night, 14 minutes long according to CBS producers; and
an interview Friday with NBC anchor Tom Brokaw for a series next
week on the candidate's positions.
   Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd Bentsen was scheduled
to appear Wednesday night on CBS News. The Dukakis campaign also has
purchased five minutes of television time for Bentsen on the CBS
network Sunday night, said campaign adviser Tad Devine.
   Dukakis will be interviewed by David Frost for a Fox Television
network show to be broadcast Nov. 6, two days before the election.
   Since adopting a high-profile media strategy aimed at getting
voters to take another look at his candidacy, Dukakis has appeared
on the three network morning programs, a nationally televised cable
interview show and ABC's ``Nightline.''
   He also bought four five-minute, prime-time slots for a paid
advertisement that aired Saturday night on ABC. It was repeated
Tuesday night and will be shown again Nov. 1 and Nov. 5. Each airing
costs the campaign between $125,000 and $175,000.
   Bush had a stormy 9-minute confrontation with Rather on CBS News
last Jan. 25, during the height of the primary season. He turned
down the ``Nightline'' invitation, saying he had already appeared on
the show, but is weighing interview requests from other news and
talk shows.
   ``We're giving serious consideration to a few of them,'' said
Bush spokesman Mark Goodin. ``We will end up doing several. How many
I don't know. It's a question of whether we can get to them.''
</TEXT>
