<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SelmaMayor     10-26 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Selma Mayor,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Selma Mayor Elected Legally, Judge Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has upheld the re-election of the
Selma mayor to a record seventh term, ruling that a black former
city councilman failed to provide any evidence the results were
tainted.
   Montgomery County Circuit Judge Joseph Phelps also ordered
challenger Cleophus Mann to pay all court costs. Phelps heard the
case in Dallas County, where Selma is located, after two Dallas
County judges removed themselves from the case.
   Mann failed by 433 votes to force a runoff from the Aug. 23
election with incumbent Mayor Joe Smitherman. Mann challenged the
results, saying polling places had been moved improperly and voters
were intimidated, but Phelps ruled Tuesday that the suit had no
basis.
   ``The plaintiff (Mann) testified he had no evidence that illegal
votes had been cast in the Aug. 23 election and did not offer any
evidence regarding the casting of illegal votes at trial,'' said
Phelps.
   ``I don't want to beat a dead dog, but there never was a case to
start with,'' Smitherman said. ``He had his day in court, and the
judge's order speaks for itself.''
   Mann refused to comment on the decision.
   Phelps said Mann's claim seemed to focus on allegations that the
city failed to obtain approval from the U.S. Justice Department
before moving several polling places, as required under the 1965
Voting Rights Act.
   But the judge noted that Mann voted for the changes when he
served on the city council and said that the moves were for the
convenience of voters, not for discriminatory purposes.
   During an Oct. 17 hearing, Mann testified that voters were
intimidated and pointed to the presence of Selma Police Chief M.E.
Summerlin at the polls wearing his weapon.
   But in his ruling, Phelps said he found ``no act of intimidation
or other acts of misconduct'' calculated to prevent the exercise of
the right to vote.
   Smitherman was elected to his first term as mayor of the western
Alabama city shortly before it drew national attention as a
battleground of the civil rights movement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
