<HEAD>Two Marine Helicopters Crash In Arizona Desert; 10 Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Four people...', to add names of helicopter
manufacturers.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Helicopter Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YUMA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Marine Corps helicopters crashed in a
desert gunnery range during a training excercise, killing all 10
servicemen aboard, officials said today.
   It was not immediately known whether the two helicopters
collided, said Cpl. Darren Fuller, a public affairs spokesman at the
Marine Corps Air Station in Yuma.
   It was the second crash involving military helicopters this week.
   The aircraft were being used in a ``troop insertion exercise''
with crews using night-vision goggles when the crash occurred, said
Army Maj. Linda Dumoulin, a Pentagon duty officer.
   Four people were on a Boeing CH-46 helicopter and six on a Bell
UH-1N copter. Both helicopters are designed to carry more troops but
were not transporting full teams for the exercise, which Dumoulin
said was part of a weapons-tactics instructor's course.
   There were no survivors, said Fuller.
   The copters went down in the remote desert site about 7:45 p.m.
Tuesday approximately 125 miles southeast of the air station, said
Fuller.
   An investigation team was at the site, he said. Names of the
victims were being withheld pending notification of next of kin.
   Yuma is about 180 miles southwest of Phoenix on the Colorado
River.
   Monday night, a UH-1H helicopter crashed near the U.S.-Mexico
border in California, killing the five lawmen and three National
Guardsmen aboard during the first mission of a joint anti-drug
smuggling program.
   The Army National Guard copter smashed into the rocky foothills
of the Laguna Mountains and burst into flames after striking the
500,000 kilowatt power line.
</TEXT>
