<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1202EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Swindall 3rdLd-Writethru a0592 10-26 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Swindall, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0592,0779</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says He Will Dismiss Jury In Swindall Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with judge officially dismissing
jury, comment from Swindall, deleting outdated material; picking up
15th graf pvs, `Polls show...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today dismissed the jury in the
perjury trial of Rep. Pat Swindall because of fliers that the
congressman had mailed out, making it unlikely Swindall could be
tried before Election Day.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Vining said he believed Swindall
violated court rules by sending out campaign mass mailings that
reached residents who were potential jurors in the case both last
week and this week.
   Vining said he was ``not inclined'' to use the only other avenue
through which Swindall could be tried before the election, a
non-jury trial with Vining determining the verdict.
   But Vining left the door open to such a possibility, telling
Swindall, ``I will call you in the morning and let you know if I've
changed my mind.'' He said he was unlikely to do so, but added,
``Judges are wont to change their minds.'' No date was immediately
set for the selection of a new jury, if the judge does not change
his mind about a non-jury trial.
   Swindall, 38, was indicted Oct. 17 on 10 perjury counts. The
charges cited his statements to a grand jury about his dealings with
a an undercover Internal Revenue Service agent posing as a money
broker, and Atlanta businessman Charles LeChasney, who already has
pleaded guilty to money laundering charges that do not involve
Swindall.
   Vining had copies of two mass mailings, one of which was dated
after the time that he ordered Swindall to obey local court rules on
his comments outside the courtroom.
   Copies of the mailings were not immediately available, but
Swindall said one was headlined, ``Why did Congrssman Pat Swindall
ask to be indicted?''
   Prosecutor Craig Gillen said Swindall should not be allowed to
keep up such mailings ``under the guise of running a political
campaign.''
   ``If Mr. Swindall prefers to run for office, he can't have his
cake and eat it too,'' Gillen said. ``If he wants to send these
mailings out, let's have the trial in December or November, and have
it in an orderly fashion.''
   Pounding the rostrum as he addressed Vining, Swindall said, ``I
find it absolutely incredible that the government tells me and the
voters of the 4th District that I have to make a choice between
running for re-election and coming down here and having this trial.''
   Vining had warned both sides prior to the trial that if they said
anything outside the courtroom that would affect the trial he would
take action.
   He did not place any specific subject areas off limits, but he
seemed particularly upset that one of the mailings had referred to
Swindall's claim that he had passed a polygraph test.
   After Vining dismissed the jury, Swindall said he was ``deeply
disappointed by the turn of events today.'' He said Vining's comment
that he could change his mind was ``a ray of hope.''
   U.S. Attorney Robert Barr declined to comment on Vining's ruling.
   Opening arguments by Swindall, a lawyer who is representing
himself, and Gillen had been set for today. A jury had been seated
Tuesday.
   Swindall was so anxious about the trial's pace Tuesday morning
that he suggested giving up his right to a jury, but Vining quickly
rejected that idea.
   Polls show the two-term Republican congressman from suburban
Atlanta faces a tough re-election bid against Democrat Ben Jones in
the Nov. 8 election.
   In his appearance before a grand jury in February, Swindall, who
was looking for an $850,000 home mortgage, said he did not recall
being told the money broker's backers might be laundering illegal
drug proceeds. The government, which secretly recorded several
meetings, charges Swindall lied in his account.
   Swindall's questioning of prospective jurors revealed that he may
call former presidential candidate Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., to the
witness stand.
   Swindall asked two former New York residents who were on the
panel of prospective jurors if they knew Kemp, who ran
unsuccessfully for the GOP presidential nomination this year.
Neither of the two was chosen as a juror.
   Swindall later said he is considering calling Kemp to testify. He
said he will decide later based on how the government presents its
case.
   Swindall, who was a co-chairman of Kemp's presidential campaign
in Georgia, said last week he might call some members of Congress
and administration officials as character witnesses.
</TEXT>
