<DOCNO> AP881026-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AIDS-Hospitals     10-26 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Hospitals,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Risk Small for Hospital Workers, Even When Jabbed With Needles</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: The 6:30 p.m. EDT embargo on this story has been broken.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-AIDS Gloves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fewer than half of 1 percent of health care workers
mistakenly exposed to AIDS-tainted blood through cuts, needle wounds
or other accidents become infected with the lethal virus, a new
survey shows.
   The review, conducted at 335 hospitals across the United States,
concludes that ``the risk of HIV infection after exposure to the
blood of a patient infected with HIV is low.''
   The risk of catching AIDS from patients is a serious concern in
many hospitals. The latest research confirms earlier studies showing
that while this threat is slight, on-the-job infection can happen.
   The researchers followed 1,201 nurses and other hospital workers
who came into contact with the blood of people infected with HIV,
the AIDS virus. A report on the work, directed by Ruthanne Marcus of
the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta, was published in this
week's New England Journal of Medicine.
   Results of AIDS testing were available for 963 of the health care
workers, and four of them, or 0.42 percent, were infected as a
result of needle sticks.
   Two of the four cases occurred when people were accidentally
stuck with needles by fellow workers during emergency resuscitation
procedures.
   Among the report's findings:
   _Sixty-three percent of the potential AIDS exposures occurred in
nurses, 14 percent in doctors and medical students, 11 percent in
lab technicians, 7 percent in people drawing blood, 3 percent in
respiratory therapists and 2 percent in housekeeping and maintenance
workers.
   _Eight percent of the exposures resulted from needle sticks. The
rest were cuts with sharp objects, open wound contamination and
exposure to mucous membranes.
   _Thirty-seven percent of the exposures could have been prevented
if routine precautions had been followed.
   The researchers said their work ``underscores the need to handle
sharp instruments carefully in all circumstances, even during
emergencies.''
   In a separate report in the journal, researchers reported on the
high rate of AIDS infection at a hospital in Kinshasa, Zaire. They
said there was no evidence that the health care workers had gotten
their infections on the job, because the infection rate was the same
among those with heavy contact with patients and those who rarely
saw patients.
   The research, conducted by Dr. Bosenge N'Galy and colleagues from
Project SIDA, was based on AIDS infection tests given to 2,002
workers at Mama Yemo Hospital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
