<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0486 10-26 0829</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0486,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Pollsters Won't Decide Election, Hears Hispanics Hint
at Upset</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with late developments; picks up pvs 4th graf
bgng, ``I feel good.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis declared today the ``pollsters are
not going to call the election'' and heard Hispanic leaders say that
a heavy voter turnout by their constituents could deliver a
Democratic upset on Election Day.
   The Democratic presidential nominee had breakfast with Hispanic
leaders in Denver the morning after he said during in a 90-minute
interview on ABC-TV's ``Nightline'' that he was making ``real
progess'' against Republican rival George Bush. Most national polls
suggest otherwise.
   ``The pollsters are not going to call the election,'' Dukakis
told reporters in a statement. ``It's people who are going to be
voting.''
   Dukakis claimed overwhelming support among Hispanics, which he
said stemmed from his longstanding commitment to minority issues,
especially the war against drugs.
   ``They want a president who doesn't talk about the subject but
who has done something about it,'' the Massachusetts governor said.
   The Hispanic leaders praised Dukakis for his commitment to civil
and voting rights, affirmative action, urban renewal and economic
development.
   They said Hispanics are grossly under-represented in presidential
polls, and that a 70 percent turnout among them could swing a close
election in Dukakis' favor.
   Rep. Albert Bustamante of Texas saluted Dukakis as both a
``technocrat'' and the ``liberal of 1988.'' He said this meant
Dukakis cared children, the elderly, health care and the environment.
   When Bustamante used the word technocrat, Dukakis grinned and
chimed in ``15 percent.'' The candidate did not take questions from
reporters.
   During his TV interview with Ted Koppel, Dukakis said conceded he
was partly to blame for not answering early GOP campaign attacks on
his record.
   But he claimed he was gaining on the vice president despite new
polls showing he was trailing Bush by double-digit margins.
   ``I feel good about things,'' he said in the nationally televised
interview. ``I think we're making some real progress.''
   After the program Dukakis told reporters he thought the interview
was ``great, terrific.''
   Dukakis was campaigning in Colorado and Illinois today and
planned to keep a high television profile in the remaining days of
the campaign, including an interview with CBS on Thursday and NBC on
Friday.
   Dukakis was questioned on a broad range of issues during the
``Nightline'' appearance, giving the Reagan administration some
credit for winning arms control agreements with the Soviet Union
while denouncing the administration _ and specifically Bush _ for
failing in the war on drugs.
   ``I'm willing to get much, much tougher than this
administration'' in the drug fight, he said. But he reiterated his
opposition to capital punishment regardless of the offense.
   It was not until well into the interview that Dukakis raised the
issue he has been focusing on in his speeches in recent days: Bush's
support of a capital gains tax credit that Dukakis characterizes as
a boon for the rich, including the vice president himself, that will
result in an added burden on average Americans.
   Koppel, after referring to the latest polls, asked Dukakis what
Bush had done to ``nail your hide to the wall thus far.''
   Dukakis did not dispute the characterization before blaming his
position in the polls on a relentlessly negative GOP campaign and
his failure to counterattack.
   ``The Bush campaign made a very careful and deliberate decision
way back in the spring to run a tough, attacking, negative campaign
and they've been doing it ever since. And perhaps I responded too
late, perhaps I should have been out there attacking or
counterattacking from the beginning,'' Dukakis said.
   ``They questioned my patriotism, they questioned my wife's
patriotism ... they questioned my health and that kind of thing has
made this a tough and difficult campaign.''
   He accused BUsh of ducking the issues by running a campaign
``loaded with distortion ad misrepresentation and falsehoods.''
   Two polls released Tuesday night reported Bush held a
double-digit lead in the presidential race with only two weeks to
Election Day.
   A CBS News-New York Times survey of 1,287 probable voters showed
Bush leading Dukakis 54-41 percent while a Gallup poll of 815 likely
voters showed Bush up by 14 points, 53-3 percent.
   The CBS-Times poll was conducted Friday through Monday and had a
margin of error of three points. The Gallup survey was done Friday
through Sunday and had a four-point error margin.
   Dukakis said his own instincts indicated voters were turning
against the Republican campaign tactics, however. Asked about the
polls after the television interview, he said simply, ``Forging
ahead.''
   Dukakis came to Colorado after spending Tuesday morning
campaigning in California, where he took issue with a Republican
campaign commercial ridiculing him for riding in an Army tank.
   ``We Democrats are for a strong defense,'' he said. ``That's
nonsense,'' he said of the ad's assertion that he has opposed
virtually all new proposed weapons systems.
</TEXT>
