<HEAD>Researcher Killed by Rhinoceros</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURBAN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rhinoceros killed an animal
researcher from Scotland who was doing field work in a provincial
game reserve, authorities said Wednesday.
   Joanna Copley of St. Andrews University in Scotland was watching
a pack of baboons with a colleague as part of a research project on
Tuesday at the Mkuzi Game Reserve in Zululand when the rhinoceros
attacked, said June Payn, a spokeswoman for the Natal Province Parks
Board.
   The rhinoceros struck Ms. Copley, 23, with its horn and broke her
neck, Ms. Payn said.
   The animal apparently was searching for its calf when it charged.
The second researcher, Stephen Whitehead of Natal University, jumped
out of the way and was not injured.
