<HEAD>Warning Issued on Mobile Home Furnaces</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inadequately maintained Coleman mobile-home
furnaces could pose a danger, the manufacturer said Wednesday in
announcing it will inspect the furnaces and offer a discount on
replacements.
   About 100,000 Model 8600 Solar Pak mobile home-furnaces are
involved in the warning, the federal Consumer Product Safety
Commission reported.
   The commission said that both it and Coleman have received
reports of carbon monoxide poisoning involving furnaces that have
either been inadequately maintained or altered in some way.
   About 380,000 of the furnaces were made between 1964 and 1971,
but officials say they expect only about 100,000 remain in use.
   Coleman is offering owners of the units a free cooler as an
incentive to participate in the safety inspection program.
   The suspect furnaces can be identified by the name Coleman on the
front and the rating plate inside the furnace door, which will state
if it is a Coleman 8600 Solar Pak.
   Owners of the furnaces, and those uncertain about their units,
can telephone Coleman at 1-800-232-SOLR. The company will arrange
for an inspection by its nearest service center.
   If repairs or replacement are needed, the company is offering a
50 percent discount to owners of these units.
   Those needing further information can contact the Consumer
Product Safety Commission at 1-800-638-2772.
