<DOCNO> AP881026-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NATO     10-26 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Ministers to Debate on Modernizing Short-range Arms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO defense ministers begin a series of
talks Thursday that will focus on whether the alliance needs more
powerful nuclear weapons for front-line combat.
   Since the United States and the Soviet Union signed a treaty in
December to eliminate medium-range nuclear weapons, much attention
has shifted to upgrading short-range nuclear artillery and missiles.
   The talks of the Brussels-based North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, which begin at The Hague, Netherlands, will focus on
whether the Western alliance should modernize these forces.
   A Dutch defense specialist, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
told reporters in The Hague that the talks will ``make an inventory
of our options.'' The source said the discussions would provide Gen.
John Galvin, commander of NATO forces in Europe, with guidelines for
making a decision in 1989 or 1990.
   Most NATO nations want to extend the range of the short-range
tactical weapons to make up for the loss of weapons under the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty. That pact eliminated all
U.S. and Soviet land-based missiles with ranges from 300 to 3,000
miles.
   The range of a new generation of weapons would likely be extended
up to the treaty limits of about 300 miles, analysts say.
   A key candidate for upgrading is the Lance surface-to-surface
missile, which was introduced in 1972 and which military analysts
say will be obsolete by 1995. The Lance has a range of just over 62
miles, but a new system might boost that above 248 miles.
   The United States and United Kingdom have indicated support for
modernizing the short-range weapons. But Germany and the
Netherlands, which have strong anti-nuclear movements, have argued
that such a decision is not yet needed.
   The defense ministers, meeting as NATO's Nuclear Planning Group,
gather twice a year.
   Fourteen of NATO's 16 members will take part in the talks.
Iceland attends only as an observer, and France operates outside
NATO's common military planning. U.S. Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci will represent the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
