<2ND_LINE>AM-Egg Injuries,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors: Halloween Egg Throwing No Joke</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release at 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egg tossing during Halloween can be a dangerous
prank, resulting in severe eye damage to those who are hit, doctors
warned Thursday.
   In a letter in the New England Journal of Medicine, two New
Jersey doctors describe five cases of eye injury that resulted from
thrown eggs during Halloween week last year. The victims were four
teen-agers and a 72-year-old man.
   Four of them required hospitalization, and two were left with
severe damage to their vision.
   ``Halloween should be added to the list of holidays posing a
danger of eye injuries. Physicians and parents should educate young
people about the ocular (eye) catastrophes that can occur on a night
meant only for pranks and fun,'' wrote Drs. Philip M. Fiore and
Rudolph S. Wagner of the University of Medicine and Dentistry of New
Jersey in Newark.
</TEXT>
