<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Employee-Hostage     10-26 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Employee-Hostage,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hostage Incident Ends Without Injuries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man upset over being fired took his
former manager and three other employees hostage today, but
surrendered after talking to a television reporter and police
negotiators, police said. No one was hurt.
   The man was armed with a pistol, which he gave to his former
manager when he surrendered, said D.P. Capell, commander of the
patrol division for Charlotte Police.
   Capell said the man released the three other employees when the
reporter arrived. He surrendered after talking to the reporter and
negotiators for about an hour, he said.
   The man told WSOC-TV he was upset at being fired with little
notice after working long hours for Floortech Inc., assignment
editor Wayne Houseman said. Floortech is a floor tile manufacturer.
   ``He called his girlfriend and she called us,'' Houseman said.
``We called the company and (he) answered the phone, saying he was
upset and he knew he would go to jail for what he was doing but he
wanted to make a statement and was tired of being pushed around.''
   Houseman said the station alerted police, who were already aware
of the situation. He said the man asked to talk to a reporter, who
went into the plant with police negotiators.
   The man surrendered two hours after the incident began, shortly
before 11 a.m., and was taken to the Charlotte Law Enforcement
Center, police said.
   No charges were filed by late morning, and police declined to
release the man's name.
