<HEAD>Catholic Church Ousts Gay Priest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to DELETE reference to priest's being found
guilty of having non-marital sexual relationship.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Dorn Jr., who was suspended from the
Roman Catholic priesthood after revealing he is homosexual, has been
banned from the priesthood forever and officially excommunicated.
   A church tribunal found Dorn guilty of leaving the Catholic
church, and joining the Episcopal church.
   The ruling puts an end to a two-year public dispute in which Dorn
and the church clashed over the former priest's outspoken challenges
to Catholic teachings on homosexuality and his ultimate revelation
that he is gay.
   ``It's over,'' Dorn, 36, said after learning of the ruling
Tuesday.
   The tribunal's ruling was dated Sept. 30 and delivered to Dorn on
Tuesday by his church-appointed lawyer, the Rev. James Zusy of the
Archdiocese of St. Paul and Minneapolis. Zusy declined to comment on
the matter.
   Dorn said that he was told not to speak about the decree, but he
notified news media about the ruling and issued a statement critical
of the church.
   Former St. Cloud Bishop George Speltz fired Dorn from his job at
the Christ Church Newman Center at St. Cloud State University in
October 1986 after he wrote a newspaper article advocating a more
compassionate view of homosexuality. He was suspended from the
priesthood a few weeks later.
   Dorn, who lives in Minneapolis, declined to discuss his personal
life or possible plans to seek ordination in the Episcopal church.
