<1ST_LINE>r w AM-UnionContracts     10-26 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Union Contracts,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unions Won Average 3.3 Percent First-Year Wage Hikes So Far This
Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First-year base wage increases excluding
cost-of-living adjustments or COLAs averaged 3.3 percent in major
union contracts negotiated in the first nine months of this year,
the government said Wednesday.
   Including COLAs but not lump-sum bonuses now prevalent in
manufacturing, union workers under major contracts received
effective pay increases averaging 3.5 percent over the past year,
the Labor Department said.
   The average annual increase in the new contracts falls to 2.8
percent over their usual two-to-three-year lives, the Bureau of
Labor Statistics said, indicating a return to so-called front-loaded
contracts.
   Back-loaded contracts in which the biggest increases came closer
to the expiration of the accords than at their beginning had
dominated labor relations from the 1981-82 recession until last
year, according to government figures.
   Eighty percent of the some 1.4 million workers covered in major
contracts negotiated so far in 1988 received first-year increases in
their base pay, the bureau said. Eighteen percent accepted wage
freezes, and 2 percent gave up pay concessions.
   The bureau said 35 percent of those covered in contracts
negotiated from January through September of this year received
first-year wage adjustments of between 2 percent and 4 percent.
   Twenty-eight percent of the covered workers received base pay
adjustments between 4 percent and 6 percent. Adjustments of less
that 2 percent went to 14 percent of the covered workers in new
contracts while 3 percent received first-year adjustments greater
than 6 percent of their base wage.
   Including those who agreed to wage freezes or concessions in the
first year of newly negotiated contracts, the average base wage
increase in the first year of newly negotiated contracts was 2.5
percent, the government said.
   The cost-of-living adjustments or COLAs designed to adjust wages
to reflect changes in consumer prices were introduced or
reestablished for about 11 percent or 161,000 of the covered workers
under settlements reached so far this year.
   The government said virtually all of them are Teamsters covered
by the National Master Freight Agreement negotiated last spring. The
new three-year trucking industry contract reestablish a COLA that
had been suspended during the past accord.
   As a result, the government said, the proportion of union workers
covered by COLA protections in their contracts has climbed from 38
percent at the end of 1987 to 40 percent as of Oct. 1. In the 1970s,
more than half of all union workers had COLA provisions in their
contracts.
   Both COLAs and lump-sum bonuses continue to be more prevalent in
manufacturing than service industries.
   Labor contracts with manufacturers now provide some 51 percent of
the covered workers with lump-sum bonuses ranging from $200 up to
$10,000 a year and 62 percent of the workers with COLA.
   For union workers in non-manufacturing industries, only 10
percent get bonuses and 26 percent have COLA protections, the
government said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
