<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Gacy-GOPLeaflet     10-26 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gacy-GOP Leaflet,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Multiple Killer Complains about GOP Mailing Using His Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted multiple killer John Wayne
Gacy has complained to state Republican officials about a campaign
leaflet that said he would be eligible for weekend passes had he
committed his crimes in Massachusetts.
   In a letter received Monday at state Republican headquarters,
Gacy criticized the GOP for ``exploiting the name of John Wayne Gacy
in order to scare people into voting for George Bush.''
   The letter said: ``Can't Bush run on his own record and the
truth, instead of all this scarey (sic) fantasy?''
   Gacy, imprisoned at the Menard Correctional Center in southern
Illinois, confirmed today that he wrote the letter, according to
Brian Fairchild, a spokesman for the state Department of Corrections.
   A slightly different version of the letter was mailed to The
Associated Press.
   Gacy was convicted in 1980 of killing 33 young men and boys, 29
of whom were found buried in his home in an unincorporated area near
Chicago. He was sentenced to death and his case is under appeal.
   The brochure Gacy cites was distributed by the state Republican
Party. It was labeled ``garbage'' earlier this month by
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, the Democratic presidential
candidate.
   ``If John Wayne Gacy had committed his atrocious crimes in Boston
instead of Chicago, he would be eligible for weekend passes under
Michael Dukakis' furlough program,'' the leaflet said.
   Some convicted killers were granted furloughs during Dukakis'
administration, and the Bush campaign has made frequent reference to
one of them, Willie Horton, who subsequently raped a woman in
Maryland. The furlough program has since been changed to exclude
first-degree murderers.
   Stuart Piper, executive director of the state Republican Party,
said he was surprised by the letter.
   ``We didn't know if the letter was from (Gacy) and we didn't feel
that it dignified any public response,'' Piper said. ``Apparently,
he felt differently and released it to the media himself.''
</TEXT>
