<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FTCMailOrder     10-26 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FTC Mail Order,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC May Expand Mail-Order Protections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is wondering whether to give
folks who buy goods by telephone the same protections already
available to mail-order shoppers.
   The Federal Trade Commission several years ago set up
consumer-protection rules for people buying by mail. Among other
things those regulations require the seller to ship the product
within 30 days, unless the buyer agrees to a delay, and set rules
for refunds and other consumer protections.
   With telephone sales now growing enormously, the FTC announced
that it is considering extending the mail-order rules to include
telephone orders and other new telemarketing technologies.
   The agency is accepting public comments until Dec. 27. Interested
persons should write: Advance Notice of Proposed Rulemaking _
Amendment of the Mail Order Merchandise Rule, Federal Trade
Commission, 6th Street and Pennsylvania Ave., N.W., Washington,
D.C., 20580.
