<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BabySwap     10-26 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Swap,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Steps Forward; Tells Daughter Of Baby Swap Claims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saying he was tired of being a ``mystery
man,'' the father of a 9-year-old girl came forward today and
disclosed that he's told his daughter of a Pennsylvania couple's
claim to be her rightful parents.
   The couple alleges the girl was born to them but was switched
with an ailing child soon after birth at a Florida hospital.
   Robert Mays, a 43-year-old salesman, held a news conference at
his lawyer's office and said he told his daughter Kimberly Michelle
about the case last week.
   Mays, who has remained silent while trying to protect his
daughter, said he was worried she might learn about the case from
someone else.
   ``I was tired of living a lie. ... I saw no reason to keep it
secret from her any longer,'' he said.
   Mays' name, which has been known to the media, had been
voluntarily withheld in published reports to protect the child. Mays
thanked reporters for their consideration.
   ``I had hoped this scenario would go some other way,'' Mays said,
adding that he has no reason to believe that Regina and Ernest Twigg
of Langhorne, Pa., will stop pursuing their claim.
   He said his daughter took the news of the months-long legal
battle very well.
   ``She's an intelligent little girl ... well-adjusted. She's a
totally loved child and well taken care of.'' The child's mother
died of cancer when she was 3{.
   The Twiggs maintain that their daughter, a healthy girl, was
deliberately switched in the nursery at Hardee Memorial Hospital in
Wauchula shortly after birth, and they were given a sickly child.
Hospital workers then altered records to hide the swap, they allege.
   The girl they raised, Arlena, died in August from a heart defect.
The Twiggs say Kimberly was born at Hardee Memorial in late 1978 at
about the same time as Arlena.
   The Twiggs say genetic tests this summer revealed Arlena was not
their biological daughter.
   They filed a $100 million suit against the hospital and some of
its employees and persuaded the FBI to investigate. The FBI,
however, failed to find sufficient evidence that federal laws had
been violated.
   The Twiggs have asked a court for genetic testing to determine if
Kimberly has the same blood type as theirs.
   Mays said he was reluctant to submit Kimberly to such a test
because of mere speculation. He said the Twiggs have presented no
evidence to show that Kimberly could be their daughter.
   When the whole situation began to unfold, Mays said he couldn't
believe it.
   ``I thought it was a terrible joke,'' he said today. ``It was
like a fairy tale. ... Only recently I've been honest enough with
myself to realize this isn't going to go away.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881026-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1303EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0608 10-26 0970</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0608,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Response Probably `Too Late'; Bush Buoyed by New Polls</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 5 grafs new with Bush comments; pick up 4th graf pvs bgng
``President Reagan...; delete final 2 grafs to shorten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis insisted today he is making ``real progress'' and
shrugged off a double-digit deficit in new polls. Republican George
Bush said his proposed capital gains tax cut is ``not a tax break
for the rich.''
   ``The pollsters are not going to call the election,'' Dukakis
said in a statement to reporters in Denver. ``It's people who are
going to be voting.''
   Dukakis met with Hispanic leaders in tossup Colorado before
traveling to Illinois.
   In Detroit, Bush defended his proposal to slash the capital gains
tax on profits from stocks, real estate and other assets from its
current level of 28 percent down to 15 percent. Dukakis has
denounced it as a tax break for the wealthy and said Bush personally
would reap a $22,000 advantage a year.
   ``It is not a tax break for the rich. It is a break for those who
want to have a job in this country and I am for it,'' Bush declared.
``Unfortunately, my opponent's only experience with business is
regulating it and taxing it.''
   President Reagan ventured into the Democratic stronghold of
Maryland and noted the Democrats' complaints about the negative tone
of the campaign.
   ``Well, I think they're squirming because George has shown
America how far outside the mainstream they really are,'' Reagan
said.
   Republican vice presidential candidate Dan Quayle, in Florida
campaigning for Senate candidate Connie Mack III, talked as though
the election were over. He noted the difficulty of a White House
that has to deal with an opposition-controlled Congress. ``When
you're in the minority, the majority controls the gavel. They're
able to set the agenda in Congress,'' Quayle said.
   With less than two weeks remaining until Election Day, Dukakis
insisted in a late-night television interview Tuesday that there was
still time for him to overtake front-runner Bush.
   But when asked shortly after the program about polls showing him
trailing by 13 and 14 percentage points, the Democratic nominee
simply replied, ``Forging ahead.''
   In the 90-minute interview on ABC's ``Nightline,'' questioner Ted
Koppel asked Dukakis what Bush had done to ``nail your hide to the
wall thus far.'' The Democratic nominee failed to challenge Koppel's
assessment of the White House race before answering the question.
   ``Two things,'' Dukakis said. ``The Bush campaign made a very
careful and deliberate decision way back in the spring to run a
tough, attacking, negative campaign. And they've been doing it ever
since and perhaps I responded too late, perhaps I should have been
out there attacking or counterattacking from the beginning.''
   He also criticized Republican advertising and charged Bush with
running a campaign ``loaded with distortion and misrepresentation
and falsehoods.''
   Earlier Tuesday, Bush defended his campaign ads against the
Dukakis attacks.
   ``Because he was trying to run away from his record, I have
factually pointed out where he stands on the record,'' Bush said
during a campaign stop in Akron, Ohio. ``And I am not going to be
deterred. I am going to keep doing that honestly, factually.''
   The vice president, targeting a must-win Dukakis state, told an
audience in Lima, Ohio, that the election is a referendum on peace
and prosperity and that Dukakis is too inexperienced to be president.
   ``We cannot gamble America's future on a president who hasn't had
one single day's experience in national defense matters or foreign
affairs,'' Bush said.
   Polls released Tuesday suggested that the Democratic ticket faces
a difficult task in its quest for the White House.
   A CBS News-New York Times survey of 1,287 probable voters showed
Bush leading Dukakis 54-41 percent while a Gallup poll of 815 likely
voters showed Bush up by 14 points, 53-39 percent.
   The CBS-Times poll was conducted Friday through Monday and had a
margin of error of three points. The Gallup survey was done Friday
through Sunday and had a four-point error margin.
   As part of their uphill fight, the Dukakis campaign released four
new TV ads which ask voters to imagine a world where children can
play without fear of drug dealers, where the elderly are no longer a
burden, where a single paycheck pays the bills and where America is
No. 1 in competition on foreign markets.
   All four ads end with the phrase, ``Dukakis-Bentsen. The best
America is yet to come.''
   The ads are scheduled to begin airing on Thursday in spot markets
around the country, said Dukakis spokeswoman Lorraine Voles.
   The Bush campaign also released an ad alleging that Dukakis
misled 62 million Americans when he denied during the last
presidential debate that he raided his state pension system to
balance the budget.
   The ad's narrator concludes: ``And Michael Dukakis says George
Bush is running a campaign of lies? Michael Dukakis is
unbelievable.''
   Bush aides said they did not know where or when the commercials
will air.
   In addition to advertising, the Dukakis campaign is filling the
airwaves with none other than Dukakis and Bentsen. The Democratic
nominee will appear on the ``CBS Evening News'' Thursday for a
14-minute interview with Dan Rather and also appear on NBC with
anchor Tom Brokaw for a series next week on the candidate's
positions.
   Bentsen is scheduled to appear on the CBS program tonight. The
Dukakis campaign also had bought five minutes of time on the network
Sunday night for a spot the Texas senator will likely tape today in
Los Angeles.
   Bentsen kept up his attack Tuesday on what he called GOP
distortions of the Democratic record.
   ``The kind of campaign these Republicans are waging would tear
the heart out of a democracy,'' he told a rally in Great Falls, Mont.
</TEXT>
