<DOCNO> AP881026-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Zambia     10-26 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zambia,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zambian President Expected to Win Re-Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER HEARING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zambians voted Wednesday in elections
expected to reaffirm support for the nation's founding father, whose
popularity remains high despite severe economic problems.
   President Kenneth Kaunda, who led the British colony to
independence Oct. 24, 1964, needed 51 percent of ballots cast to
serve another five years. Of Kenya's 7 million people, 2.6 million
are registered to vote.
   Also up for election were the 125 seats in the National Assembly.
Zambians had to decide from 609 candidates from the United National
Independence Party.
   Voters chose between two symbols _ picking an eagle if they
wanted to vote for Kaunda, or choosing a frog to vote against him.
This is to accommodate illiterate voters.
   The last election was held in October 1983, when Kaunda won his
fifth five-year term.
   Most observers believed that despite pressures for economic
reforms, most voters would cast their ballot for Kaunda.
   ``I will go by what the people say,'' said Kaunda, 64, after
casting his ballot. ``This is exactly what we fought for. It is the
meaning of independence.''
   He said the elections should inspire voteless people in South
Africa and in South-West Africa, or Namibia, which is ruled by South
Africa.
   The congress of the United National Independence Party has
routinely nominated Kaunda the sole candidate since independence,
although it is free to choose more than one. New elections are held
if the sole candidate loses.
   Analysts expected a low turnout for the sixth post-independence
elections, but long lines had formed outside some polling stations
in the capital, Lusaka, before voting began at 6 a.m.
   Rural Zambians went to the polls by bus, bicycle, tractor and on
foot. In some areas, voters paddled canoes to the booths. In the
Mpika district of Central province, where roads are impassable
because of heavy rains, voters were ferried by helicopters.
   But Zambian reporters in several rural areas said polling was
slow and there were small lines outside most booths.
   When Kaunda led Zambia to independence, his people enjoyed one of
the highest standards of living in Africa, thanks largely to high
world prices for copper which earns 90 percent of export income.
   But when prices slumped in the 1970s, a time when landlocked
Zambia had transformed from food exporter to importer, the nation's
fortunes changed. The foreign debt mounted and today stands at $5
billion.
   Most foreign donors have stopped helping Zambia since Kaunda last
year abandoned an economic recovery program proposed by the
International Monetary Fund.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881026-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1316EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-SuspectedNazi     10-26 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Suspected Nazi,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West German Ambassador Urged to Bring Suspected Nazi to Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York prosecutor on Wednesday urged West
German Ambassador Jurgen Ruhfus to help bring to justice a man who
fled the United States while awaiting deportation as a suspected
Nazi war criminal.
   Brooklyn District Attorney Elizabeth Holtzman said she told the
ambassador there was great concern in the United States that
Boleslav Maikovskis would ``slip through the cracks'' of the West
German judicial system.
   Maikovskis, 83, left the United States last year after the U.S.
Supreme Court ruled him eligible for deportation for his alleged
involvement in Nazi atrocities during World War II, including the
burning of a village in Latvia and the shooting of women and
children.
   In 1965, the Soviet Union sentenced Maikovskis to death in
absentia. He could have been deported to the Soviet Union, in the
wake of refusals in recent years by both Switzerland and West
Germany to take him, but former Attorney General Edwin Meese refused
to designate the Soviet Union as his destination.
   Holtzman said Ruhfus told her authorities in West Germany had
only found out that Maikovskis was living there several weeks ago
when the matter was first made public in the U.S. media.
   The Justice Department has also said it was unaware Maikovskis
fled the country for West Germany, where he has sought political
asylum.
   Holtzman said it was unclear to her whether local authorities in
the town of Dortmund knew of Maikovskis' presence and his suspected
Nazi past until the matter became public.
   Authorities in West Germany earlier this month detained
Maikovskis and launched an investigation of his past in connection
with the murder charges leveled against him by the Soviets.
   Holtzman indicated she believed Maikovskis had received some
assurances from West German authorities that he would be safe in
their country. ``Otherwise why would he go to a country that has
refused in the past to accept his deportation from the United
States?'' she said.
   West Germany and Switzerland both refused to accept Maikovskis
after the Justice Department initially ordered him deported in 1984.
   Meese refused to designate the Soviet Union as the country for
Maikovskis' deportation even though the Soviets had expressed great
interest in bringing him to trial.
   ``Meese violated the law by failing to act on the court's
determination that Maikovskis should be deported from the United
States,'' Holtzman said.
   The German ambassador promised to keep Holtzman informed of steps
being taken against Maikovskis and to convey to the Bonn government
``the strong interest here that Maikovskis not go unpunished,''
Holtzman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881026-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1321EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-KennedyAllegations     10-26 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kennedy Allegations,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Ex-convict Denies Involvement in JFK Assassination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British television program claimed three French
gangsters assassinated President John F. Kennedy on a contract from
U.S. organized crime, but French records show two of them were not
in Dallas on Nov. 22, 1963.
   One of the three men, Sauveur Pironti, also denied the allegation
in an interview published Wednesday by the Marseilles newspaper Le
Provencal.
   It quoted him as saying ``I was not in Dallas, but in the
military in Toulon,'' and said he displayed a military service
record showing he was based on a mine sweeper in Toulon from Oct.
16, 1962, to April 16, 1964.
   ``I believe at that time my friend Sarti was being held in
Baumettes (prison in Marseilles) and (Roger) Bocagnani was in prison
at Fort du Ha in Bordeaux,'' the newspaper quoted Pironti as saying.
   According to the two-hour Central Television program ``The Men
Who Killed Kennedy,'' broadcast Tuesday night, Lucien Sarti was was
shot to death in Mexico in 1972 and Bocagnani is believed to be
working in the Colombian cocaine trade.
   French Navy headquarters confirmed the dates of service in Toulon
and said Pironti, 46, could not have been in Dallas on the day of
the assassination. The Justice Ministry said Bocagnani was in a jail
cell in Marseille on that day.
   Kennedy was killed as he rode in a motorcade through Dallas. Lee
Harvey Oswald was charged with the shooting, but Jack Ruby shot and
killed him two days later. The Warren Commission said Oswald acted
alone in the assassination.
   There have been many theories over the years that Oswald was not
the killer or was part of a conspiracy in which assorted
organizations, governments and personalities were involved.
   Central Television, a company in Britain's commercial Independent
Television network, said its report was based on a four-year inquiry
by Steve Rivele, an American writer and researcher, and Nigel
Turner, the documentary's British director.
   Rivele said the three men were hired through organized crime
circles on the French Mediterranean island of Corsica, but the
program produced no direct evidence of a Corsican connection.
   According to Rivele, he got on the Corsican trail by interviewing
Christian David, a French drug smuggler held at the Leavenworth
federal prison in Kansas.
   In exchange for help in hiring an attorney, Rivele said, David
told him he was offered the contract and refused it, then gradually
revealed the identities of those involved.
   The American journalist said he persuaded a contact in the U.S.
Drug Enforcement Agency, not identified, to give him someone who
could corroborate David's story. He identified that man as Michel
Nicoli, a government witness living under a false identity.
   Nicoli, interviewed with his face obscured, said he heard Sarti,
Bocagnoni and Pironti were the killers in 1966, when he lived in
Buenos Aires. He said he believed it to be true but gave no
indication that he had direct evidence of their involvement.
   David's lawyer was interviewed and said the his client had given
him a sealed envelope to be opened only if he was freed.
   Le Provencal said Pironti, a Corsican, has lived in Marseilles
since his release four years ago after a prison term for drug
smuggling.
   It quoted him as saying he spoke for Sarti and Bocagnani, ``and I
can tell you that if they were in Marseille they would be with me
here tonight. This business ... is the most incredible misadventure
of my life.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881026-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1347EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Prisoners     10-26 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Prisoners,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group: East Germans Jailed 1,800 Political Prisoners in 12 Months</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Kohl, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany has imprisoned 1,800 political
prisoners in the past 12 months, a West Berlin watchdog group said
Wednesday.
   The Working Group August 13, which keeps tabs on trends in East
Germany, also said that of those imprisoned ``600 had been released
to resettle in West Germany.''
   The group is named after the date in 1961 when construction of
the Berlin Wall began.
   It said ``most of those imprisoned were accused of attempting to
flee the country, violation of state and social order, or unlawful
contacts and forming of mobs.''
   The report also said that 750,000 East Germans have applied to
leave the country for West Germany. So far this year, 20,000 people
had been permitted to resettle in the West, it said.
</TEXT>
