<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1646EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Stars&Stripes     10-26 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stars & Stripes,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Considering Civilians To Head `Stars & Stripes' Newspapers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department, bracing for charges of
censorship at the Stars & Stripes military newspapers, is debating a
significant shift in structure that would put civilian journalists
at the top of the masthead instead of military officers.
   Pentagon officials say no final decision has been made to ditch
the existing organizational system. But the officials say there
appears to be fairly uniform agreement ``that something has to be
done.''
   ``We don't want to fold these papers; there's nothing out there
to replace them,'' explained one official, who spoke only on
condition of anonymity. ``So you've got to consider ways to
strengthen editorial control and dampen charges of censorship.''
   The sources said Wednesday they expected a decision on the future
of the newspapers to be made soon _ perhaps within the next week _
because the Pentagon is facing a deadline for responding to a draft
study of the newspapers by the General Accounting Office.
   That report by Congress' watchdog agency, while still in
preliminary form, is described by officials who have read it as
quite critical of the newspapers' operation.
   It finds ``overwhelming evidence'' of military censorship at one
of the two papers, the Pacific edition of Stars & Stripes, one
source said.
   ``The best way to respond to the GAO would be to tell them we're
already changing things around,'' another source said.
   The GAO investigation was launched early this year at the behest
of Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., who persuaded Congress to demand
an inquiry into `allegations of censorship by military commanders of
the Department of Defense newspaper, Stars and Stripes.''
   In demanding the investigation, Proxmire blasted the Pentagon for
sending soldiers overseas to protect freedom while denying them
``one of the most important freedoms that we have in this country _
that is the right to a free press under the First Amendment.''
   Although frequently referred to as one newspaper, the Stars and
Stripes is published in two separate editions by largely autonomous
bureaus in West Germany and Japan. Designed to serve as the
``hometown paper'' for American military personnel posted overseas,
the papers have a long history that dates to publication in France
during World War I.
   The papers are staffed by military as well as civilian
journalists, but both papers are led by an officer who holds the
title of commander and editor-in-chief. Those officers, in turn,
must answer to the heads of the European and Pacific commands.
   The Pentagon describes the papers as ``authorized, but unofficial
publications.'' Both operate under a charter to provide ``a free
flow of news and information ... without censorship or news
management.''
   In reality, however, reporters who have worked for the papers say
they always walk a tightrope between reporting the news and
satisfying military commanders worried about upsetting the host
country.
   Examples of the problem are among those that prompted Proxmire to
demand an investigation. There have been persistent reports the
Pacific edition of Stars & Stripes killed stories on the results of
AIDS testing and the fact that some military wives were working in
Japan as bar hostesses.
   According to the sources, the GAO reviewed those and other cases
of alleged censorship, then asked an advisory panel from the Sigma
Delta Chi professional journalism fraternity to help characterize
the handling of each story as either typical news judgment or
censorship.
   ``SDX didn't characterize all of the GAO cases as censorship, and
quite frankly that lends credibility to the report,'' one source
said. ``But there is overwhelming evidence of censorship,
overwhelming.''
</TEXT>
