<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Kahane     10-26 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kahane,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kahane Gets Court OK To Make U.S. Speaking Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge ruled Wednesday that
Brooklyn-born Rabbi Meir Kahane can travel here from Israel for a
speaking tour while he challenges a government finding that he had
renounced his U.S. citizenship.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker ordered the State
Department not to interfere with Kahane's plan to enter the United
States early Thursday to begin a three-week speaking tour at a
suburban Washington synagogue.
   Parker made the ruling at the conclusion of a 90-minute hearing
during which an attorney for Kahane argued that the founder of the
militant Jewish Defense League only renounced his U.S. citizenship
to retain his seat in the Knesset, the Israeli parliament.
   Attorney Nathan Lewin maintained that Kahane only signed
renunciation papers when faced with the ``Hobson's choice'' of
losing his seat in the Knesset or losing his American citizenship.
   Kahane, also an Israeli citizen, renounced his American
citizenship to comply with a new Israeli law that prohibits Knesset
members from being citizens of other nations.
   Kahane sent a telegram to withdraw the renunciation after the
Israeli Supreme Court ruled his anti-Arab political party was racist
and therefore ineligible to partcipate in the Nov. 1 parliamentary
election.
   The law requiring Kahane to renounce his U.S. citizenship to keep
his parliamentary seat was ``a figurative gun at his head,'' Lewin
said.
   ``Did he cross his fingers when he signed the oath?'' the judge
said.
   Lewin replied that Kahane issued a public statement explaining
the reason for his renunciation and filed a written version with
U.S. Embassy officials when he signed the oath.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael L. Martinez argued that Kahane
``knew exactly what he was doing. It was a voluntary choice.''
   He cited several court cases in which Americans who had renounced
their nationality to qualify for jobs in foreign countries were not
allowed later to reclaim their citizenship.
   ``He has affirmatively gone in to renounce his citizenship. Not
being a citizen anymore, he has no right to come into this country
on a U.S. passport,'' Martinez said. ``He knew what the consequences
of his choice were _ therefore it was voluntary.''
   Martinez noted that because Kahane had signed the incorrect form
on Aug. 16 he returned to the Tel Aviv embassy in September and
``for a second time renounced his citizenship by filling out the
correct papers.''
   Lewin said Kahane should not be stripped of his citizenship
rights until the court rules on whether his renunciation was valid.
   ``They don't have a constitutional right to take something away
from him as precious as citizenship without an adversary hearing,''
Lewin said.
   He accused the State Department of trying to muzzle Kahane, whose
extremist views have been the focus of controversy both here and in
Israel.
   ``Because Meir Kahane is a notorious figure and people know about
him, the State Department is taking a strong line,'' Lewin said.
``They don't want him here.''
   ``Whether they agreed or disagree with him, this is a country
where he has a right to come and speak,'' Lewin said.
   Four years ago, a federal judge rejected the State Department's
claim that Kahane had renounced his citizenship by taking a seat in
the Knesset.
  
</TEXT>
