<HEAD>Quayle Tells Miami Youth `We're Happy, Tomorrow We'll Be Happier'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle courted voters in the pro-Republican
Cuban community of Florida on Wednesday, stumped for a GOP Senate
candidate and told high school students that ``today we're happy and
tomorrow we're going to be even happier.''
   The Republican vice presidential nominee touted the prospects for
a rosy future at a space and missile contractor's plant in Tampa,
Fla., before a heavily Cuban audience at Miami High School and at an
outdoor rally in the ``Little Havana'' section of Miami.
   Quayle was cheered loudly at the high school, especially when he
mentioned the school's band and basketball and football teams, in a
rambling speech about education, drugs and the future.
   The students buzzed when the 41-year-old Indiana senator said
prenatal care and adoption should be options if a teen-age girl
becomes pregnant. He said he and GOP presidential candidate George
Bush were committed to good jobs and education.
   ``A job is opportunity. A job is hope. A job is a chance of being
able to go out and produce for yourself and your family,'' Quayle
said.
   ``And that future, which is your future, and I want you to join
with me and George Bush in working for that future _ that future
where people are looking up, that future where people are smiling,
that future where people are working, that future where people are
producing ...
   ``What you do in this city in this state at this time,'' he said,
``that future, because of your work, because of your commitment to
the cause, will be better, will be brighter. We'll let the sunshine
come in to shine on us because today we're happy and tomorrow we'll
be even happier.''
   Quayle later modified his usual stump speech with one-liners
intended to appeal to the anti-communist sentiments of his audience
outside the Little Havana Activities and Nutrition Centers of Dade
County.
   He promised that he and Bush ``will invest in our people, quality
education, job opportunities, family, neighborhood and, yes, a thing
we call America. A thing we call America because this country is
still the beacon of hope for millions around the world.''
   Quayle began the day at a fund-raising breakfast in Tampa for
Republican Rep. Connie Mack III, who is locked in a close battle
against Rep. Buddy MacKay, D-Fla., for the Senate seatbeing vacated
by Lawton Chiles Jr., a Democrat.
   ``I know that Florida is going to vote for George Bush on Nov.
8,'' Quayle said. But he said Bush had asked him to deliver the
message that he wants Mack as ``a partner in the U.S. Senate.''
   GOP officials said Quayle will be making more such appearances on
behalf of Senate candidates in New Jersey, Ohio and Wisconsin.
   Reporters asked Quayle about a new CBS News_New York Times poll
showing that he is the least popular among the four candidates on
the Republican and Democratic tickets this fall.
   Quayle replied that Dukakis is ``the person that is unpopular in
America ... he's dragging his ticket down.''
   As for whether his presence on the GOP ticket might be hurting
Bush, the senator said, ``As a matter of fact when we got on this
ticket, we were double digits behind, and we're doing quite well.''
