<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChristaPlanetarium     10-26 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Christa Planetarium,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christa Planetarium Underway</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID TIRRELL-WYSOCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christa McAuliffe's husband and parents
Wednesday helped break ground for a pyramid-shaped planetarium
honoring the teacher killed along with six other astronauts aboard
the space shuttle Challenger.
   ``She was the most humble of persons. She would be embarrassed to
have her name on a building,'' said Steven McAuliffe, who said his
wife believed she was representing all teachers in the space program.
   About 1,000 people gathered on frost-covered grass at the New
Hampshire Technical Institute: teachers and school officials from
Concord as well as children and other residents caught up in the
excitement that led to Challenger's flight and the grief that
followed its destruction on Jan. 28, 1986.
   The $2.6 million planetarium is expected to be dedicated in
January 1990. During the day the glass exterior will reflect the
clouds _ at night the moon and stars.
   The key feature will be a computer projection system that
simulates space travel and shows the sky's changes over 2 million
years.
   Visitors under the 40-foot dome will experience the sights of
moving through space or view the night sky as if they were part of a
lunar expedition and watch the Earth rise.
   The project was selected from about 100 suggestions for a state
memorial, a choice McAuliffe praised. ``I can't imagine a more
appropriate, a more fitting memorial,'' he said.
   Her parents, Ed and Grace Corrigan of Framingham, Mass., wielded
shovels in a line of dignitaries.
   ``She would be very pleased that something like this is ongoing
and such a positive thing for education,'' Mrs. Corrigan said. ``I
just wish she were here with us.''
</TEXT>
