<DOCNO> AP881026-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1726EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Legislature     10-26 0880</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Legislature,0905</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Soviet Faces Budget Issue Thursday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet parliament will confront a dilemma when
it convenes Thursday: the need to slash an enormous budget deficit
while soothing public anger over empty store shelves.
   The 1,500 deputies of the Supreme Soviet typically sit through
hours of numbing speeches in their two-day autumn session before
unanimously approving the annual budget and development plan.
   This time, with the example of June's vociferous Communist Party
conference telling them glasnost has ripped the economic veil,
Western diplomats predict the deputies may actually offer some
candid comments on the Kremlin's economic plan.
   They also might comment on Gorbachev's proposal for
multiple-candidate elections to a new Congress of People's Deputies,
although the reform laws published last weekend are scheduled for
consideration at a separate Supreme Soviet meeting in November.
   Thursday's session will be the first to deal openly with what the
government acknowledges is a serious budget deficit. Tass, the
official news agency, says that problem ``was passed over in silence
previously.''
   Some analysts say that deficit could be as high as $100 billion
due to a combination of problems ranging from the cleanup of the
Chernobyl nuclear disaster to lost revenues from curtailed vodka
sales.
   Simultaneously, the Soviet Union is trying to fill its
chronically empty food shelves and stop the periodic disappearance
of everyday necessities. Among items unavailable in most Moscow
stores are laundry detergent, razor blades and deodorant.
   The leadership already has made one hard decision: investment in
heavy industry will be sharply cut back in 1989 in order to finance
purchase of more consumer goods. When President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
visited the Siberian city of Krasnayarsk last month, he was besieged
by angry citizens complaining of shortages.
   For the Soviet Union, where heavy industry has been the favored
child for decades, and where Josef Stalin once seriously argued that
chronic shortages of consumer goods fueled economic growth, this is
a radical turnabout.
   The Tass report says the 1989 plan calls for 6 percent growth in
consumer goods versus 2.5 percent in heavy industry. Western
economists point out that the Soviet Union may never achieve these
goals, but the comparative projections imply a dramatic shift in
underlying investment.
   For example, a recently completed tractor factory is being
converted to passenger car production.
   Still, the tasks are daunting. To fulfill Gorbachev's promise
that every family will have its own apartment by the year 2000, he
needs a crash construction program in an industry legendary for
endless delays and careless workmanship.
   Even those with sufficient space may find themselves in the 10
percent of Moscow's housing that lacks hot water and central heat in
a city where the temperature drops below freezing six months out of
the year.
   Gorbachev's best hope for solving the shortages is found in the
incredible waste now blamed on central planning. For example, at a
recent agricultural conference, a farmer complained to Gorbachev
that he was left without fuel at harvest time because too much oil
has been sold for hard currency to buy grain.
   Gorbachev himself said more than 25 percent of the nation's
harvest is lost by rotting en route to the stores.
   For cutting the budget, Gorbachev appears to be relying on his
plan to shift to more productive work as much as half of the bloated
bureaucracy, a mass that numbers somewhere between 18 million and 30
million people.
   He also is counting on modern _ and largely Western _ technology
to increase productivity in manufacturing. In the first nine months
of this year, 1 million factory jobs were eliminated, a statistic
announced with pride in a nation that once pointed to layoffs as
being among the horrors of capitalism.
   The government statistician who revealed that figure said
one-third of those workers retired and the other two-thirds found
positions in service industries or the new private cooperatives.
   The looming question in solving the deficit, however, is the same
one facing the United States: Will the Soviet Union cut its defense
budget?
   The West, not to mention the Soviet public, may never know.
Soviet military expenditures are scattered throughout the national
budget, and the official line item is a fraction of the true total,
estimated by the CIA at about 15 percent of the total Soviet economy.
   All these challenges are coming at a time of radicial change in
the structure of the Soviet economy.
   For example, the development plan before the legislature calls
for most new machinery, textiles, ceramics and shoes to be sold on
an open market for the first time in more than half a century. The
ministries for machine-building and light industry, which
traditionally set quotas for those goods, would control only a
fraction of production.
   Western diplomats, speaking on the condition they not be
identified, said such issues could produce fireworks at the usually
staid Supreme Soviet.
   In the four weeks since he slammed through a reorganization of
the ruling Politburo and Central Committee of the Communist Party,
Gorbachev and his allies have hinted they intend to press for even
more radical change.
   A return to family farming, conversion of even major industry to
private cooperatives and making the ruble convertible on
international currency markets are among the proposals being
discussed.
</TEXT>
