<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0668 10-26 0816</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0668,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Shrugs Off Polls, Raps GOP `Baloney' on Gun Controls</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 12 grafs new with late developments and rewording for
transition; picks up pvs 6th graf bgng, Gallup polls; SUBS pvs 20th
(last) graf to CORRECT misspelling, reading Romer instead Roemer.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PUEBLO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis campaigned among Hispanic voters Wednesday, shrugged off
discouraging new polls and accused Republicans of uttering ``a lot
of baloney'' about gun controls.
   Dukakis met with Hispanic leaders in Denver the morning after a
90-minute appearance on ABC-TV's ``Nightline'' program, then flew to
Pueblo in southern Colorado for a large outdoor rally.
   ``The pollsters are not going to call this election,'' Dukakis
said. ``It's people that are going to be voting. We have 13
important days ahead of us.''
   Dukakis again accused Republican rival George Bush and his allies
of producing ``noise pollution'' and distorting the Massachusetts
governor's record on such issues as gun controls.
   ``They're afraid if the smog clears from all the noise pollution
that they have been laying down, that people will realize that they
don't understand average American families,'' the Democratic nominee
said.
   ``Yes, it has been a campaign of distortion and
misrepresentation,'' he said. ``The latest one is gun control.''
   Dukakis has found himself on the defensive about gun controls
during nearly ever visit to the West, where the National Rifle
Association has been broadcasting commercials charging that Dukakis
would disarm gun owners.
   Dukakis says he does not oppose gun ownership by hunters,
sportsmen and homeowners protecting their lives and property, but he
wants to deny them to criminals.
   ``I hope you'll take that word back to your friends and
neighbors. These charges are a lot of baloney, and I hope you'll
tell them that,'' he told about 4,000 people outside the Pueblo
courthouse as he stood next to a large hot-air balloon.
   ``Jack Kennedy said, here in Colorado in 1960, `No attacks, no
attempt to discredit me, no attempt to discredit us will keep us
from speaking up for a stronger America','' Dukakis said, evoking
the name of the late president who defeated Richard Nixon in that
election.
   For the second straight day, Dukakis was greerted by dismal polls
published by leading newspapers.
   A CBS News-New York Times poll placed him 13 percentage points
behind Bush, a further decline in his standing since their Oct. 13
debate in Los Angeles.
   Gallup polls showed Dukakis trailing by 14 points among likely
voters. An earlier Los Angeles Times poll put him nine points down
in must-win California.
   Dukakis took no questions from reporters Wednesday, but referred
to the latest bad news polls during his breakfast meeting with
Hispanic members of Congress and community leaders in Denver.
   ``I'm inspired and encouraged as I always am when I meet with
you,'' he told them. ``We go forth now from Denver to Pueblo and on
across this country to work, to campaign and to win. And we're going
to win.''
   Dukakis aides sought to put the best face possible on the poll
results. They said the CBS-Times poll did not match their own
findings, but some advisers privately did not dispute the California
poll.
   In addition, a Denver Post poll showed him trailing by double
digits in Colorado. Charlie Baker, Dukakis' national field director,
said internal campaign polling showed voters ``trending toward us in
the last few days.''
   He gave no specifics, but said the national contest ``is very
close.''
   In the past week, Dukakis has devoted much of his time to
attacking what he calls lies and distortions by the Bush campaign
and the vice president's criticism of his record on defense, crime
and other issues.
   Baker said that approach was working, the poll results
notwithstanding.
   ``It's clear this campaign of lies and distortions is catching up
with these guys,'' Baker said. ``Our tracking polls showed for the
first time when you ask who is responsible for the negative
campaign, they say George Bush.''
   Dukakis received warmly enthusiastic expressions of support from
the Hispanic leaders.
   Rep. Albert Bustamante, D-Texas, praised Dukakis using the words
``liberal'' and ``technocrat,'' which sometimes are attached to the
Democratic nominee in derision.
   He said Dukakis doesn't smile a lot and isn't a backslapper like
most politicians. ``He's a technocrat. He understands management,''
Bustamante said.
   ``As far as being a liberal in 1988, if liberalism means we care
about children, and we are about the elderly, and we care about the
environment, and we care about family farms ... then I am for
Michael Dukakis, the liberal of 1988.''
   Bustamante said that if there is a heavy voter turnout among
Hispanics on Nov. 8 _ 70 percent or more _ they could swing a close
election in Dukakis' favor.
   Gov. Roy Romer said Dukakis faces an uphill battle in Colorado.
``It's a pretty big hill,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
