<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DCHomicides     10-26 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DC Homicides,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug-Related Turf Battles Push Washington Toward Homicide Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increasingly violent turf battles involving
drug dealers have pushed the nation's capital to the brink of a
homicide record this year, the city's police chief said Wednesday.
   With less than three months remaining in 1988, 285 people have
been killed in the District of Columbia, two deaths short of the
record for one year set in 1969. There were 227 homicides in
Washington last year.
   ``We don't have organized crime in this city, so we have a lot of
young entrepreneurs fighting for turf,'' Police Chief Maurice T.
Turner said.
   ``There is just more and more fighting over where the drugs are
to be sold,'' Turner told a news conference at police headquarters.
   Police estimate that 60 percent of this year's killings have been
drug-related, compared with 1986 when 33 percent of the homicides
involved drugs.
   The demand for crack, a highly addictive cocaine derivative, has
fueled the accelerating homicide rate, Turner said.
   ``This is one of the last major cities in this country to have an
infusion of crack,'' Turner said. ``When crack arrived in other
cities, like New York, murder rates went up there too.''
   Turner called for increased federal efforts to stem the flow of
drugs into the United States.
   ``The federal government must increase its commitment to
interdict drugs at our borders and port cities,'' Turner said.
``Unless we intensify our efforts there, the drug problem will
continue to flourish.''
   More than 45,000 people have been arrested since the district
initiated a tough anti-drug program in 1986, but Turner said that
for each drug dealer arrested, another is ready to step forward to
take his place.
   ``People are willing to take the risk of going to jail in order
to make large sums of money,'' Turner said. ``You can make a million
dollars a year selling drugs. They don't have skills. Most of them
are high-school dropouts. What would you do?''
   Although the city's police force has been cut from 5,100 in 1977
to its current level of 3,800, Turner said more police officers
would not necessarily stem the drug trade. Instead, he said, having
more officers on the streets would simply produce more arrests _ and
more crowding in the city's overcrowded jails.
   Turner called on parents and teachers in the nation's capital to
help educate their children about the perils of drug use. He said
casual drug users, as well as drug dealers, are both part of the
problem.
   Speeding addicts through drug treatment programs also will help
reduce the city's appetite for narcotics, Turner said. Drug addicts
must now wait an average of three weeks or longer to enter
city-funded drug treatment programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
