<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SaudiKilling     10-26 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Saudi Killing,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Islamic Group Claims Responsibility For Killing Saudi Embassy
Employee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ZEYNEP ALEMDAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Islamic extremists claimed responsibility
Wednesday for the killing of a Saudi Arabian diplomat, and the Saudi
ambassador said his embassy had received more than 100 threatening
letters before the attack.
   Police speculated a sole gunman shot Abdulgani Bedawi as the
Saudi Arabian Embassy employee returned to his Ankara apartment
Tuesday night, said Ankara Gov. Saffet Arikan Beduk.
   In Beirut, an extremist group calling itself Islamic Jihad in
Hijaz said it killed Bedawi to avenge the execution of four of its
followers.
   The claim came in a typewritten Arabic statement from the
pro-Iranian Shiite group, whose previous statements detailed
underground activity against the Saudi monarchy. The statement was
delivered to a Western news agency in Beirut.
   There was no immediate response to the Islamic group's claim in
Ankara.
   The Saudi ambassador, Abdulaziz Khojah, said Bedawi had been the
embassy's telex operator for the last six years and held diplomatic
status.
   Khojah said he ruled out robbery or personal conflict in the
killing.
   He added that the embassy had received more than 100 threatening
letters written in Turkish during the Moslem pilgrimage season this
summer.
   Without elaborating, the ambassador said: ``I don't believe the
Turks have anything to do with the incident even though the letters
were in Turkish.''
   Saudi Arabia restricted the number of Moslems who could visit the
country during the pilgrimage season this year according to each
Moslem nation's population.
   The decision came after a riot by Iranians during the 1987
pilgrimage to Mecca that killed more than 400 Iranians.
   Saudi Arabia broke diplomatic ties with Iran in April, listing as
reasons the clash in Mecca and an attack on the Saudi Embassy in
Tehran.
   A Turkish official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
Saudi officials had not requested extra protection for embassy
personnel.
   Beduk said police had no clues on the identity of the assailant
but believed a sole gunman killed Bedawi. He did not elaborate.
   Neighbors reported hearing no gunshots, raising the possibility a
silencer was used.
</TEXT>
