<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Libya     10-26 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Libya,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Counterterrorism Adviser Concerned About Libyan Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top counterterrorism official in the U.S.
government said Wednesday he was concerned that Libya might give
chemical weapons to terrorists.
   Ambassador L. Paul Bremer said that while there is no evidence
that Libya intends to arm terrorists with chemical weapons, there
are reasons to fear it might.
   CIA Director William Webster said Tuesday that Libya's chemical
weapons plant was the largest detected by his agency anywhere in the
world.
   Webster refused to say whether the facility was operational, but
other officials have said Libya is on the verge of production.
   ``They have no record of restraint,'' Bremer said in an interview
Wednesday. ``We're concerned, and we think others should be too.''
   Libya, which appeared to suspend its support for terrorist groups
following the U.S. aerial bombing of Tripoli in April 1986, has
resumed its involvement in international terrorism over the past
year, Bremer said.
   The United States has accused Libya of sponsoring attacks against
U.S. Information Agency offices in Costa Rica, Colombia and Peru, as
well as a club frequented by American servicemen in Naples, Italy.
Five people were killed in the Naples attack earlier this year.
   Specifically, U.S. officials accuse Libya of backing the
Palestinian Abu Nidal group, the Irish Republican Army and the
Japanese Red Army.
   Bremer said ``Libya has a track record of providing lethal
weapons to terrorists.''
   He said Libya provided the weapons for the Abu Nidal attacks in
December 1985 at the Rome and Vienna airports, as well as the
Palestinian faction's attack on the City of Poros cruise liner off
the Greek coast last July.
   Libya also sent Soviet-made SA-7 anti-aircraft missiles and
Semtech explosives to the Irish Republican Army, Bremer said. One
shipload of these weapons was intercepted off the French coast last
November.
</TEXT>
