<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Pill     10-26 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Pill,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company to Suspend Distribution of Abortion Pill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company will stop distributing a pill to induce
abortions because of ``an outcry of opinion at home and abroad,''
officials said Wednesday.
   Some company sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said it
received threats of a boycott against their products, especially
from the United States.
   The move was hailed by Archbishop Albert Decourtray, head of
France's conference of Roman Catholic bishops.
   ``I hope that this withdrawal is due to moral considerations and
not to other reasons stemming from passion or violence,'' he said in
Lourdes, where the conference is meeting.
   In a speech to the conference, Decourtray said the drug
represented a ``serious threat, a new step in the everyday
acceptance of abortion.''
   Opponents of abortion used authorization of the drug to resurrect
the philosophical battle and repeat their long-standing positions.
   The pharmaceutical company, Roussel Uclaf, said the decision to
stop worldwide distribution of the highly effective pill, known as
RU 486, came in response to the ``outcry of public opinion at home
and abroad'' against the drug.
   The pill is an anti-hormone that works against the female hormone
progesterone, which is vital to a normal pregnancy. The new drug
blocks implantation of the fertilized egg in the uterine wall.
   RU 486 is about 80 percent effective when used alone. With a
second product called sulprotone, or prostaglandine E, it is more
than 95 percent effective.
   The new drug is not a do-it-yourself, morning-after pill that can
be purchased at the supermarket and taken at home. It must be used
under supervision of medical specialists in a hospital.
   On Sept. 23, French Health Minister Claude Evin authorized
prescription of the drug subject to strict conditions. It was
delivered on an experimental basis to about 100 hospitals where
abortions are performed.
   The government decision gave Roussel Uclaf, which invested much
money in developing the drug, the green light to put it on the
market. The product already had been approved by the Chinese
government.
   Officials at Roussel, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the company had received threats of boycott against all its
products, ``especially from abroad and especially from the United
States.''
   Abortion has been legal in France, a predominantly Roman Catholic
country, since 1975. Evin said that authorization of RU 486 in no
way changed existing French law on abortions and that they still
would be carried out under strict legal conditions.
   Dr. Arlette Geslin, Roussel's director of medical relations, said
company officials were not suspending distribution of the drug
because of any harmful side effects found in testing.
   ``That is not the case,'' she said. ``And if it had been, we
would have said it was the factor that motivated our decision.''
   Roussel Uclaf is part of the giant West German chemical group
Hoescht, which has the majority share. The French government has a
36 percent share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881026-0151 </DOCNO>
