<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Oxford     10-26 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oxford,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oxford Launches American-style Appeal for Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oxford University launched a U.S.-style,
worldwide appeal Wednesday for more than $380 million to help
overcome a funding crunch that school officials blame mostly on
government cutbacks.
   ``Oxford was built on private philanthropy until about 1920, then
forgot how to do it,'' said Henry Drucker, director of the campaign.
``So we have to go back to the United States and, in a sense, learn
what we taught them in the first place.''
   The ancient school, which already has gained pledges of $90
million in its $387 million drive, will ask alumni and companies to
help bolster its $10 million endowment, refill the nearly 10 percent
of its faculty posts left vacant, and support other projects.
   ``We aim to be a trailblazer and change the climate of opinion
where corporations realize they should be supporting universities
(as they do) in the United States,'' said Vice Chancellor Sir
Patrick Neill.
   About 35 students mounted a protest against the campaign, saying
Oxford should have pressured the government harder before asking for
private support, said university spokeswoman Anne Lonsdale. About 25
other students demonstrated nearby in support of the appeal.
   The five-year drive will include not only fundraising letters but
also the university's first alumni magazine, ``Oxford Today,'' which
was mailed Wednesday. The campaign will have an office in New York
and possibly Tokyo.
   The university, which received its first charter in 1213, has
left 122 of its 1,420 faculty posts vacant as part of a retrenchment
program brought on by an 11 percent cut in government funding for
1986-1991.
</TEXT>
