<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0127</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito Given More Blood After Difficult Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palace doctors gave Emperor Hirohito almost a half
pint more blood Wednesday after a setback the day before in
five-week efforts to help him regain his health.
   The 87-year-old monarch remained in stable condition, palace
officials said.
   Hirohito, who took power in 1926 and is the world's
longest-reigning monarch, took to bed Sept. 19 after internal
hemorrhaging. Domestic media have reported he has cancer, but palace
officials have refused to comment on the reports.
   The doctors gave Hirohito 0.42 pints of blood in a transfusion
Wednesday to counter his anemia. They administered 1.68 pints in two
emergency transfusions Tuesday after a large loss of blood caused
his blood pressure to plummet.
</TEXT>
