<DOCNO> AP881026-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1949EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SoccerRiot     10-26 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soccer Riot,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Defense Motion on Public Reading of File</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Wednesday refused a request
to read in court the 48,000-page file related to a soccer riot that
killed 39 people.
   Judge Pierre Verlynde also refused to give free copies to lawyers
defending those charged in the case.
   Some of the lawyers for the 26 Britons charged with involuntary
manslaughter threatened to abandon the trial after the ruling, but
they later returned.
   Verlynde said that parts of the court file specifically
concerning each defendant could be read in court when appropriate.
The reading of the full file would have taken several months.
   Television footage of the riots at the 1985 European Champions'
Cup at Heysel Stadium showed that British fans tore down a fence
separating them from Italian fans and charged them. In the panic
that followed, 39 fans died, including 34 Italians, and more than
500 were injured.
   The Britons were extradited to Belgium last year after they were
identified from the TV footage.
   Since Oct. 18, proceedings have been dominated by legal wrangling
over whether the defense could have free copies of the court file to
study at home.
   Copies of the file can be studied in a court office and the trial
has already been postponed half a year to allow the defense more
time to better prepare their case.
   But since the reopening of the trial Oct. 18, the defense has
continued to insist on more copies.
   Each of the Britons facer up to 10 years in jail.
   Along with the Britons, two Belgian police officers and a former
Belgian soccer federation chairman are accused of doing a poor job
of organizing security at the match. They face up to two years in
jail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
