<DOCNO> AP881026-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1954EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     10-26 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Industry Minister Calls for Quick End to Meat Rationing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new industry minister called Wednesday
for a quick end to meat rationing, and he said the market must
determine prices.
   Meat and gasoline are the only items still rationed since the
government introduced widespread rationing in 1980-81.
   The new minister, Mieczyslaw Wilczek, said he has always
maintained that it was ``abnormal'' that there is food rationing in
a country that has 1.25 acres of land per capita.
   ``We want to lift rationing as soon as possible,'' he said. ``We
must be careful with meat prices because we burned ourselves a few
times with it. That's not the way. The market should decide how much
ham costs.''
   Under rationing, each person gets 5{ pounds of meat a month,
except manual laborers, such as miners and steelworkers who receive
nearly 10 pounds. Meat also can be bought without ration cards at
private meat shops where the price is about three to four times as
much as meat bought with the cards.
   Wilczek, a wealthy private businessman and member of the
Communist Party, outlined his views to improve Poland's ailing
economy at his first news conference since parliament confirmed him
as Industry Minister on Oct. 14.
   Before joining the government, Wilczek was co-owner with foreign
investors of a feed concentrate company, but he has sold his share
worth $215,000, he said in an interview with the Express Wieczorny
newspaper this month.
   Wilczek's wealth and private-sector experience have aroused wide
interest in Poland, and he is seen as Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F.
Rakowski's most innovative appointment in the new cabinet.
   The previous government resigned Sept. 19 after fierce criticism
for mishandling the party-approved economic reform program and
Rakowski, the former party propaganda chief, was approved as the new
prime minister Sept. 27.
   In the past, the government has favored heavy industry,
subsidizing inefficient industries such as steel, shipbuilding and
coal production, and neglected production of consumer goods and
service sectors.
   But the Rakowski government has decided to put priority on the
development of agriculture, housing and environmental protection
sectors of the economy and big factories will have to tighten their
belts to survive, Wilczek said.
   ``There are major industrial companies that have negative yield.
I understand that as soon as possible those companies must be closed
down.''
   Wilczek singled out the shipbuilding industry as a target for
restructuring. The government has been considering closing the Lenin
Shipyard in Gdansk, where the Solidarity trade union was born,
because it is considered unprofitable.
   ``Perhaps fewer and fewer shipyards would make for more efficient
shipyards,'' Wilczek said, without specifying which ones might be
eliminated.
   He also said that one solution to Poland's economic problems
would be to facilitate the creation of small enterprises, especially
service and commercial operations.
   Laws and rules which hinder the development of light industry
will be changed to make it easier for entrepreneurs to do business,
he said.
   Reviving the economy is one of the major challenges facing the
government. Inflation is 60 percent, and the foreign debt stands at
around $40 billion.
</TEXT>
