<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Kissinger-Dukakis     10-26 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kissinger-Dukakis,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kissinger Says Dukakis Lacks Foreign Policy Grasp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union would probably rather see Vice
President George Bush elected president because he would be far more
predictable than Democrat Michael Dukakis, former Secretary of State
Henry A. Kissinger said Wednesday.
   A Dukakis victory ``would bring about so many uncertainties and
so much confusion,'' Kissinger said at a National Press Club
luncheon. Kissinger also said he has a higher regard for Republican
vice presidential nominee Dan Quayle than the public perception of
him.
   Based on contact he has had with Quayle in the Indiana senator's
role on the Armed Services Committee, Kissinger said that Quayle
knows a ``great deal'' about arms control.
   ``In the area of foreign policy, he has a good basis together
with the experience he will undoubtedly gain as vice president,''
Kissinger said.
   Kissinger, who served in the Nixon-Ford administrations, said
that Dukakis has a 1960s view of the role of American power.
   ``I think he's deeply distrustful of American power,'' Kissinger
said. ``Even when he supports this or that weapons system, it does
not form part of any coherent strategy.''
   ``I really believe that Gov. Dukakis does not have the grasp of
foreign policy to deal with the issues,'' Kissinger said.
</TEXT>
