<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Church     10-26 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Church,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jaruzelski Meets Primate in Ancient Capital of Gniezo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski and
Roman Catholic primate Cardinal Jozef Glemp met Wednesday at a
church palace in the medieval capital city of Gniezno, church and
state officials said.
   Jaruzelski, first secretary of the Polish United Workers
(Communist) Party, was met Glemp at a church palace in Gniezno and
toured the city's 14th century Gothic cathedral.
   The small city in central Poland, 145 miles west of Warsaw, is
the original capital of Poland and the seat of Christianity in the
country, dating back more than 1,000 years. Glemp is archbishop of
Gniezno and Warsaw.
   There was no announcement of the topics of the Jaruzelski-Glemp
talks, the latest in a series of meetings between the two in recent
years.
   But the meeting coincided with difficulties over the convening of
talks between the authorities and opposition on Poland's future. The
talks originally were to have begun last week but the government has
raised objections to two of the proposed delegates of the banned
Solidarity trade union.
   The church has strongly promoted dialogue between officials and
Solidarity, and the leader of the Catholic Club of Intelligentsia in
Warsaw, Andrzej Stelmachowski, has been a key figure in attempting
to set up the talks.
   The meeting also came after church sources at the Vatican said
the Polish government recently offered to sign a concordat giving a
legal basis for church activities in Poland in exchange for
establishment of full diplomatic relations between Poland and the
Holy See.
   The corcordat would replace an agreement that existed between the
church and Poland's government before World War II which was never
renewed after introduction of communist rule.
</TEXT>
