<DOCNO> AP881026-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1958EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-LatinSummit     10-26 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Latin Summit,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latin American Presidents to Discuss Regional Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PUNTA DEL ESTE, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The presidents of seven South
America countries arrived Wednesday to seek common positions on
strife in Central America that has resisted peace efforts.
   The leaders of the countries, known as the Group of Eight, also
will discuss drug trafficking and foreign debt at their sessions
Thursday.
   Panama, the eighth member of the group, was suspended after Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, the nation's military leader, ousted
President Eric Delvalle.
   Conflict in Central America is ``like a red light within a world
... tending toward the solution of regional conflicts,'' Argentina's
undersecretary for Latin American affairs, Alberto Ferrari
Etcheberry, said before the meeting.
   Pointing to the Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan, the end of
Iraq's war with Iran, and signs that Angola's civil war may be
winding down, Etcheberry said, ``The case of Central America is not
advancing and, on the contrary, is entering a period of paralysis.''
   In Nicaragua, rebels financed and armed by the United States are
trying to overthrow the leftist government of President Daniel
Noriega. Neighboring El Salvador has endured a guerrilla war since
1980. Thousands have died in both countries.
   The Group of Eight is an outgrowth of the so-called Contadora
Group, which was formed in 1983 by Mexico, Colombia, Venezuela and
Panama to promote peace in Central America. Argentina, Brazil,
Uruguay and Peru formed the Contadora Support Group in 1985.
   A year later, leaders of the eight countries decided to meet
regularly and discuss issues on a broader front, including trade,
foreign debt and international drug trafficking.
   Developing a foreign debt strategy may be the most pressing topic
on their agenda. The countries are using ever greater shares of
their national budgets for repaying that debt, but the money is
needed for investment and restructuring their economies.
   ``You can't condemn an entire continent to stagnation because
that conspires against hemispheric security and universal justice,''
Argentine President Alfonsin said in a speech to the World Business
Council on Monday.
   Latin American countries owe more than $400 billion to a range of
public and private creditors, and the Group of Eight represents more
than $320 billion of that amount.
   Aides who have been drafting the final communique for the group
also said it will call for a reduction of trade barriers erected by
developed countries.
</TEXT>
