<HEAD>Drug Assets To Pay For Prison Space</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some $95.4 million in seized assets forfeited
by drug traffickers and organized crime figures will be used to
expand federal prison space, the Justice Department announced
Wednesday.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh transferred the money from the
assets forfeiture fund under an amendment approved last year by the
Senate.
   The money will replenish funds used to repair and build prison
facilities at Atlanta and Oakdale, La., where Mariel Cuban prisoners
rioted last year; to build detention units at Fort Worth, Texas, and
Tallahassee, Fla.; and to uprgrade the Lompoc, Calif., prison camp
to the status of a federal correctional institution.
   The U.S. Marshals Service, which maintains the assets forfeiture
fund, is currently managing more than $500 million worth of property
seized from criminals, including cars, boats, aircraft, residential
and commercial properties, banks, golf courses, recording studios
and historic mansions. The property is disposed of by the marshals
service.
