<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Iran,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Diplomats Arrested In Smuggling Of Dissident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested five Iranian diplomats in
eastern Turkey who allegedly kidnapped an anti-Khomeini activist and
were taking him in the trunk of their car to Iran, the Anatolia news
agency said Wednesday.
   Prosecutor Olcay Seckin of Erzincan province was quoted as saying
the five were arrested at a gas station about 360 miles from the
Iranian border. The Anatolia report said a gas station attendent had
told police there was a man in the trunk of the Iranians' car.
   Anatolia did not say when the arrests were made but another news
agency, Hurriyet, reported they were picked up Sunday.
   It said military police found Seyit Ebu Hasan, an Iranian
engineer, with his arms and legs tied.
   Seckin could not be reached for comment Wednesday but an official
at his office said the five were turned over to police Tuesday.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said they
would be delivered for questioning to the State Security Court in
Istanbul, apparently because the abduction originated there. He
would not elaborate.
   Erzincan is 635 miles east of Istanbul and a trip by car takes at
least 24 hours.
   In provinces such as Istanbul, which is under emergency law,
suspects can be held 15 days before charges are brought against them.
   Anatolia identified the five as Resul Bnnsahalan, N.
Ghusrorabdullah Pahhul, Hamit Gezo Mehran Baheri, Ramazan Kahlo and
Orjan Lihe, and said they were all stationed at Iran's consulate in
Istanbul.
   A spokeman at the consulate, Musteba Saidi, said there were no
diplomats by those names working there.
   Hurriyet reported allegations that the five were Iranian
intelligence agents and were trying to smuggle the engineer back to
Iran. The news service said the engineer had been involved in
activities against Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
</TEXT>
