<HEAD>Bush Campaign Tells Press To Play Fare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush's campaign press plane
became an airborne collection agency Wednesday under a new
pay-as-you-fly rule.
   It was said to stem from orders from campaign chairman James A.
Baker III because the campaign is $1 million in the red on press
travel payments.
   A memo issued by Alixe Glen, a deputy press secretary, said
traveling reporters, photographers and technicians had to pay up
immediately, leg by leg, for their travels with Bush unless their
organizations had paid in advance for the remainder of the campaign.
   The memo was issued between Detroit and Sioux Falls, and campaign
aides then roamed the plane taking credit cards from people whose
organizations hadn't paid.
   The campaign estimated the cost per day at about $900 per person.
