<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Disaster-Politics     10-26 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Disaster-Politics,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Storm Accompanies Hurricane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Joan spawned an intense
political storm between the Sandinistas and their opponents as it
rampaged across Nicaragua.
   President Daniel Ortega frequently compared the hurricane's
assault to attacks by guerrillas and said the best relief aid the
United States could offer would be halting aid to the rebels, known
as Contras.
   Monsignor Bismarck Carballo, a Roman Catholic church spokesman,
accused the government of mixing political slogans with emergency
broadcasts.
   Joan came ashore early Saturday morning at Bluefields, flattened
the Caribbean port of 38,000 people, and cut a path of destruction
across to the Pacific in the following 24 hours.
   It killed at least 60 people and left 300,000 homeless. Nicaragua
issued a general appeal for emergency assistance. Nations as diverse
as Britain and Cuba responded with aid, but the United States said
it probably would not.
   Ortega said Wednesday the hurricane had destroyed a key farming
and ranching area in central Nicaragua. After touring the region he
said Joan wiped out cattle herds, pastures, forests, grain crops,
more than 20,000 homes in 22 communities in 40 square miles.
   The official radio, Voice of Nicaragua, described the district 90
miles east of Managua as the country's main farming and ranching
area.
   Political barbs began last week as the storm approached the
Caribbean coast, after the U.S. Congress approved a resolution
leaving open the possibility of renewed aid to the Contras.
   ``It is inconceivable that, while Nicaraguans face the threat of
catastrophe the American Congress maintains its threat to escalate
the war,'' Ortega said.
   The Contras and Sandinistas agreed in March to a cease-fire, but
further talks broke off in September. Most rebels moved to base
camps in Honduras in the last few months, but both sides still
report minor skirmishes.
   Nicaragua's economy has been devastated by seven years of civil
war, which the government says has cost $7 million.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Monday of Ortega:
``It seems clear he wants to use this storm as another platform for
propaganda against the Contras.''
   In his complaints about propaganda during the Hurricane
emergency, Carballo said: ``The Voice of Nicaragua started to
transmit that neither President Reagan nor Joan would destroy the
revolution.''
   Anti-U.S. rhetoric has caused the government problems among the 3
million Nicaraguans. Some refused to evacuate for Joan because, they
said, the Sandinistas had lost their credibility by warning
repeatedly of ``imminent'' U.S. invasions.
   ``People are tired of hearing these calls and don't believe
them,'' said Ruben Hernandez, who refused to leave his home in a
poor, low-lying neighborhood of Managua.
   Both Fitzwater and Nicaragua's sole opposition newspaper, La
Prensa, criticized an emergency law that suspended articles of the
constitution dealing with freedom of speech for 30 days, which
includes the U.S. election Nov. 8.
   ``To do it at this time under cover of a storm is no worse really
than the performance he has displayed for the past six or seven
years in terms of closing down the press,'' Fitzwater said.
   While touring devastated Bluefields on Monday, Ortega said
Nicaragua might accept U.S. government hurricane aid if it was
offered ``without conditions,'' and expressed certainty that help
would come from private American groups that oppose their
government's Central America policy.
   On Tuesday, the pro-government newspaper El Nuevo Diario said
Nicaragua did not want aid from Washington.
   Fitzwater said Monday the United States feared any emergency aid
it offered would help Nicaragua against the Contras.
   In reply, the government newspaper Barricada said: ``It's better
for the Yankees to keep their blankets, milk for children and
medicine for our homeless brothers.''
   Bluefields fisherman Aster Gerth asked a visitor, however: ``Do
you think the United States will help? The Russians and the Cubans
can't do what the United States can.''
   Roberto Arguello, director of the Nicaraguan American Bankers
Association, said most Nicaraguan exiles in Miami had the attitude:
``Let the Russians help them out.''
   Cuba sent hurricane experts before the storm hit and sheltered
Nicaraguan air force planes at its airfields. Cuban doctors and
emergency supplies arrived immediately after Joan's departure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
