<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Indictments,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Dozen People Charged In Two Federal Drug Indictments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors Wednesday accused 27 people,
including a Ku Klux Klansman and a Georgia lawyer, of taking part in
an eight-state ring that distributed cocaine and marijuana and
manufactured methamphetamine.
   U.S. Attorney Robert Barr said the drug and money-laundering
charges were contained in an indictment returned Friday that also
seeks the seizure of a golf course.
   The indictment identifies Donald E. Miles of Norcross as the
ringleader.
   Barr said 16 of the 27 defendants, including Miles, had been
arrested and prosecutors were asking they be held without bail.
   The ring operated in Georgia, Florida, North Carolina, South
Carolina, Alabama, California, Washington and Idaho, with most of
the manufacturing of methamphetmine, or ``speed,'' done in
Washington, Barr said.
   The indictment seeks the forfeiture of 15 pieces of land,
including a golf course in Winder worth more than $3 million and 23
vehicles worth about $200,000.
   Most of those named in the indictment are from Georgia, including
Donald Oscar Nelson, an attorney in middle Georgia's Monroe County.
He is accused of using drug proceeds to make purchases for Miles.
   Others indicted included Jim Blair of Five Points, Ala., former
Imperial Wizard of Knights of the Ku Klux Klan. He gave up the
national post in 1986 in an unsuccessful bid for a seat in the
Alabama House.
   Authorities said they had no evidence of Klan involvement in the
drug ring.
   Nelson and Blair were among those arrested.
</TEXT>
