<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PresidentialPolls     10-26 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Polls,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Up by Eight in ABC-Post Poll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national poll Wednesday gave George Bush an
eight-point advantage over Michael Dukakis in the race for
president, a somewhat smaller lead than the Republican nominee
enjoyed in two earlier polls this week.
   The ABC News-Washington Post poll of 1,242 likely voters put the
contest at 52-44 percent, closer than the 13-point gap in a CBS
News-New York Times poll and the 14 points among likely voters in a
Gallup poll released Tuesday.
   The ABC-Post poll was conducted during the seven days ending
Tuesday, rather than the three- and four-day field periods of the
earlier polls.
   That could account for differing results. Polls done during fewer
days are more liable to be influenced by daily movements in voter
preference. In polls done over more time, changes may be tempered by
days of stable opinion.
   ABC-Post polls have showed slight movement in the race, with Bush
ahead by six points in an Oct. 5-11 poll, seven in an Oct. 12-18
poll and eight now. The Gallup and CBS-Times polls, done in shorter
periods, found more movement for Bush after the Oct. 13 presidential
debate.
   The margin of sampling error in the ABC-Post poll was plus or
minus three percentage points.
</TEXT>
