<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wintry Weather Descends on Plains; Rain and Storms Hit Gulf Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cold air swept from Canada toward the northern Plains on
Wednesday and thunderstorms continued over parts of Louisiana and
eastern Texas.
   Strong winds, freezing temperatures and scattered snow showers
were expected by late Wednesday in Montana and North Dakota, with
snow accumulations up to 6 inches in western and central Montana.
   The wind chill factor was expected to create the equivalent of
temperatures of zero to 10 below zero across North Dakota on
Thursday.
   Thunderstorms produced tornadoes in southwest Louisiana at the
town of Sulphur, in southwest Lake Charles, near the town of
Jennings and 20 miles north of Crowley. Minor damage was reported.
   Showers drenched parts of Mississippi, Alabama and northern
Georgia.
   Lake-effect snow in the Northeast diminished Wednesday, but some
locations in the northeast corner of Ohio, northwest Pennsylvania
and the western tip of New York reported a few inches of snow.
Willoughby, Ohio, had 5 inches of snow on the ground around at
midday and 1 to 3 inches of snow was measured across Chautauqua
County, N.Y., along Lake Erie southwest of Buffalo.
   A few rain and snow showers fell in Michigan, eastern New York,
northeast Pennsylvania and New England.
   Skies were mostly sunny Wednesday afternoon from the lower Ohio
Valley across the central Plains and the southern Rockies to the
desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 30
degrees at Ely Minn., to 91 degrees at Thermal, Calif., and Palm
Springs, Calif. The nation's low Wednesday morning was 7 degrees at
Gunnison Colo.
   The forecast for Thursday called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the southern Plains across northern Louisiana and
Arkansas to Missouri. Scattered showers were predicted from the
lower Ohio Valley to the upper Mississippi Valley, with showers
turning to snow across northern Minnesota, the northern Plains and
northern Rockies.
   High temperatures were forecast to be in the 20s and 30s from
northern Minnesota across most of the Dakotas to the northern
Rockies; 40s and 50s from the northern and middle Atlantic Coast
states across the Great Lakes region, southern Minnesota, Nebraska,
the central Rockies and Idaho to Washington state; and 80s in much
of Florida, the southern Plains, southern New Mexico and interior
valleys of California. Readings should reach 85 to 95 degrees in the
desert Southwest and 60s and 70s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
