<HEAD>Two Workers Hurt By Falling Artwork</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-ton sculpture in a SoHo art gallery fell on
top of two workers Wednesday, causing one of them to lose a leg,
officials said.
   The workers were removing the piece, ``Reading Cones'' by Richard
Serra, from the first-floor Leo Castelli Gallery at 142 Greene St.
when a set of heavy-duty jacks collapsed and dropped the artwork,
said Efrain Parrilla, a Fire Department spokesman.
   Rescue workers lifted the sculpture to free the men and then took
them to hospitals.
   John Clark, a Bellevue Hospital administrator, said surgeons were
unable to save Joseph Gallo's right leg, which was amputated below
the knee. Clark said Gallo, 30, was admitted in serious but stable
condition.
   Daniel Hafner, in his 30s, was in stable condition at
Beekman-Downtown Hospital.
   The curved piece of steel is 3 inches thick, 14 feet high, 17
feet long and weighs 32,000 pounds, said a gallery spokesman. The
workers were taking it to storage.
