<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-CouncilElection     10-26 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Council Election,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Assembly Elects Five New Security Council Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada, Colombia, Ethiopia, Finland and
Malaysia were elected on Wednesday to the Security Council, the U.N.
body responsible for peacekeeping and international security.
   General Assembly delegates cast secret ballots for the new
non-permanent members of the 15-member Council, putting them in
wooden boxes carried through the hall by clerks. The terms are for
two years.
   Canada, Ethiopia and Colombia got the necessary two-thirds
support on the first ballot and Malaysia won on the second after
Bangladesh withdrew. Finland edged out Greece on the third ballot.
   At stake were two seats assigned to Western nations, and one each
for Asia, Africa and the Latin America-Caribbean region.
   The five nations whose terms end Jan. 1 are Argentina, Italy,
Japan, West Germany and Zambia.
   Algeria, Brazil, Nepal, Senegal and Yugoslavia are in the second
year of their terms as non-permanent members. The five permanent
members, each of which has veto power, are the United States, Soviet
Union, Britain, China and France.
</TEXT>
