<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NorthernIreland 1stLd-Writethru a0761 10-26 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0761,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Booby-Trap Car Bomb Kills Postal Official</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout UPDATING with guerrillas killing policeman,
wounding another in ambush. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas shot and killed a
policeman and wounded another in an ambush Wednesday, and a car bomb
killed a Post Office manager outside Belfast's main postal sorting
office, police said.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility for the attacks,
which occurred 70 miles apart and within minutes of each other,
around 7 p.m. (3 p.m. EDT).
   The policemen had just come off duty and were traveling to
Enniskillen in County Fermanagh when their private car was raked
with gunfire near the village of Kinawley, 70 miles southwest of
Belfast, said police Sgt. Michael Glover.
   Both men were seriously wounded and one later died of his
injuries, police said. Their identities were not immediately
released.
   In central Belfast, a booby-trap bomb exploded under a car in a
multi-story parking lot across the road from the city's main sorting
office, killing a Post Office transport manager.
   The official, who was not immediately identified, got into the
car after leaving work and had driven a short distance toward the
exit when the blast destroyed his car, Glover said.
   The victim apparently had no connection with the security forces,
which are targeted by the Irish Republican Army, Glover said.
   The outlawed, Roman Catholic guerrilla group is fighting to drive
the British out of Northern Ireland and unite the
Protestant-dominated province with the Catholic Republic of Ireland
under socialist rule.
   A total of 2,703 people are known to have been killed since
political and sectarian violence erupted in Northern Ireland in 1969.
</TEXT>
