<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COVINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A male calendar contest at a popular
nightclub is causing a stir in this northern Kentucky city, and the
club's owner says there wouldn't be a problem if the contestants
were women instead of men.
   The Monday night performance, billed as ``The Men of Menagerie
Calendar Contest,'' took place as scheduled at the Glass Menagerie,
but city officials say the show must not go on.
   The matter has been turned over to the city's legal advisers,
said Zoning Administrator Ralph Hopper.
   Hopper warned the nightclub's owner that the contest violates
city zoning ordinances on adult entertainment and ordered the club
to halt the show or face a fine.
   About an hour before the Monday performance, Lt. Ralph Schawe
delivered Hopper's order. But the show went on anyway.
   ``It was a very professional show. The costumes were fantastic,''
said Detective Marty Epperson, a plainclothes officer who went to
the contest to serve as a witness for the city.
   Participants wore costumes at the beginning and stripped down to
G-strings while music played, she said.
   The nightclub is in a highway commercial zone in which adult
entertainment is prohibited. The club could face a fine of $10 to
$500 per day, and its liquor license could be jeopardized.
   The contest is no different than female calendar contests
sponsored by other Covington nightspots, said Glass Menagerie owner
Larry Grause.
   Participants ``strut their stuff'' for the audience, which
chooses the winner by applause, he said.
   ``As far as we're concerned, this a sexist type of attack,''
Grause said. ``Obviously, it was generated by our competitors
because it was a successful promotion.''
   Hopper said he was unaware of similar contests at other
nightspots.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For those wanting to move up and live in upper,
upscale neighborhoods, it's either the East Coast or the West Coast.
   The most expensive suburb in the United States is La Jolla,
Calif., where the average home goes for $1.1 million, according to a
survey of the costliest 75 suburban real estate markets.
   But more than half the communities on the list are in the
tristate New York metropolitan area.
   After La Jolla comes Alpine, N.J., where homes average $1.06
million, followed by two Long Island villages, Laurel Hollow and
Mill Neck, and Jupier Island, Fla., all at a flat $1 million,
according to the survey conducted during the summer by the Solomon
Organization, a public relations company.
   The study was undertaken for RELO, a Chicago-based association of
1,300 independent real estate brokers who specialize in arranging
moves for corporate employees.
   The rest of the top 10 were: Old Westbury, N.Y., $980,000; Saddle
River, N.J., $975,000; Lattingtown, N.Y., $950,000; Rancho Santa
Fe., Calif., $922,000, and Brookville, N.Y., and Muttontown, N.Y.,
$900,000.
