<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Slaying     10-26 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Slaying,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Mark Anniversary of Human Rights Leader's Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of people marched
through the capital on Wednesday, the first anniversary of a human
rights leader's slaying, and Amnesty International said right-wing
death squads have re-emerged.
   About 500 people attended a religious service honoring Herbert
Anaya Sanabria, then marched through the capital to lay flowers at
his grave.
   Anaya, 33, was gunned down on Oct. 26, 1987, near his home in San
Salvador. He was the fifth director of the Salvadoran Human Rights
Commission to be assassinated since 1980.
   The government blamed the crime on the leftist guerrilla
Farabundo Marti Liberation Front. But Roman Catholic Church and
humanitarian groups say it was the work of a rightist death squad.
   Amnesty International, the London-based human rights group, said
death squads, usually including soldiers or police, have killed
hundreds of people suspected of being leftists or government
opponents in the past two years.
   It said death squads are re-emerging because of military
opposition to peace negotiations with the front and that Anaya's
slaying was seen as an attempt to discourage the talks.
   Soldiers and death squads killed tens of thousands of suspected
leftists in the 1970s and early 1980s, but death squad activity
diminished after the U.S.-backed civilian government came to power
in 1984.
   Col. Jose Galileo refused to comment on the Amnesty International
report, but he said the armed forces would issue a bulletin on the
issue later, possibly Thursday.
   The government said the guerrilla front killed Anaya because he
left the front to collaborate with the military.
   It said a suspected guerrilla, Jorge Alberto Miranda Arevalo,
admitted killing Anaya. Miranda, 19, says he was forced to confess
to a crime he did not commit.
   Anaya's widow, Mirna Perla, told a news conference Wednesday that
Miranda is ``another innocent victim.''
   In another incident Wednesday, two guerrillas broke into a radio
station in San Salvador on Wednesday and broadcast a tape attacking
Duarte's government. The guerrillas were gone by the time police
arrived.
   The guerrillas have been fighting the U.S.-backed armed forces
for nine years. An estimated 65,000 people, most of them civilians,
have died in the war.
</TEXT>
