<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CadetsStricken     10-26 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cadets Stricken,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Director of Embattled Police Training Council Takes Leave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of the police training council that
supervised an academy where 16 cadets were hospitalized from
exhaustion stepped down Wednesday amid a series of investigations.
   Gary F. Egan, executive director of the Massachusetts Criminal
Justice Training Council, was placed on leave of absence until the
state attorney general's office determines what felled cadets at the
police academy in Agawam.
   A statement issued by the council said Egan ``felt his continued
presence in the midst of press attention was interfering with the
agency's ability to carry out its job of training police throughout
the commonwealth.''
   At least 16 recruits in a class of 50 were hospitalized with
dehydration, exhaustion and kidney failure by the end of the first
week of training at the western Massachusetts academy last month.
One recruit had a liver transplant and was in a coma for two weeks.
   Public Safety Secretary Charles V. Barry asked Egan to take the
leave from his $53,000-a-year job, according to sources in the state
Executive Office of Public Safety, which is monitoring the council.
   Attorney General James M. Shannon has been investigating what
caused the cadets to collapse and what role was played by the
physical and stress training program they were undergoing. In
addition, a panel appointed by Gov. Michael S. Dukakis is reviewing
the council's training procedures.
   Shannon also is investigating reports of financial and hiring
improprieties on the staff of the 24-member council, which is
comprised of police, sheriff, corrections and other law enforcement
officials.
   The council runs five of 15 police training centers in the state,
including the Agawam facility. It certifies and provides technical
assistance to the other 10, which are operated by local or county
law enforcement agencies.
   The Agawam academy was closed Sept. 21 for the investigation.
Cadets are being trained at a National Guard barracks in Agawam.
</TEXT>
