<DOCNO> AP881026-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 2247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Whales-NotreDame     10-26 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Whales-Notre Dame,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whale Rescue Poses Question About Human Life, Notre Dame President
Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trapped Whales, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tremendous publicity given to the
rescue of whales stranded off Alaska has some people questioning the
relative values of animal and human life, the president of the
University of Notre Dame said.
   The Rev. Edward ``Monk'' Malloy told about 300 people at a
``social concern forum'' Tuesday that he was an animal lover, but
that the rescue attempts are ``more of a public relations effort to
appease certain elements in the ecology movement, to show that the
government cares.''
   Malloy cited the whale rescue, along with longstanding social
concerns such as abortion and hunger in the world, as issues members
of the audience should use to help examine their ethics in a context
of being part of a global community.
   ``We realize we are one in the midst of many and we have to ask,
`Can we hone in on one issue or a set of interconnected issues?'''
   Malloy said that well-meaning people caught up by one concern
should not overlook related problems.
   He noted that civil strife and corrupt governments in Africa
sometimes divert aid offered by people moved by heart-wrenching
photographs of starving children.
   ``So, in the efforts to deal with the broad-based concerns of
hunger, good will alone will not help, and we should be prudent,''
Malloy said.
   Malloy argued that even in the drive against abortion, which is a
major concern of the Roman Catholic Church he serves, it is
important to look beyond a single issue.
   ``Being pro-life has served as a rallying cry for some
Christians,'' he said. ``But pro-life should include more than life
in the womb. Concern should also be given to the life of an infant,
the life of the elderly and the life of the mentally, physically and
spiritually handicapped.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
