<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GayPriest     10-26 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gay Priest,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tribunal Excommunicates Gay Priest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic priest who advocated a more
compassionate view of homosexuality and later revealed that he was
gay has been excommunicated by a church tribunal for joining the
Episcopal Church.
   The tribunal dismissed William Dorn Jr. from the ``clerical
state'' and banned him from the priesthood forever. It found him
guilty of leaving the Vatican-ruled church in favor of the
Britain-based Protestant denomination.
   The ruling puts an end to a two-year public dispute in which Dorn
and the Roman Catholic Church clashed over his outspoken challenges
to church teachings on homosexuality and his ultimate revelation
that he is gay.
   ``It's over,'' said Dorn, 36, after learning of the ruling
Tuesday.
   The tribunal's ruling was dated Sept. 30 and delivered Tuesday to
Dorn by his church-appointed lawyer, the Rev. James Zusy of the
Archdiocese of St. Paul and Minneapolis. Dorn said that he was not
allowed to keep a copy of the decree and was ordered not to speak
about it.
   However, he notified the media and issued a statement critical of
the church hierarchy. Zusy refused to discuss the matter, saying,
``I cannot say a word. I am bound to secrecy.''
   Former St. Cloud Bishop George Speltz suspended, then fired Dorn
from his job at the Christ Church Newman Center at St. Cloud State
University in October 1986.
   Speltz was angered by a controversial article Dorn had written
for the St. Cloud Visitor, the diocesan newspaper. The article
advocated a more compassionate view of homosexuality, which Dorn
called a ``gift from God.''
   In June, the three-member tribunal met in Park Rapids at the
order of Bishop Victor Balke of Crookston, where Dorn was ordained
in 1979.
   Dorn on several occasions declined an invitation to come back to
the church on the condition he remain silent about homosexuality.
   Commenting on the church's action, Dorn said that by silencing
priests who challenge traditional doctrine, church officials are
losing touch with people and closing doors on the oppressed.
   ``In fear, (church officials) cling to the vestiges of power,''
he said. ``They speak only to themselves, and so believe they are
mighty.''
   Dorn, who lives in south Minneapolis, declined to discuss his
personal life or possible plans to seek ordination in the Episcopal
Church.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
