<1ST_LINE>u w AM-TrappedWhales-Reagan     10-26 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trapped Whales-Reagan,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Congratulates Soviets, Others For Work In Freeing Whales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan late Wednesday lauded the
efforts of the crew members of two Soviet icebreakers, among others,
for their work leading to the freeing of two whales trapped in the
Arctic ice.
   ``I am gratified that the California gray whales have been
released to the open sea,'' Reagan said in a statement read by Mark
Weinberger, a White House spokesman.
   ``The human persistence and determination by so many individuals
on behalf of these whales shows mankind's concern for the
environment,'' he said. ``It has been an inspiring endeavor.
   ``We thank and congratulate the crews of the two Soviet
icebreakers who finally broke through to the whales. They were part
of a remarkable team effort _ by governments, individuals and
business. Due to all these efforts, the whales have returned to the
sea.''
   The whales that had been imprisoned nearly three weeks were
headed out to open sea Wednesday after two Soviet ice-breaking
vessels smashed a pathway to them from the sea.
   Breathing holes had been cut for the whales by Americans working
in the opposite direction.
   A third whale that also had been trapped is believed to have died
last week.
</TEXT>
