<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AndersonObservances     10-26 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anderson Observances,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Western New York Plans Observances to Mark Anderson's 41st Birthday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanon hostage Terry Anderson marks his
41st birthday Thursday as he has his last three: in the hands of
Shiite Moslem kidnappers.
   Half a world away, people in his home state will use the day to
press for his freedom.
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, is the longest held U.S. hostage. He was snatched March 16,
1985, off the streets of Beirut by pro-Iranian extremists who have
issued numerous threats against his life.
   To mark the day, a radio station and merchants group in
Anderson's hometown of Batavia are sponsoring a birthday party with
a huge cake decorated with 1,321 candles, one for each day of the
journalist's captivity.
   Organizers are freezing a portion of the cake to give Anderson
when he is freed.
   ``The community hasn't forgot him,'' said Terri Fritz of radio
station WBAT.
   Many residents of the small city of 17,000 also will put lighted
candles in their windows for Anderson, she said.
   At Buffalo State College, students will hold a rally on
Anderson's behalf.
   ``We see it as a chance to sensitize students to the issues of
freedom,'' said journalism professor Paul DeWald. ``Terry is Joe
America to us and we have to stand up for him.''
   Students will wear armbands with Anderson's name and sign a huge
birthday card that will be forwarded to Lebanon, DeWald said.
   In Catskill, south of Albany, parishioners of St. Patrick's Roman
Catholic Church plan a prayer service for Anderson.
   The Rev. Bedde Ferrara, an organizer of the event, also said
children from Catholic schools have written letters to Anderson that
will be given to Anderson's sister, Peggy Say.
   Mrs. Say attended a children's church ceremony for the hostages
in Buffalo on Tuesday. At the ceremony, she said she had learned
from a French hostage that Anderson was hoping to be released before
the presidential election.
   ``He's got himself geared up for a release before the election,''
she said. ``If it doesn't come he's going to be terribly
disappointed.''
</TEXT>
