<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Fogerty     10-26 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fogerty,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Courtroom Rocks as Singer Fights Lawsuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal courtroom rocked to Creedence
Clearwater Revival records Wednesday as lawyers for former lead
singer John Fogerty tried to show that a song from his 1985 comeback
album wasn't stolen from another Fogerty hit.
   Fantasy Records, which recorded Creedence, has filed suit
essentially accusing Fogerty of plagiarizing himself.
   The suit against Fogerty and his current recording company,
Warner Bros. Records Inc., contends ``Old Man Down the Road,'' a
single from Fogerty's solo ``Centerfield'' album, copied the melody
from ``Run Through the Jungle,'' which Fogerty wrote and sang for
Creedence in 1970 and to which Fantasy now owns the rights.
   Relations between Fogerty and his former recording company have
been bitter since Creedence disbanded in 1972. Fogerty had to change
the title of one song in ``Centerfield'' after Saul Zaentz, owner of
Fantasy Records, said he was being libeled.
   In the current case, the two songs are similar in tune and
structure, as lawyers for Fantasy demonstrated earlier this week in
testimony by musicologists equipped with charts, a piano and a
computer sound system that superimposed one pattern of notes on
another.
   A defense musicologist for Warner Bros. guided the U.S. District
Court jurors through a series of Creedence records _ ``Green
River,'' ``Keep on Chooglin','' ``Tombstone Shadow'' and ``Bootleg''
_ with his own series of elaborate charts pointing out similarities
to ``Run Through the Jungle'' and ``Old Man Down the Road.''
   The six jurors and four alternates, who appeared to range from
about 30 to their 60s, listened to the late 1960s-early 1970s medley
with serious expressions and varied postures _ one middle-aged man
yawned at one point, while several jurors nodded in time to the beat.
   The defense witness, Harold Barlow, who described himself as a
``music plagiarism expert'' as well as a songwriter and arranger,
said all the songs had many notes in common.
   ``He (Fogerty) is working with an idea,'' Barlow said. ``The idea
is to use B-flat and C in a repetitive structure. ... Mr. Fogerty
has made this structure commonplace. The way he uses them, the
expression of the idea, they're used differently.''
   Under cross-examination, Barlow acknowledged that he had compared
the two songs early in the case, without examining any other songs,
and concluded they were ``substantially similar,'' the standard that
determines copyright infringement.
   But he insisted that a valid comparison must also take into
account earlier works that might have influenced later compositions;
in light of those, ``Old Man Down the Road'' can't be considered a
copy of the 1970 song, Barlow said.
   Fogerty testified briefly Monday and is scheduled to appear again
Friday.
   In pretrial statements read into the record Wednesday by lawyers
for Fantasy, Fogerty said several of his songs, including the two
involved in the case, used ``similar phrasing.''
   But he added in the statement, ``As far as I'm concerned, the two
songs are totally different.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
