<HEAD>Woman Says Being Shot By Husband Strengthened Relationship</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Danelle in 3rd graf is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FARGO, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman shot in the mouth by her husband in a
struggle over whether to kill the family dog asked a judge for
leniency for her husband, saying the shooting had strengthened their
marriage.
   East Central District Judge Cynthia Rothe on Tuesday gave Paul
Dickelman a one-year suspended jail sentence on his reckless
endangerment conviction. He also must perform 200 hours of community
service work and will be on two years' probation.
   Dickelman, 31, who spent five days in jail after the shooting in
June, had suffered enough, said his wife, Danelle, 27, of rural
Horace.
   He had been drinking and planned to shoot the dog because it
urinated on their carpet. During a struggle over the .22-caliber
pistol, Mrs. Dickelman was shot, said John Goff, an assistant Cass
County state's attorney.
   Mrs. Dickelman said her husband has since sought help for a
drinking problem and the couple ``were trying to turn this ... into
a positive thing.''
