<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--CounterfeitDolls     10-26 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Counterfeit Dolls,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Fined for Smuggling Counterfeit Dolls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has fined a company and one of
its employees for smuggling counterfeit Cabbage Patch and Rainbow
Brite dolls into the country from Taiwan.
   U.S. District Judge John R. Hargrove on Tuesday fined Louis
DeSimone, 41, an agent for Jayce International, of Willowick, Ohio,
$50,000 and imposed a $35,000 fine on the company, which imports and
distributes children's toys.
   The maximum penalty for smuggling is a $250,000 fine.
   DeSimone and Jayce International pleaded guilty last month to
charges of smuggling the dolls into the country. The dolls were not
properly declared to U.S. Customs officials.
   The company has not been licensed by Appalachian Artworks, which
holds the copyright to Cabbage Patch dolls, to sell the dolls in the
United States.
   During a routine search on May 8, 1986, customs agents discovered
3,252 Cabbage Patch dolls and 227 Rainbow Brite dolls hidden behind
boxes of electric fans, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Susan M.
Ringler.
</TEXT>
