<DOCNO> AP881026-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 2233EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BombingSentence 1stLd-Writethru a0782 10-26 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bombing Sentence, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0782,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>4 Sentenced In White Supremacy Bombing Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to CORRECT that group was called `The
Order II' and modeled itself on The Order; background on The Order;
SUBS byline to fix style; picks up 10th graf: `In September ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By QUANE KENYON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Dorr, the ringleader of a white
supremacist group that modeled itself on The Order and launched a
series of bombings, was sentenced Wednesday to up to 20 years in
prison.
   Two other members of The Order II were sentenced to eight years
in prison, but a third defendant was placed on probation. Deborah
Dorr, 36, Dorr's wife, and Edward Hawley, 24, were both ordered to
jail. Hawley's wife, Olive, 29, was given a six-year prison
sentence, but it was suspended to five years probation.
   The Dorr-Hawley group, described as ``The Order II'' or ``Bruder
Schweigen Task Force'' in documents found in the Dorr home, was
apparently a small group modeled on the militant white supremacist
group The Order.
   The Order was a violent offshoot of the white supremacist Aryan
Nations organization at Hayden Lake, which is 30 miles northeast of
Spokane, Wash.
   Twenty-three members of the original Order were indicted in
Seattle on racketeering charges. Twelve pleaded guilty to various
charges in the indictment while 10 others were convicted in December
1985. A 23rd person is imprisoned in Missouri on other convictions.
   Prosecutors in Seattle alleged The Order staged a string of
crimes, including bank and armored car robberies, in late 1983 and
1984 in a plot to overthrow the governemnt and establish an Aryan
homeland in the Northwest.
   The Dorrs and Hawleys were indicted by a federal grand jury
earlier this year on counts of racketeering, conspiracy,
counterfeiting, bombing, illegal possession of automatic weapons and
malicious destruction of federal property.
   They also face separate state charges in the bombings. A trial is
tentatively scheduled for early next year.
   In all but one case, U.S. District Judge Harold Ryan went along
with a plea-bargain agreement between the defendants and the U.S.
Justice Department. The defendants all pleaded guilty.
   Prosecutors recommended up to 12 years for Hawley, but Ryan cut
that by a third.
   ``I think there is hope for you,'' Ryan told Hawley. ``I feel
that you have been a follower, and you followed your way into a
whole heap of trouble.''
   In September 1986, a series of explosions rocked the Coeur
d'Alene area in northern Idaho. One of the blasts damaged the home
of a Roman Catholic priest active in human rights work and another
damaged the federal building in Coeur d'Alene. There were no
injuries.
   Dorr and Hawley already are serving a four-year sentence in an
Arizona prison on a federal counterfeiting conviction in Washington
state. Ryan gave them credit for time served since their arrests two
years ago.
   The sentences handed down Wednesday were made concurrent with the
previous convictions.
   Court officials said Dorr, 37, could be eligiible for
consideration for parole in four to five years and Hawley in two
years.
   Mrs. Dorr probably will have to serve at least one-third of her
eight-year sentence, a defense attorney said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
