<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen 2ndLd-Writethru a0778 10-26 0858</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0778,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Raps Quayle at California Campaign Stop</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 17th graf, ``We need..., to CORRECT attribution.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate Lloyd
Bentsen said Wednesday evening the Republicans had run a ``miserable
campaign'' of distortions which Michael Dukakis did not address
until after it hurt the Democratic ticket.
   Bentsen, appearing on the CBS Evening News, said he did not think
George Bush was a racist, but he reiterated his opinion that the ads
Bush was sanctioning were.
   ``I think what we have seen is a miserable campaign,'' he said.
   ``What he's allowing to be done is ... hypocrisy at work,'' he
said, complaining that Bush allows his advisers to distort the
truth. ``Now, he ought to root those things out.''
   Bentsen cited the Republicans' use of ads showing pictures of
Willie Horton, a black Massachusetts prisoner who escaped on
furlough and was convicted of raping a white Maryland woman. ``In
this instance, you've seen how they've used his photograph over and
over and over again,'' he said.
   Asked by CBS anchorman Dan Rather if the Democrats were being
opportunistic themselves, Bentsen said they were in fact slow to
respond.
   ``Dan, They started immediately after that Democratic convention,
and Frankly I thought they should have been answered then,'' he
said. ``But my friend Mike Dukakis was incredulous, he just didn't
believe that sort of charges with the distortions could stick.
   ``But they have and they have hurt. And that's one of the reasons
we're in the kind of a race we're in now.''
   Rather asked Bentsen how often he himself had met with Jesse
Jackson, and Bentsen said they had participated recently in a joint
satellite session with college students. The two men were in
separate cities for that event.
   Bentsen also said he planned to appear with Jackson this week.
Campaign officials said afterward the event was still tentative
because of Jackson's schedule.
   On the stump in California, where the CBS broadcast originated,
Bentsen moved on from hitting at Bush's campaign advertising and
trained his sights again Wednesday at Bush's running mate, Dan
Quayle.
   ``I think millions of Americans would agree that Dan Quayle is
not qualified to be president'' if he had to step into the job,
Bentsen told a crowd at a Riverside outdoor plaza.
   Bentsen's appearance came hours before he was scheduled to appear
on CBS as part of a strategy by the presidential campaign of Michael
Dukakis to get as much television exposure as possible.
   Bentsen ridiculed the Republican campaign for saying Quayle would
head up a Bush administration war on drugs and lead the U.S. space
program.
   As for Quayle's assertion that he would have a major influence on
national defense policy, Bentsen said: ``That's a frightening
thought. Are you ready for that?''
   There was an enthusiastic response from the noontime crowd. Mike
McCurry, Bentsen's press secretary, said Quayle was a bigger issue
in California than in most other states according to the campaign's
poll.
   ``We need to keep that issue in front of the voters,'' McCurry
said.
   Bentsen arrived in California after a swing through Montana and
the Dakotas, moving from states with the fewest electoral votes to
the one with the most.
   ``This is the big banana. This is the one we have to win,'' he
said.
   The rally, complete with two high school bands, cheerleaders and
balloons was in part a warmup for an unprecedented television blitz
by the campaign using Bentsen.
   The candidate was taping a five-minute television commercial in
Los Angeles Wednesday which the Democratic campaign plans to air
nationwide on Sunday night. Never has a presidential campaign bought
commercial time to feature its vice presidential candidate.
   The campaign has purchased a five-minute block on the ABC
television network on Sunday night.
   Bentsen will ``be talking about correcting the record, stating
the case ... the things he's been talking about so eloquently out on
the stump,'' said Tad Devine, who coordinates Bentsen's campaign and
is a top adviser for Dukakis.
   The Democrats are counting on a major get-out-the-vote effort on
Election Day to help carry key states, and it is necessary to keep
up enthusiasm in the face of polls showing the ticket trailing, he
said.
   Since Bentsen was chosen, he has been a consistent asset for
Dukakis and has proven himself a likeable candidate, Devine said.
Since the debate against Quayle and especially in the past few days,
``This vice presidential part of the campaign is becoming much more
salient,'' he said.
   In addition to taping the five-minute spot and his appearance on
the CBS Evening News, Bentsen plans to make additional footage that
could be used in commercials in the final week of the race. A joint
commercial spot with Dukakis also was possible before Election Day,
Devine said.
   Bentsen's appearance with Dan Rather demonstrated to voters that
he was capable of meeting with the press and public and his
Republican counterpart was not, Devine said.
   ``Let's face it, the Republicans wouldn't dream of putting Dan
Quayle on a set with Dan Rather or anybody else,'' he said.
</TEXT>
