<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Amish-Signs     10-26 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amish-Signs,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amish Go To Court Over Requirement to Display Signs on Buggies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRESTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Requiring Amish people to display
slow-moving vehicle signs on their horse-drawn buggies desecrates
their religion, an attorney argued Wednesday in asking a judge to
dismiss citations against 15 defendants.
   The 15 were cited for failure to obey a state law requiring them
to display the triangular warning signs on the rear of their
buggies. In the dark or fog, the signs must be reflective orange,
and the Amish shun bright colors.
   Attorney Philip Villaume of St. Paul told Fillmore County
District Judge Clement Snyder that the Amish recognize the state's
interest in safety on public roadways and are willing to use
reflective tape and lanterns.
   Prosecutor Matt Opat has said the public safety issues outweigh
any infringement the law may have on the defendants' constitutional
right of religious freedom.
   Lee Zook, 42, a professor at Luther College in Decorah, Iowa,
testified as an expert on the Amish that slow-moving vehicle signs
are an ``intrusion into their life. This has nothing to do with
being symbolic of being God's people,'' which the Amish believe they
are, Zook said.
   Amish are opposed to bright colors because they draw attention to
themselves, Zook said. He said they put their trust in God and that
they know traveling on the highway with a horse and buggy is
somewhat dangerous.
   The U.S. Supreme Court has interpreted the First Amendment to
mean that sincerely held religious beliefs may not be infringed upon
by the state unless the limitation is the least restrictive means to
achieve a ``compelling state interest.''
   A ruling in the case is not expected for at least one month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
