<1ST_LINE>r w AM-O'HareControllers 1stLd-Writethru a0785 10-26 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-O'Hare Controllers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0785,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Outlines Plans to Reduce Flight-Handling Errors at O'Hare</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf and INSERTS new grafs 5-8 to UPDATE with Dixon
comments; SUBS 12th, 13th grafs pvs, bgng: ``To address...'' to
CLARIFY status of steps being taken; picks up 14th graf pvs, bgng:
``It also...''
^By DAVID FOX</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration sent a
report to Congress on Wednesday outlining plans to reduce
air-traffic controller errors at Chicago's O'Hare International
Airport, but Illinois' two senators said it fell short of
expectations.
   The six-page document sent to Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., for relay
to other lawmakers contained few details and set no timetable for
implementating FAA proposals.
   Among them were the hiring of an unspecified number of former
O'Hare controllers to ease a staff shortage, a pay incentive to
increase the size of the tower staff, and the expansion of
controller facilities.
   ``We have a big problem at O'Hare,'' Simon said. ``What we wanted
was an action plan. What we got was a wish list.''
   Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., issued a statement calling the report
``inadequate.''
   ``This doesn't begin to address the problem,'' Dixon said.
   Dixon has proposed the re-hiring of some of the controllers who
were fired in a 1981 strike. He said O'Hare needs 37 more
controllers to bring its total to 72, but the FAA report calls for
the addition of only five.
   Dixon also said the FAA report made no mention of limits on the
number of flights going into and out of O'Hare.
   The Senate passed a resolution earlier this month instructing the
FAA to inform Congress by Oct. 25 of its immediate and long-term
goals to improve operations blamed for a surge of controller errors
at O'Hare, the nation's busiest airport.
   Its controllers have had 30 such mistakes this year, compared
with 12 during all of 1987 and their previous record of 22 in 1986,
the FAA said.
   The report, which was approved Tuesday by Transportation
Secretary James Burnley and presented to Simon a day after the
Senate deadline, promised action to improve operations at O'Hare in
five broad categories: staffing and training, facilities and
equipment, communications, airspace, and safety and efficiency on
the ground.
   To address a manpower shortage, the FAA cited two steps that
officials already have decided to take.
   Five controllers are being relieved of training responsibilities
and returned to regular traffic handling at the facility, and the
agency has begun assigning personnel with experience at O'Hare on a
temporary basis until more fully trained controllers can be added to
the staff.
   It also said it hopes to adopt the pay incentive program and
intends to establish a recruiting program as well as look into the
possibility of ``sectorizing positions of operation'' so controllers
need to be trained at fewer operating stations.
   ``This review, as others, has identified numerous equipment and
physical plant improvements that could be made in order to improve
the efficient operation at Chicago tower,'' the report said. ``Many
of these can be made in the short term.''
   For example, the FAA has leased a television-type weather monitor
for the Chicago tower while the agency waits for acquisition of
similar units throughout the air-traffic control system.
   The agency also cited several steps to make communications
between pilots, controllers, airlines and technicians more efficient
_ such as reassessing the distribution of hand-held two-way radios
and limiting radio conversations.
   The recommendations essentially summarized 80 proposals the
agency had made earlier to improve operations at O'Hare and broke no
new ground, said Simon's press secretary, David Carle.
   ``Not only was Simon disappointed with the lack of a timetable,
but he felt the FAA should have addressed other problems, like
flight delays,'' Carle said. ``He said that demonstrates the agency
still doesn't recognize that the status quo is unacceptable.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
