<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Gulf 1stLd-Writethru   10-26 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0826,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq's U.N. Ambassador Says Shatt Could Be Replaced If Necessary</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 5th graf, `The Shatt...' to fix spelling.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iraqi ambassador to the U.N. said
Wednesday that if Iran-Iraq peace talks break down over the
Shatt-al-Arab waterway, Iraq will reopen a new deep-water port just
west of the Shatt.
   Ambassador Ismat Kittani said the port at Khor Zouber was
productive before war broke out in September 1980 and could be
restored if Iran is unwilling to guarantee free navigation on the
Shatt-al-Arab and agree to its being dredged.
   He spoke with reporters at his home Wednesday night just before
returning to Baghdad for consultations. The peace talks resume in
Geneva on Monday.
   Khor Zouber is reached by turning west just before entering the
Shatt-al-Arab, Kittani said, and entering the Khor Abdallah channel,
which empties into the Persian Gulf.
   The Shatt was Iraq's main outlet to the gulf before the war, but
has been blocked by sunken ships, unexploded ordnance and silt that
has accumulated since the war began in September 1980.
   Asked if Iraq wanted to develop an alternative deep-water port,
Kittani replied, ``We'll have to'' if the Iranians won't agree to
begin the dredging and reopening of the Shatt, known to Iran as the
Arvand River.
   ``We certainly can do without Basra'' if necessary, said Kittani.
Basra, Iraq's major port city on the Shatt, was heavily shelled in
the war.
   The envoy noted that before the war, ``at least 85 percent of
Iran's imports came to Iran through the Shatt, to Khorramshar'' on
the east bank of the passage.
   Kittani said regarding rights to the Shatt: ``Each is on his side
(of the passage). We will decide the sovereignty of running water
later (in the peace talks).''
   ``Whatever agreement is signed on the Shatt, both countries will
be able to use it,'' with specific rights to be worked out, said
Kittani.
   Iran insists the 1975 Algiers Treaty, which defines their border
as running down the middle of the Shatt, must be maintained.
   President Saddam Hussein of Iraq rejected the treaty in 1980.
Iraq distrusts Iran's commitment to a true peace settlement, and
diplomats have said it appears Iraq may want to gain sovereignty
over the entire Shatt to guarantee its freedom of navigation.
</TEXT>
