<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Plane Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0753,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vice President Criticizes State Airline After Crash Kills 12</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout; listing foreign victims;
revising figures; unaccounted person now accounted for; other. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The vice president of Peru questioned the
safety of the state airline on Wednesday and urged that it be
reorganized, a day after 12 people died in the fiery crash of an
Aeroperu jetliner.
   A Swiss priest and four other Europeans were among those killed.
   Fifty-seven people survived, many with serious injuries, when the
twin-jet Fokker-28 crashed immediately after taking off from the
airport in Juliaca, more than 12,000 feet above sea level in the
Andes mountains.
   Aeroperu said six Americans and nine other foreigners were among
44 people with significant injuries. The other survivors received
minor bruises.
   The U.S. Embassy said Aeroperu earlier mistakenly identified one
of the dead as an American. The British Embassy said the man,
Douglas Harris, was a 53-year-old Briton living in the United States.
   Areoperu said a passenger earlier listed as unaccounted for was a
Peruvian, who survived without major injuries.
   The company also issued a communique late Wednesday, responding
to mounting criticism since the crash. ``The plane was in proper
operating condition, fulfilling strictly the maintenance regulations
stipulated by the manufacturer,'' the communique said.
   However, Vice President Luis Alberto Sanchez said in a radio
interview, ``Aeroperu needed and still needs substantial reform. New
planes are needed ... But, above all, they must be functioning in a
constant state of repair.'' The Pilots' Association of Aeroperu had
charged that the airline's fleet of 10 planes was in poor shape
because of a shortage of spare parts and lack of maintenance.
   The union struck briefly two months ago over the issue.
   Aeroperu said the foreigners aboard the Dutch-made craft when it
crashed were mainly tourists returning from a visit to nearby Lake
Titicaca. Flight 771 was bound for Lima, 540 miles to the northwest,
with a stop in Arequipa.
   Survivors and witnesses on the ground said an explosion rocked
the plane seconds after takeoff. The plane crashed by the Cabanillas
River, a mile from the airport.
   Many victims died from burns suffered after the plane split in
three pieces on impact and the tail section burst into flames,
officials said.
   Transportation Minister Camilo Carrillo said the pilot averted a
greater disaster by steering the jet toward a sandy flood plain,
which softened the impact.
   Officials gave no cause for the accident. They said an
investigation was under way.
   Besides Harris, Aeroperu identified the European dead as the Rev.
Kurt Lenz, a Roman Catholic priest from Switzerland who worked near
Juliaca; Herbert and Ingeborg Pfiller, a married couple from France;
and Bruno Baldazari of Italy.
   It listed six Americans, three Spaniards, two Italians, two
French, one Briton and one Brazilian among the injured.
   Prior to Tuesday's crash, the last major air accident here
occurred Dec. 9 when a twin-engine Navy Fokker F-27 crashed off
Lima's Pacific coast, killing 44 people, including nearly the entire
squad of Peru's No. 1 soccer team Alianza Lima.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
