<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Ecclesia-Abuse 2ndLd-Writethru a0793 10-26 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ecclesia-Abuse, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0793,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Funeral Held for Girl Beaten to Death in Oregon</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th graf: `The girl's ..., to UPDATE
with Broussard's relative calling group a cult; Picks up 9th graf:
`Meanwhile in ...; SUBS last graf to ADD Broussard's full name; ADDS
1 graf with hearings delayed for those charged in death.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 8-year-old girl allegedly beaten to death
at an Oregon farm while other children watched and counted the blows
was laid to rest Wednesday, with a plea from her uncle to ``learn to
love another better.''
   Dayna Lorea Broussard died Oct. 14 at the home used by Ecclesia
Athletic Association, a group founded by her father, Eldridge
Broussard Jr. purportedly to train ghetto youngsters to be
world-class athletes and entertainers.
   The girl was beaten and whipped by members of the group,
authorities alleged. Four people were charged with manslaughter.
   Broussard was not among the 150 family members and friends who
filled the Angelus Funeral Home, where the little girl lay in an
open pink casket.
   ``Little Dayna is in the arms of Jesus now,'' said the Rev.
Charles Bereal, pastor of Calvary Bible Church of Compton. ``She's
safe. Amen.''
   ``We're the ones who are left behind,'' he said. ``We're the ones
who are still struggling.''
   In his eulogy, Bereal asked mourners to trust in God with the
simplicity of a child. ``Adults have a tendency to be proud,''
Bereal said. ``A child will willingly go, saying, `I trust you. I
humble myself to you.'''
   The girl's uncle, Henry Webb, told mourners: ``This is an
experience that we've never experienced before. Through this
experience may we learn to love one another better and to experience
life more.''
   The girl's cousin, Michael Bereal, who acted as a pallbearer,
said most members of the family were deeply troubled by Broussard's
actions.
   ``It's a cult,'' said Bereal, ``I hope the authorities break all
that stuff up. It's all El Broussard _ he's the whole problem.''
   Meanwhile in Los Angeles, a misdemeanor complaint alleging child
endangerment and inflicting illegal corporal punishment was filed
Wednesday against Alvin Elvis Broussard, the 25-year-old brother of
Eldridge Broussard Jr.
   The complaint stemmed from a police visit to the Watts Christian
Center on Oct. 16, prompted by news reports of Dayna's death in
Oregon, said Mike Qualls, a spokesman for City Attorney James K.
Hahn.
   ``While the officers were at the center, they noticed that a
10-year-old boy had bruises on his head and chest,'' Hahn said in a
prepared statement. ``They questioned him about his injuries and he
told them Alvin Broussard had struck him with a rubber hose and a
closed fist.''
   Alvin Broussard initially was booked for investigation of felony
child endangerment, but the case subsequently was referred to Hahn's
office for misdemeanor prosecution, said Deputy City Attorney Alice
Hand.
   In Oregon, authorities said the children, who were kept in a
sparsely furnished, four-bedroom farmhouse, were subjected to
ritualistic beatings of up to 800 strokes with a paddle or
electrical cord.
   In some cases, including the beating death of Dayna, children
were forced to watch and keep count, authorities said. The beatings
were intended to enhance athletic performance, not to punish
misbehavior, authorities have said.
   The children, mostly from the impoverished Watts section of Los
Angeles, were kept in the farmhouse near Sandy, about 30 miles
southeast of Portland.
   The state of Oregon has taken 53 children into protective custody
from the farm. Two other children involved in the group are in
custody in Los Angeles.
   Eldridge Broussard Jr. has denied that the children were beaten
or abused, saying they were only ``spanked.''
   The four suspects in the girl's death, all of whom have pleaded
innocent to first-degree manslaughter charges, remained in custody
Wednesday after defense lawyers asked that scheduled release
hearings be delayed. A defense lawyer said the attorneys haven't had
enough time to review investigative reports in the case.
</TEXT>
