<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DrugAgentSlain     10-26 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Agent Slain,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendant Sentenced to 10 Years in DEA Agent's Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Mexican drug trafficker convicted in the
torture-murder of a U.S. drug agent was sentenced Wednesday to life
in prison plus 240 years by a judge who said the evidence was
conclusive.
   Rene Verdugo Urquidez, 36, who admitted to running a major
marijuana trafficking organization, arose to protest his innocence
in court before he was sentenced.
   He slumped slightly as U.S. District Judge Edward Rafeedie
announced the concurrent sentences, which will make Verdugo
ineligible for parole for at least 60 years.
   Earlier, Rafeedie sentenced a co-defendant, Jesus Felix
Gutierrez, to 10 years in prison following his conviction as an
accessory after the fact.
   Felix, 38, was convicted of helping Mexican drug lord Rafael Caro
Quintero escape to Costa Rica following the 1985 torture-murder of
Enrique Camarena, a U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration agent.
   Camarena had been investigating Caro's drug smuggling empire in
Mexico when he was kidnapped outside the U.S. consulate in
Guadalajara on Feb. 7, 1985.
   Camarena's battered body was found, along with the body of his
pilot, in a shallow grave at a remote ranch 65 miles southeast of
Guadalajara on March 5, 1985.
   Verdugo declared through an interpreter: ``You are judging an
innocent person. That's all I have to say.''
   His attorney, Michael Pancer, also argued passionately before
sentencing that the jury verdict was wrong.
   ``This is the most difficult moment I've had in court in 20
years,'' the attorney said. ``I know it's important for counsel to
accept the verdict, but your honor, I can't do that.
   ``The verdict was not correct, because Mr. Verdugo is innocent of
wrongdoing in this case,'' Pancer said.
   The prosecutor, Assistant U.S. Attorney Jimmy Gurule, told the
judge that the jury was right and he urged the judge to send a
powerful message to drug traffickers by imposing a stiff sentence.
   Verdugo was typical of a band of ``narco-terrorists'' who are
``attacking the foundation and fabric of society,'' Gurule said.
   Rafeedie rejected the prosecutor's request for a 900-year
sentence, and instead imposed four consecutive 60-year terms on four
of the counts and a single life imprisonment sentence on another
charge.
   ``The fact of the matter is the evidence is conclusive and
undisputed,'' Rafeedie said, ``that on the date that the murder and
torture was taking place that (Verdugo) was at that house.''
   He added, ``There is enough here on the part of the jury to find
participation on the part of Mr. Verdugo.''
   Earlier, Rafeedie ordered that Felix serve his 10-year sentence
after his current 15-year term for marijuana trafficking.
   Felix's lawyer, Barry Tarlow, had argued that his client's role
was minor and that he was far less important in the overall scheme
of Camarena's murder than two co-defendants also convicted in the
Camarena case.
   The third defendant, Raul Lopez Alvarez, is to be sentenced
Friday.
</TEXT>
