<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Holocaust-Desecration     10-26 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holocaust-Desecration,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Holocaust Memorial Desecrated With Swastikas, ``No Remorse'' Slogan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swastikas and the words ``No Remorse''
were discovered Wednesday painted on a prominent Holocaust memorial
containing ashes of Jews who died in the Auschwitz concentration
camp.
   The desecration of the monument with anti-Semitic graffiti
stunned members of the Jewish community, who said the words written
on the 11-year-old memorial demonstrated that whoever committed the
vandalism fully understood the significance of the site.
   ``I was absolutely distraught. It was as if the seas of Nazism
were once again flourishing,'' said Arthur Spiegel, executive vice
president of the Jewish Federation of New Haven.
   The vandalism was the first incident of desecration to the
memorial since someone tried to burn down six yew bushes at the site
10 years ago, Spiegel said.
   The memorial is located in a small park situated along a major
city artery. Spiegel summoned police to the site after being alerted
early Wednesday morning of the vandalism.
   Two swastikas were spray-painted on the monument's brass plaques,
and the words ``No Remorse'' and ``White Power'' were written on the
concrete base, Spiegel said.
   The brass monument depicts the barbed wire fences of the Nazi
concentration camps. A statement dedicating the memorial to the six
million Jews who died in the Holocaust is written in English,
Yiddish and Hebrew.
   Ashes recovered from the Nazi concentration camp in Auschwitz,
Poland, were re-interred in the base of the memorial, and local
Holocaust survivors who have ``no other cemetery to go to'' visit it
to say prayers for family members and friends who perished in the
war, Spiegel said.
   Spiegel said the use of the slogan ``No Remorse'' indicated to
him that an adult was responsible for the desecration. ``Youngsters
don't use the word `remorse.' That is not in a child's vocabulary,''
he said.
   City police Major Thomas Muller said an investigation was
continuing, and that police could not yet say whether the act was
the work of a youngster or an adult.
   The swastikas and slogans were all removed, with the only lasting
damage occurring to the brass plates, Spiegel said.
   The memorial, designed by a Christian architect who accepted no
payment for his services, was erected in 1977.
   Plaques recognizing the role of ``righteous gentiles'' who helped
Jews during the war and servicemen who fought the Nazis were added
to the memorial site.
   The monument was the first of its kind in the country built
jointly by a municipality and a Jewish organization, he said.
   About 300 of the estimated 25,000 Jews living in the New Haven
area are Holocaust survivors, according to the Jewish Federation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
