<1ST_LINE>a a PM-GreatLakesPilots ADV02   10-26 0841</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Great Lakes Pilots, ADV 02,0865</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wednesday PMs, Nov. 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Learning To Sail The Seas At The Great Lakes Maritime Academy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEOFFREY HAYNES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a darkened classroom, a slide
projector beams a photograph of a bend in the St. Marys River where
crosscurrents have fooled some of the most experienced Great Lakes
freighter pilots.
   The students studying the narrow river stretch make mental notes
for the day they will steer a hulking 700-foot lake freighter
through the same winding passage.
   For cadets at the Great Lakes Maritime Academy, such training in
current navigational technology is combined with the guidance of
experienced sailors.
   ``It's much better training than you can get on a ship because we
can simulate near-collisions or running aground,'' said Rear Adm.
James F. McNulty, superintendent of the academy, which is part of
Northwestern Michigan College.
   Graduates of the three-year deck officer program can be licensed
to pilot commercial vessels, starting at $18,000 to $20,000 a year.
   Does the reality of life on the high seas match the adventure and
glamor of Great Lakes folklore?
   ``I wouldn't recommend it for anyone who doesn't like getting
dirty or who needs to see a movie every night or who likes to run
out to the store,'' said graduate Candace Peterson, 30, of Two
Harbors, Minn., one of few women working on the U.S. fleet on the
Great Lakes.
   ``There's no glamour in it at all. But it's wonderful going home,
knowing you've made a good wage and have choices of what to do with
your money,'' said Peterson, third assistant engineer on the USX
Corp.'s fleet. She expects to make $30,000 to $40,000 this shipping
season.
   New graduates typically work as relief help for vacationing
sailors or those who take advantage of their 30 days shore leave for
each 90 days worked, McNulty said.
   In his first job after graduating in 1985, John Basile piloted a
tour boat around Escanaba, Mich., for $8 an hour. The following two
years, he worked as a fill-in deck hand, making $20,000 to $25,000
each year.
   ``I've loved the water all my life and wanted to have something
to do with it,'' said Basile, who now sails lake freighters with
Inland Lakes Management of Alpena. ``I wanted to make a lot of money
and I didn't want to spend a lot of time in college.''
   McNulty has been speaking to the Elks, Optimists and Kiwanis
clubs, trying to recruit students from Cleveland, Milwaukee and
throughout Michigan. The task isn't easy.
   ``In the early 1980s, the opportunities for graduates were not
good and the news was widespread,'' he said.
   Great Lakes shipping slumped in the early 1980s due mostly to a
slipping demand for steel. The 1987 season was brisk, and through
August of this year, the most recent figures available, shipments of
iron ore, coal and stone were up 13.5 percent over the same
eight-month period last year, said Glenn Nekvasil, spokesman for the
Lake Carriers Association.
   By 1991, at least 71 pilots and 69 engineers will be needed by
the 14 shipping companies that comprise the Lake Carriers
Association to fill vacancies created by retirement, the
Cleveland-based association says.
   McNulty, an ebullient 58-year-old Irishman who earned the rank of
rear admiral in the U.S. Navy before retiring, became director of
the academy in 1984.
   Enrollment is 57 students this year; its high was 210 in 1981.
   Among the school's benefactors is Canadian balladeer Gordon
Lightfoot, who underwrites a $5,000 annual scholarship. His donation
came after one of the school's cadets died in the sinking of the
Edmund Fitzgerald on Lake Superior in November 1975, the subject of
a hit song by Lightfoot.
   The academy is one of six regional state-run facilities in the
United States. It is considered quasi-military, but except for
requiring cadets to wear khaki-colored pants and shirts and black
shoes, military rules are absent, McNulty said.
   The school offers two programs. One trains cadets to become deck
officers who can eventually pilot the Great Lakes freighters that
primarily haul iron ore, stone and coal. The second program trains
cadets to maintain equipment on the commercial vessels.
   Subjects include naval science, nautical rules, ship construction
and ship stability and ship handling. Both programs lead to an
associate of applied science degree.
   The three-year programs include nine months of training on a
commercial freighter. That's when many students learn whether life
on the seas is for them.
   ``A lot of youngsters decide they want to become sailors after
reading some romantic novel,'' McNulty said. ``It's not all like
that, it can be very dull.''
   Of each 50 students who enroll in the program, McNulty said about
15 drop out.
   ``We've lost a couple good ones to love,'' McNulty said. ``They
get back and their girl says, `If this is the way it's going to be,
get yourself another girl.' To be a sailor's wife, it takes a
special kind of gal.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, Nov. 2</NOTE>
