<2ND_LINE>BC-House, ADV 30,0892</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 30 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Elections Expected to Result in Few Changes In House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Richard H. Stallings sat nervously on the
House floor as the seemingly interminable 100th Congress lurched
toward adjournment more than 2,000 miles from his Idaho
congressional district.
   Stallings, a two-term Democrat, is one of about 40
representatives who face tough re-election fights, and the
late-night House sessions forced him to cancel a series of campaign
appearances. ``Nothing replaces the individual contact with the
constituents,'' he said.
   Activists from both parties expect that when the smoke clears,
many of those struggling incumbents _ about evenly divided between
both parties _ will be victorious. And if history repeats itself,
nearly all of the 408 members of the House seeking re-election will
be there when the 101st Congress convenes in January.
   In 1986, 385 of the 393 House incumbents seeking re-election _ 98
percent _ were victorious. Of the winners, nearly nine out of every
10 captured at least 60 percent of the major party vote, considered
a landslide margin.
   ``Accountability to voters may be a vestigal memory,'' says
Michael Waldman, legislative director of Congress Watch, a frequent
critic of congressional practices. ``Members fear popular
discontent, but they really needn't be because it rarely results in
their defeat.''
   Presidential elections can affect congressional races, but House
incumbents from the party that loses the White House rarely suffer
massive losses. When President Reagan swamped Walter Mondale by
taking 49 states in 1984, Republicans picked up only 14 seats in the
House. The Republicans gained 34 House seats on Reagan's coattails
in 1980, yet Jimmy Carter brought in only one additional House
Democrat in 1976.
   Even with Republican presidential nominee George Bush showing a
steady lead over Democratic rival Michael Dukakis in the polls, no
one expects the Democrats' 255-177 advantage in the House _ there
are three vacancies _ to be seriously diminished.
   Spokeswoman Peggy Connolly of the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee says the overall change in the parties' numbers
in the chamber will probably be two to five seats in either
direction. Steven Lotterer, National Republican Congressional
Committee spokesman, said he expects the GOP to gain some seats, but
adds, ``No one's looking to take over the House.''
   A large reason for this is that incumbents have several built-in
advantages. Their districts, drawn up by their home-state
legislatures, are often shaped to include as many friendly voters as
possible.
   They usually have a much easier job than their opponents do of
raising campaign money. For the 1986 elections, candidates in the
435 House races spent $211 million, with incumbents outspending
challengers by almost 3-to-1.
   In addition, incumbents have staffs, district offices, mailing
privileges, telephones, and other perks that they can turn to their
political advantage.
   They also get to introduce legislation that helps the folks back
home. In the final days of the 100th Congress, Stallings got the
House to pass legislation designating a new national reserve and a
national monument in southern Idaho.
   ``While my opponent is issuing press releases, I'm back here
legislating,'' he said of his rival, Republican Dane Watkins.
   Stallings, of course, was not the only House member last week
eagerly awaiting the chance to return to his district for
campaigning. Some other incumbents who face stiff challenges are:
   _Seven-term veteran Rep. Robert J. Lagomarsino, R-Calif., whose
challenger _ state Sen. Gary K. Hart _ atypically expects to spend
the same $1 million the incumbent has budgeted.
   _Rep. Jim Bates, D-Calif., whose GOP opponent, attorney Rob
Butterfield, received a boost from reports that Bates has sexually
harassed female staff aides.
   _Rep. Pat Swindall, R-Ga., who was running a tight race against
Democrat Ben Jones even before Swindall's indictment on charges of
lying to a grand jury investigating money laundering.
   _Rep. John Hiler, R-Ind., who faces a rematch with Democrat Tom
Ward, whom he defeated by 47 votes in 1986's closest congressional
contest.
   _Rep. Clyde Holloway, R-La., who like two years ago is challenged
by Democrat Faye Williams. The economically blighted district is 85
percent Democratic and 35 percent black, but Holloway, a white,
defeated Williams, who is black, by 51 percent to 49 percent last
time.
   _Rep. Bill Emerson, R-Mo., a four-term member who underwent
treatment for alcoholism. His district is one of the poorest in the
country. He faces Democrat Wayne Cryts, whom he narrowly defeated in
1986.
   _A slew of North Carolina incumbents, including Democratic Rep.
David Price, who is challenged by Republican Tom Fetzer; Democratic
Rep. Stephen Neal, who faces Republican Lyons Gray; GOP Rep. Howard
Coble, who won by 79 votes in 1986 and now faces Democrat Tom
Gilmore.
   _Rep. Peter Kostmayer, D-Pa., who has already had his five-term
House career interrupted by a defeat and faces GOP former state Sen.
Ed Howard.
   _Rep. Liz Patterson, D-S.C., a well-liked first-term member who
faces Republican Knox White, a 34-year-old Greenville city
councilman who is trying to paint the congresswoman as a liberal.
   _Rep. Mac Sweeney, R-Texas, a two-term lawmaker who is the first
Republican to represent his district since Reconstruction, facing
Democratic lawyer Greg Laughlin, his 1986 opponent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
