<1ST_LINE>s p BC-Governors ADV30   10-26 0834</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Governors, ADV 30,0857</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 30 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Democrats Lead in Rhode Island, Indiana, Utah and West Virginia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats are given a good chance of retaking the governor's
mansion in Rhode Island, Indiana, Utah and West Virginia as 12
states fill their top job in contests that have grown closer and
nastier with the approach of Election Day.
   Allegations of racism shadow Indiana's campaign; in Rhode Island,
the hiring of a reputed mobster's ex-wife for a state job has become
an issue, and the race in North Carolina has used television with
notably creative malice.
   Democrats hold 27 of the 50 governorships. Nine incumbents _ six
Republicans and three Democrats _ will be on the ballot. Republican
Robert Orr of Indiana is barred by law from a third term; Montana
Democrat Ted Schwinden and New Hampshire Republican John Sununu are
retiring.
   If Massachussetts' Michael Dukakis is elected president, Lt. Gov.
Evelyn Murphy, also a Democrat, will serve out his term, which
expires in 1990. In Nevada, Lt. Gov. Bob Miller will complete the
two years remaining in fellow Democrat Dick Bryan's term if Bryan is
elected to the Senate.
   Other states electing governors are: Delaware, Missouri, North
Dakota, Vermont and Washington.
   In Rhode Island, Republican Gov. Edward D. DiPrete faces Democrat
Bruce G. Sundlun in a battle largely over ethics. A poll last week
for WPRO radio and WLNE-TV poll had Sundlun leading 44 percent to 35
percent. The margin of error was 5 points.
   The poll came after the former wife of a reputed mobster was
given a job at the Governor's Justice Commission and fired in an
uproar two days later.
   Sundlun, a communications executive who lost to DiPrete by a
landslide in 1986, also has capitalized on news stories about
DiPrete family land deals, an unfinished bridge, and state contracts
awarded to DiPrete campaign contributors.
   DiPrete, in turn, has accused Sundlun of business misconduct and
mismanagement.
   Republican Gov. Arch Moore's bid for an unprecedented fourth term
in economically depressed West Virginia appears headed for defeat at
the hands of an insurance executive and political novice who spent a
record $2.1 million on the primary alone. Unemployment is high and
the government had to borrow $80 million to keep going this year.
Democrat Gaston Caperton held a double-digit lead in recent polls.
   In Indiana, Republican Lt. Gov. John M. Mutz is turning up the
heat in an underdog race against the 32-year-old son of former Sen.
Birch E. Bayh, a contest being watched for the coattail effect of
the Bush-Quayle ticket in Sen. Dan Quayle's home state.
   Evan Bayh, Indiana secretary of state, leads by a much as 13
points in the most recent polls and stands to become the first
Democrat elected governor of Indiana since 1964.
   Mutz has charged that a Bayh TV commercial ``appeals to the
darker side of the human personality'' by evoking racist sentiments
against the Japanese. The ad contends many of the best jobs at a
state-subsidized Subaru-Isuzu auto plant will go to workers of
Japanese ancestry.
   An indignant Bayh responded, ``I would never do anything to
appeal to anyone's racial bigotry.''
   In Utah, Republican Norm Bangerter's bid for a second term is in
deep trouble against Democrat Ted Wilson, former mayor of Salt Lake
City. Wilson leads by as much as 12 points, down from 20 last month,
and independent Merrill Cook has robbed Bangerter of support from
conservative Republicans who blame him for the biggest tax increase
in Utah history.
   In North Carolina, Republican Gov. Jim Martin leads Lt. Gov. Bob
Jordan, a Democrat, in a campaign that has made for good TV.
   Jordan has lampooned Martin's budget-writing process with a
commercial starring chimpanzees in business suits. Martin has run an
ad with footage of Jordan telling black newspaper editors he agrees
with them on some issues but won't discuss them publicly for fear of
alienating ``rednecks.''
   DELAWARE _ Republican Michael Castle has only token opposition in
his bid for a second term against Democrat Jacob Kreshtool.
   MISSOURI _ Republican Gov. John Ashcroft is strongly favored
against Democratic state Rep. Betty Hearnes, wife of a former
governor.
   MONTANA _ A comeback attempt by former Gov. Thomas Judge, a
Democrat, against Republican state Sen. Stan Stephens, is seen as a
toss-up.
   NORTH DAKOTA _ Democratic Gov. George Sinner holds a commanding
lead over Republican Leon Mallberg, a businessman making his first
run for statewide office.
   NEW HAMPSHIRE _ Republican Judd Gregg, a congressman and son of a
former New Hampshire governor, is heavily favored over Paul
McEachern, a fierce opponent of the Seabrook nuclear plant who ran
two years ago.
   VERMONT _ Madeleine Kunin, Vermont's first famale governor, has a
robust economy heavily in her favor against state House GOP leader
Michael Bernhardt.
   WASHINGTON _ Democrat Booth Gardner rolls toward re-election
against state Rep. Bob Williams, who comes out of the evangelical
wing of the Republican Party.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 30</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
