<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   10-26 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0595</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kraft Inc. has advised Philip Morris Cos.
Inc. to sweeten its $90 a share takeover bid to more than $110 a
share or stop pursuing its hostile offer.
   Kraft Chairman John Richman's letter to Philip Morris on Tuesday
follows Kraft's announcement of a recapitalization plan that company
officials claimed would bring shareholders more than $110 a share in
cash and securities.
   The recapitalization plan was announced Sunday after Kraft
rejected as inadequate Philip Morris' surprise $90-a-share, or $11
billion, buyout offer of last week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minorco SA has dropped its $4.73 billion hostile
bid for Consolidated Gold Fields PLC after the British government
said it would investigate the deal's effect on the market for
strategic metals.
   Tuesday's developments followed a U.S. district judge's decision
in New York on Monday to issue a temporary injunction against the
offer on antitrust grounds.
   Consolidated Gold Fields has resisted the buyout overture.
Minorco is the Luxembourg-based investment arm of the South African
gold and diamond mining giants, Anglo American Corp. and De Beers
Consolidated Mines Ltd.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of Popeyes Famous Fried Chicken and
Biscuits is launching a cash tender offer for Church's Fried Chicken
Inc. that values its fast-food chicken restaurant rival at about
$290 million.
   The deal announced Tuesday, if completed, would combine the
second and third largest fast-food chicken chains in the nation. The
biggest is Kentucky Fried Chicken, a unit of Pepsico Inc. of
Purchase, N.Y.
   A. Copeland Enterprises Inc., based in New Orleans, said it was
offering $8 a share for each of Church's 36 million shares. Church's
management, based in San Antonio, Texas, urged its shareholders not
to tender their shares until its board could review the offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court jury has rejected a $6.5
billion lawsuit filed by a widow who claimed her husband died of
liver damage from taking two Tylenol products at the same time.
   The U.S. District Court jury deliberated about an hour Monday
before rejecting the negligence suit filed by Silvia Jauchler, whose
husband Maurice died last year.
   Johnson & Johnson attorney Robert E. Christiansen said Tylenol
did not cause the dead man's problem and that the company was
grateful for the jury's verdict.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Mobil Corp. and Chevron Corp. each have reported double-digit
third quarter profit gains, while profits at Texaco Inc. and
Phillips Petroleum Co. more than doubled in the latest period.
   Meanwhile, Shell Oil Co., Sun Co. and Amerada Hess Corp. each
reported sharp declines Tuesday in their net earnings due partly to
declining crude oil prices.
   The larger oil companies said earnings were both hurt and helped
by falling crude prices. Lower costs for the raw product contributed
to higher profit margins in refining and marketing operations but
eroded gains in exploration and production.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WHEELING, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new contract with the United
Steelworkers union is one of the major obstacles as
Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp. prepares to present its
reorganization plan to federal bankruptcy court.
   Company President and Chief Executive Officer William
Scharffenberger said Tuesday that negotiating an equitable labor
agreement ``is the single most important task still before us.''
   Scharffenberger said the next contract between management and
workers will determine whether Wheeling-Pittsburgh can compete in
the global steel economy after emerging from bankruptcy.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
