<DOCNO> AP881026-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0039EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   10-26 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0570</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department says orders for
``big-ticket'' durable goods plunged an unexpected 4.1 percent in
September.
   Total orders fell $5.0 billion to a seasonally adjusted $117.7
billion last month, pulled down by dramatic declines in the volatile
defense and transportation sectors.
   But economists said Tuesday's report does not necessary mean that
the red-hot manufacturing boom is ending.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes fell 2.2 percent in
September after a surprisingly strong summer that was sparked by a
decline in fixed-rate mortgage interest rates during August,
according to a trade group.
   The National Association of Realtors said Tuesday sales of
existing homes declined to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.63
million units last month, following a 2.2 percent increase in August.
   But last month's level was still higher than most economists
would have predicted this spring, when mortgage interest rates began
to creep higher.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wages have risen an average 3.9 percent over
the last 12 months, according to the Labor Department, but private
employer costs for benefits have soared 6.7 percent largely on
increases in Social Security taxes.
   The combined effect of the pay raises and higher benefit costs
have sent total employer costs up 4.7 percent in the 12 months
ending Oct. 1, compared with a 3.4 percent rise in the previous
12-month period, the Labor Department said Tuesday.
   Inflation, as measured by the Consumer Price Index, has risen by
4.2 percent over the past 12 months, the government reported last
week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major builders' association has found no
evidence that energy-efficient homes increase radon concentrations
and is advising its members to build homes as tight as possible.
   ``Our practices recommend good air sealing techniques,'' just as
would be used in trying to save energy, John Spears, program manager
for the National Research Center, which is affiliated with the
National Home Builders Association, said Tuesday.
   Some analysts have suggested the increasing importance being
placed on energy efficiency also may be increasing the tendency of
radon, an odorless, radioactive gas given off by all soils, to
concentrate indoors.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MAYNARD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Digital Equipment Corp. has announced plans
to buy back shares with a current market value of more than $900
million, boosting its stock price as takeover rumors swirled.
   Analysts said a takeover bid for the computer company, the
world's second biggest after IBM, seemed unlikely and described the
buyback as a step to take advantage of the stock's bargain price
while doing something to benefit its shareholders.
   Digital's stock rose $2 a share to $92 a share Tuesday in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading, following a rise of $3
a share on Monday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished narrowly mixed Tuesday. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials closed up 3.02 at 2,173.36.
   The dollar finished mixed against most major currencies. Gold
prices rose.
   Bond prices were mixed, with the yield on the Treasury's 30-year
bond up to 8.93 percent from 8.91 percent.
   Cocoa futures prices fell sharply on New York's Coffee, Sugar &
Cocoa Exchange. On other markets, wheat, soybean and grain futures
were lower; precious metals futures advanced; energy, livestock and
meat futures were mixed.
