<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Stabilize in Quiet Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Calm and caution have returned to the energy
futures market as traders await further developments from OPEC.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the December contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, picked up 9 cents
to settle at $13.26 a barrel on Tuesday. Other contract months
declined slightly.
   On Monday, the December contract had plunged $1.20 a barrel amid
speculation that OPEC would continue flooding world markets with
crude after failing to reach an accord on limiting rampant
overproduction by its members.
   Trading was light Tuesday and prices moved in a narrow range
``while people figure out what to do,'' said Greg Dreis, a trader
with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries has several
more meetings scheduled for next month, and until then, traders are
expected buy or sell in response to any news that indicates whether
the cartel can rein in its output.
   While traders were hesitant in buying crude Tuesday, they
purchased wholesale unleaded gasoline futures enthusiastically. The
November contract for gasoline rose 1.98 cents on the mercantile
exchange to close at 51.94 cents a gallon.
   Demand for gasoline has run high while supplies are low, Dreis
said.
   Home heating oil, which is more plentiful, was mixed. The
November contract for heating oil rose 0.46 cent to close at 40.36
cents a gallon, but subsequent contract months declined.
</TEXT>
