<DOCNO> AP881026-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0056EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GoldFields     10-26 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gold Fields,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minorco Drops Hostile Bid For Consolidated Gold Fields</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minorco SA's decision to drop its proposed $4.73
billion hostile takeover of Consolidated Gold Fields PLC does not
necessarily mean the South African partnership is halting its
pursuit of Gold Fields, analysts say.
   Minorco dropped its bid Tuesday after the government's Monopolies
and Mergers Commission said it would investigate the deal's impact
on the market for strategic metals, effectively blocking the deal
from proceeding for up to three months.
   The offer _ the biggest takeover bid ever for a British company _
had been conditioned on it not being referred to the commission.
   Although some analysts said Minorco might sell its 29.6 percent
stake in Gold Fields, others said Minorco likely would wait to see
the outcome of the investigation, and proceed with a new bid if the
commission rules in its favor.
   The developments followed a U.S. district judge's decision in New
York on Monday to issue a temporary injunction against the offer on
antitrust grounds. Gold Fields had contended that a takeover by
Minorco would give that company control of 35 percent of the Western
world's gold supplies, compared with its present 20 percent share.
   Gold Fields owns a 49.3 percent stake in New York-based Newmont
Mining Corp., plus minority stakes in Australian and South African
mining companies. Minorco has said it would sell Gold Fields'
Newmont and South African holdings if its bid succeeded.
   Minorco's offer was for 19 pounds ($33.25) in cash and one
Minorco share for every two Gold Fields shares it didn't already
own. At Tuesday's closing level for Minorco shares of 658 pence
($11.52), the offer valued each Consolidated Gold Fields share at
12.79 pounds ($22.38).
   Consolidated Gold Fields' shares plummeted on news of the
referral, falling 106 pence ($1.85) to finish at 11.39 pounds
($19.97) on London's Stock Exchange.
   Graham Birch, an analyst with the London investment firm
Kleinwort Grieveson Securities Ltd., said, the commission's decision
was a setback for Minorco. But he said the commission likely would
rule in Minorco's favor and that Minorco could then revive its bid.
   Gold Fields has raised strong objections to being acquired by a
company that is South African-controlled. Minorco is the
Luxembourg-based investment arm of the South African gold and
diamond mining giants, Anglo American Corp. and De Beers
Consolidated Mines Ltd. The wealthy South African Oppenheimer family
holds unspecified stakes in the latter two companies.
   Minorco is unlikely to return to its former role of passive
investor in Gold Fields, which it has played since first taking a
significant stake in the company in the early 1980s, analysts agreed.
   Gold Fields Chairman Rudolph Agnew said at a news conference that
the company plans to continue its defensive tactics, including
taking steps to boost its share price. Agnew, who said he was
``delighted'' by the decision to turn the case over the monopolies
commission, would not elaborate on what steps Gold Fields might take.
   Trade Secretary Lord Young, who referred the matter to the
monopolies commission, asked it to report to him within three months.
   The investigation will center on the proposed takeover's impact
on strategic metals, titanium and zircon in particular, a spokesman
at the Department of Trade and Industry said.
   ``It was thought a merger would lead to greater concentration of
the world's supply, which would be a potential detriment to users in
the U.K.,'' said the department spokesman, who spoke on condition he
was not identified.
   Titanium, a metal largely used as a whitener in paints, also is
used in jet engines. Zircon is mainly used as a refracting agent in
glass and steel furnaces, but is also a critical substance in
nuclear submarines and power plants, and in rocket nose cones.
   One possible course of action that could satisfy the commission
would be for Minorco to sell Consolidated Gold Fields' interests
related to the strategic metals titanium and zircon, analysts said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
