<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   10-26 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mid-October Sales Up for U.S. Makers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. automakers say they sold 14.8 percent more
cars and light trucks in mid-October than they did one year ago,
when the stock market crash and lack of dealer incentives kept
buyers away from showrooms.
   Automakers on Tuesday reported selling 318,664 cars and light
trucks during the Oct. 11-20 period this year, compared with 246,835
during the same period last year.
   There were nine selling days in mid-October this year and eight
last year, so the percentage change is based on the daily sales rate
rather than on total sales for the period.
   For months, the year-to-year sales comparisons have been colored
by heavy use of incentives in the summer and early autumn of 1987.
But most of those incentives expired Oct. 1, 1987, while incentives
continued this month, further fogging comparisons.
   Sales in mid-October 1988 were beginning to return to a more
normal pace, said analyst Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc.
   ``We're beginning to compare against a very weak period last
year, including the October 19 stock market crash,'' she said.
``You're probably going to see the same kind of numbers in the next
10-day period.''
   Among the Big Three automakers, Chrysler Corp. car sales rose to
29,269 this year from 19,909, a 30.7 percent increase on the basis
of daily sales in the mid-October period. This year, Chrysler has
sold 873,107 cars, compared with 775,401 cars it had sold by Oct. 20
last year, a 12.1 percent rise.
   Part of the mid-October increase, Heaney said, is attributable to
Chrysler's shifting some small-car production in 1987, and the
introduction of two popular large cars.
   ``You have the (Dodge) Dynasty and (Chrysler) New Yorker which
were launched at this time last year and those sales ... have been
strong all year,'' she said. ``That helps build this number up.''
   Ford Motor Co. reported a 14.4 percent surge in its car sales in
mid-October, going to 59,613 this year from 46,335 last year. So far
this year, Ford has sold 1,803,920 cars, an 8.9 percent rise from
the 1,650,391 cars it sold through Oct. 20 last year.
   General Motors Corp., the nation's largest automaker, said it
sold 93,086 cars during mid-October, up 8.1 percent from the 76,509
cars it sold during the same period last year. In 1988, GM's car
sales have increased 0.3 percent to 2,984,066 from 2,962,654 last
year.
</TEXT>
