<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     10-26 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Slightly Higher In Quiet Trading, Gold Also Up Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose slightly in quiet European trading
this morning as the market waited for release of the preliminary
report on U.S. economic growth in the third quarter.
   Gold prices also were up slightly in calm trading.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the third-quarter gross national
product figures scheduled for release later today would probably
provide some guidance to the market.
   One Frankfurt dealer said the market expects a 3 percent to 3.5
percent rise in the GNP. ``It's nothing much to look forward to,''
the dealer said, noting that the GNP expanded at a 3 percent pace in
the second quarter.
   A trader in Rome predicted the GNP figures would have little
impact on the foreign exchange market.
   ``Maybe it will move the waters for about 10 minutes, but the
dollar is basically trendless,'' he said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.07 yen to a closing 126.80 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 126.85 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.7913 West German marks, up from 1.7860; 1.5190
Swiss francs, up from 1.5175; 6.1175 French francs, up from 6.1100;
2.0173 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0170; 1,332.30 Italian lire, up
from 1,332.00; and 1.2015 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1990.
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.7525 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7535 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $407 a troy ounce, down
from Tuesday's late bid of $407.25. But at midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a higher recommended price of
$407.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $407.40, up from $407 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.24 to close at a bid $409.76.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.24 a troy
ounce, down from Tuesday's late bid of $6.25.
</TEXT>
