<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     10-26 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Sags, Stocks Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched down against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices rose on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 139.95-point winner
Tuesday, added another 199.11 points, or 0.73 percent, to finish
trading at 27,620.60. The Nikkei quickly gained 99.51 points when
the morning session began and continued rising afterwards.
   A broker with Daiwa Securities said dealers who had been
restrained by uncertainty over Emperor Hirohito's continuing illness
finally began reacting to favorable economic indicators and started
buying stocks.
   ``People were looking around for a wide variety of issues,'' he
said, speaking anonymously. He added that this helped boost
Wednesday's trading volume, which was estimated at 1.9 billion
shares on the first section.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 126.80 yen,
down 0.07 yen from the previous day's close of 126.87 yen. The
currency opened at 126.67 yen and slightly fell while moving in a
tight range of 126.64-126.80 yen.
   The dollar-yen rate changed very little with many dealers waiting
on the sidelines, according to a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo.
   ``Although dollar-buying by speculative investors increased on
the Tokyo market, the dollar did not recover much mainly because
overseas markets were selling it,'' he said, also speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Other dealers said investors were in a wait-and-see mood before
the release of the U.S. gross national product figure for the third
quarter due later today in Washington.
</TEXT>
