<DOCNO> AP881026-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0912EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 2ndLd-Writethru   10-26 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GNP Rose A Modest 2.2 Percent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS New 5th graf, In the ..., to UPDATE with bond market
reax. Picks up 5th graf pvs, The Commerce ... Will be led with third
quarter collective bargaining agreements, scheduled for late morning
EDT release. Previous Economy Rdp should have moved as 1st Ld-
Writethru</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's economy grew at a modest 2.2 percent annual rate in
the third quarter, the poorest performance in about two years, the
government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said the summer drought, a deterioration
in the nation's trade performance and a drop in government purchases
of defense equipment were responsible for the week growth.
   The changes left the gross national product, the broadest measure
of the economy's health, rising at the slowest pace since a 1.4
percent increase in the fourth quarter of 1986.
   The GNP advance was down from increases of 3.4 percent in the
first quarter and 3 percent in the second quarter of this year.
   In the bond market, a sensitive barometer of inflation and
interest rate trends, prices rallied following the report. The
Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond was up about $5 per $1,000 face
amount, while its yield fell to 8.87 percent from 8.93 percent
Tuesday.
   The Commerce Department reported Tuesday that total orders for
durable goods fell $5.0 billion to a seasonally adjusted $117.7
billion last month, pulled down by dramatic declines in the volatile
defense and transportation sectors.
   The dollar edged lower against the British pound and Japanese yen
but managed to rise against other major currencies. The pound was
quoted in late New York trading at $1.7515, up from $1.7501 late
Monday, while the dollar declined to 126.80 yen from 127.02 yen.
   The stock market finished narrowly mixed as a trading frenzy in
takeover issues subsided. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
gained 3.02 points to close at 2,173.36.
   Currency traders took the decline in durable goods orders as a
sign that the U.S. economy could be slowing down, something that
would tend to reduce demand for dollars by foreign investors.
   But economists were reluctant to conclude that the nation's
manufacturing boom is ending.
   In other economic news on Tuesday:
   _The National Association of Realtors said sales of existing
homes fell 2.2 percent in September after a surprisingly strong
summer. The decline occurred despite a housing boom in California.
   _Automakers reported that sales of U.S.-made cars and light
trucks rose 14.8 percent in mid-October from a weak period a year
earlier.
   _The government said wages in the past 12 months have risen an
average 3.9 percent. Private employer costs for benefits have soared
6.7 percent _ more than double the previous year _ largely on
increases in Social Security taxes.
   The durable goods report for September fits in with other signs
of a slowdown last month, including the second consecutive decline
in retail sales and a drop in manufacturing employment.
   But analysts said it was too soon to declare that manufacturing,
which has driven robust economic growth this year, is slowing
significantly.
   A boom in export sales, fueled by the lower value of the dollar,
has kept factories humming. Manufacturers in turn have invested
heavily to expand the capacity of their plants, spurring the fastest
growth in capital spending since 1984.
   Durable goods, items expected to last three or more years,
include a wide range of manufactured items, from refrigerators and
other household appliances to large computers and battleships.
   Orders had jumped 5.7 percent in August, plummeted 7.4 percent in
July and soared 8.7 percent in June.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
