<HEAD>Current Account Shows Record Surplus In September</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spurred by strong exports, South
Korea's current account surplus for September was a record high
$1.44 billion, the Bank of Korea reported Wednesday.
   The surplus was $1.12 billion in September 1987. The previous
record was $1.3 billion last June, the bank said.
   The current account broadly measures a country's financial flow
and includes trade in goods and services and other transfers.
   Officals at the central bank said South Korea's current account
surplus was expected to reach $13 billion by year's end, exceeding
the previous record of $9.85 billion last year.
</TEXT>
