<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Earns-Autos 1stLd-Writethru   10-26 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Earns-Autos, 1st Ld-Writethru,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Announces 3rd Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with stock price; picks up 4th
graf pvs, The earnings ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. said today its earnings
rose 21.8 percent to a record in the third quarter compared with the
same three-month period last year, based on strong overseas sales.
   The nation's No. 2 automaker said it earned $856.3 million, or
$1.78 per share, in the July-September period, up from $703.2
million, or $1.38 per share, during the third quarter of 1987.
   Revenue rose nearly 16 percent to $17.7 billion from $15.3
billion a year earlier.
   Ford's stock fell 37{ cents a share to $53.62{ a share by
midmorning on the New York Stock Exchange as the overall market lost
ground.
   The earnings during the quarter were down 48.4 percent from the
company's industry record of $1.66 billion in earnings in the second
quarter. Typically, third-quarter earnings are lower than other
quarters for automakers because of factory retooling to gear up for
the new model year, which traditionally begins Oct. 1.
   ``The Ford team's successful effort worldwide to provide products
with improved quality and good customer value again is evident in
our third-quarter results,'' Ford Chairman Donald Petersen and Vice
Chairman Harold Poling said in a joint statement.
   The company said its overseas earnings amounted to $384 million
during the quarter, up 249 percent from the $110 million earned from
overseas operations during the period last year.
   In the United States, the company's earnings fell 20.4 percent to
$472 million during the third quarter this year from $593 million
during the period last year. Ford blamed the performance on higher
costs for new products and lower earnings by Ford's Financial
Services Group.
   General Motors Corp. and Chrysler Corp. are expected to announce
their third-quarter earnings figures Thursday.
   For the first nine months of the year, Ford's earnings rose 12.2
percent to $4.1 billion, or $8.53 a share, on sales of $60.9
billion, compared with earnings of $3.7 billion, or $7.17 a share,
on sales of $52.9 billion, a 12.2 percent increase.
   For the first two quarters of 1988, Ford posted industry world
records, making $1.62 billion in the January-March period and $1.66
billion in the April-June period.
   In the first two quarters of this year, Ford said its
record-setting profits also were bolstered by strong international
sales, mostly from Europe. Ford's domestic sales fell during the
first half of the year compared with the first six months of 1987,
because of incentives, higher labor and material costs, and
development of new products.
   Ford said losses in its Financial Services Group and product
costs were offset partially by higher shares of the car and truck
markets and more efficient manufacturing processes.
   The Financial Services Group, which includes Ford Credit, First
Nationwide, U.S. Leasing and the company's international credit
operations, added 35 cents per share to third-quarter earnings, 14.6
percent less than the group contributed during the third quarter of
last year.
   The company said benefits from a lower tax rate and increased
receivables were offset by lower earnings at Ford Credit and First
Nationwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881026-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-InsiderTrading-Wang 1stLdWritethru   10-26 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Insider Trading-Wang, 1st Ld Writethru,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wang Sentenced In Second Biggest Insider Trading Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines pvs; adds details and byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stephen Wang, a former rookie securities analyst
who pleaded guilty to participating in the second biggest insider
trading case in history, was sentenced to three years imprisonment
today by a federal judge who told him, ``You had a brilliant future
and you blew it.''
   Wang, 24, stood motionless as U.S. District Court Judge Kevin
Duffy lectured him about his illegal act before imposing the
sentence, which also includes three years' probation.
   Wang, who would be eligible for parole after a year, could have
been sentenced to five years and heavy fines for each of three fraud
counts against him.
   Shaking his head, Duffy said, ``Stephen Wang, I hope to God you
never end up in a court of law again.''
   Wang, a former junior analyst at the investment firm Morgan,
Stanley & Co., admitted to scheming with Taiwan-born businessman
Fred C. Lee to profit on secret tips about impending corporate
takeovers that Morgan Stanley was handling. Lee, who is not in the
United States, allegedly made $19 million on the information
provided between July 1987 and April 1988, and paid $200,000 to Wang.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission, which sued the pair in
late June, had demanded the return of the illegal profits plus
triple damages for a total of $76 million, making it the second
biggest insider trading case behind that of convicted felon Ivan
Boesky.
   In 1986, Boesky agreed to pay a $100 million penalty to settle
charges of trading on insider information. He is serving a
three-year prison term after pleading guilty last year to conspiring
to file a false statement with the SEC.
   Before Wang was sentenced his lawyer, Ira L. Sorkin, told the
judge his client ``fully recognizes the seriousness of the crimes.
At no time has he sought to minimize his involvement or the
seriousness of what he has done.''
   Sorkin said, ``He's broke, he has no job, he's unable to finish
his education, he has no place to live except with relatives. He
disgraced his family and hurt the firm that trusted him.''
   Wang, wearing a gray suit with a dark, dotted tie, told Duffy,
``I'm deeply sorry for what I've done. I've incurred a lot of debts
and losses of other people. I'm going to try to make amends for it.''
   But Duffy, calling it a particularly troubling case, rebuked Wang
because he had grown up in an affluent family and had no excuse for
what he did.
   ``Apparently, the first time you could have been a crook, you
were,'' Duffy said.
   ``In the eyes of society, a person who knowingly goes out to harm
the world, becomes a person who must be punished,'' the judge said.
   Duffy said a fine was inappropriate because Wang had no money.
   ``As far as I can figure out, you're worth zero,'' the judge
said. ``Therefore any punishment at all has to be in the area of
imprisonment.''
   Duffy gave Wang one month to get his affairs in order before
surrendering to the U.S. Bureau of Prisons. The exact location of
his imprisonment has not been determined, but Sorkin told reporters
afterward he would try to have Wang placed in a facility near his
family, who live in the Chicago area.
   Sorkin declined to comment on the appropriateness of the
sentence, saying, ``I don't try to second-guess judges.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney John McEnany also declined comment on the
sentence. He also would not comment on possible efforts to prosecute
Lee, who is believed to be in Hong Kong.
</TEXT>
