<1ST_LINE>r f BC-CrayResearch     10-26 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Cray Research,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts: Cray Earnings Revision Hurts Credibility On Wall Street</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be led by 5:30 p.m. EDT with closing stock price.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cray Research Inc.'s announcement that its
1988 earnings growth would be less than expected not only caused one
of the largest one-day declines in the supercomputer maker's stock
but also hurt its credibility on Wall Street, analysts say.
   ``Cray is getting savaged by earnings revisions,'' said Michael
Geran, an analyst in New York for Nikko Securities Co. International
Inc.
   Earlier this year, Cray predicted 10 percent earnings growth for
1988, but on Monday it reduced that to 5 to 7 percent.
   On Tuesday, Cray's stock on the New York Stock Exchange lost $9
to close at $59.87{, a decline of 13.1 percent on a trading volume
of nearly 1.7 million shares. It slipped another 12{ cents in early
trading today to $59.75 a share.
   In the past two years, the stock has traded has high as $135 a
share.
   Analysts said the one-day decline Tuesday was the largest they
could remember for Cray, and they attributed it to Monday's surprise
announcement.
   ``I think there's been credibility damage, and there will be a
lingering impact,'' said Gary Smaby, a Minneapolis-based analyst for
Needham & Co. Inc. in New York.
   ``The fact is that we've seen nothing but news of decreasing
earnings expectations for the last year and a half, and a lot of
investors are fatigued with the story,'' said Jeffrey Canin, an
analyst for Hambrecht & Quist in San Francisco.
   ``Investors looking to get into the stock now are going to have
to take a longer-term investment horizon, about 12 to 18 months,''
Smaby said. ``There will be no meaningful (earnings and revenues)
growth next year.''
   Cray said the decline in anticipated 1988 earnings is primarily
the result of an additional $10 million in spending on the Cray-3
supercomputer, the latest development of company founder Seymour
Cray.
   Next year's revenues are expected to be adversely affected by
increasing trade-in allowances and a shift toward computers being
leased rather than sold, the company said.
   Canin said Cray is moving through a difficult product transition
period from the Cray-2 to the not-yet-introduced Cray-3 and from the
enhanced versions of its older Cray X-MP supercomputers to the new
Cray Y-MP.
</TEXT>
