<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1111EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Delchamps     10-26 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delchamps,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A&P Withdraws Offer For Delchamps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTVALE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supermarket giant A&P today withdrew a $210
million tender offer for Delchamps Inc., a day after directors of
the Mobile, Ala.-based grocery chain rejected a higher merger
proposal.
   At a meeting late Monday, Delchamps directors decided A&P's
proposal to acquire the chain for $32-a-share, or $32 a share in a
friendly transaction was inadequate.
   James Wood, chairman and chief executive of The Great Atlantic &
Pacific Tea Co. called that proposal a ``final'' offer. The company
had a $30-a-share tender offer outstanding.
   A.F. Delchamps Jr., chairman of the board and president of the
company that bears his name, replied: ``We would hope that Mr. Wood
can be taken at his word, since we agree with him that the
dissension brought on by this takeover fight is not in the best
interest of our company or our shareholders.''
   Joel Swanson, a Delchamps spokesman, said the nine-member board
unanimously rejected the sweetened offer. A&P began trying to buy
Delchamps two years ago, but this year became more aggressive by
launching a tender offer.
   Delchamps attorney James H. McDonald Jr. said the board's
decision was based on a number of factors, including Delchamps
recent store expansion efforts and other programs designed to
enhance the value of the company.
   He said the board's decision was also based upon the advice of
counsel that such a takeover could pose antitrust problems.
   Delchamps has a federal court suit pending in Mobile against A&P
on the antitrust allegations. A&P, which is 52 percent owned by the
Tengelmann Group of West Germany, filed a countersuit.
   Delchamps had sales of about $700 million last year. A&P had
sales of $9.6 billion in 1987 from its 1,170 stores in this country
and Canada.
   Delchamps has 103 stores in Alabama, Mississippi, Florida and
Louisiana, and six liquor stores.
 
</TEXT>
