<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   10-26 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0245</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mixed to
slightly lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Analysts called the market featureless.
   Soybean futures were mostly lower because of favorable weather
reports in the growing regions of South America and sizeable
domestic stocks.
   Wheat futures nudged ahead following a U.S. Department of
Agriculture report that India would purchase 1 million tons under
the export bonus program, and smaller overnight buys by Japan and
the Philippines may have supported prices as well.
   On the opening, wheat was 1\ cent lower to { cent higher, with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.07} a bushel; corn was {
cent to 1 cent lower, with December at $2.73 a bushel; oates were
unchanged to 1 cent higher, with December at $2.36{ a bushel; and
soybeans were 3 cents lower to 2{ cents higher, with November at
$7.58{ a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures were lower on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent to .40 cent lower, with the December
contract at 74.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .12 cent to .35
cent lower, with October at 81.75 cents a pound; live hogs were .12
cent to .37 cent lower, with December at 42 cents a pound; and
frozen pork bellies were .50 cent to 1.05 cents lower, with February
at 50.45 cents a pound.
