<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Tenneco     10-26 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tenneco,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tenneco Initiates Cash Offer for Stock Buyback</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a move to increase its stock value, Tenneco
Inc. initiated a cash tender offer today to buy back 18 million
shares of its own stock for more than $1 billion through a ``Dutch
auction.''
   Tenneco Chairman James L. Ketelson said the sale of Tenneco Oil
earlier this month and the proposed repurchase of 12.18 percent of
Tenneco's total outstanding stock demonstrates the company's
commitment to increasing shareholder value by concentrating its
resources on its ``most promising'' opportunities.
   However, some on Wall Street were expected to view the terms of
the share repurchase as disappointing.
   In a Dutch auction, which Tenneco launched early today,
shareholders specify the price at which they are willing to sell
their stock back to the company, within a range established by the
buyer.
   Based upon the number and price of the shares tendered, Tenneco
officials said they will determine the single per share price within
a specified $50-$55 range that will permit the company to buy all 18
million shares. Tenneco then will buy the stock tendered at that
price or less, subject to possible proration.
   The cash sales will not be subject to the usual transaction costs
associated with open market sales, Tenneco officials said.
   John Olson, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., said a
Dutch auction is ``probably the most sensible way'' to buy back
stock. But he said Tenneco's offer is not likely to win acclaim on
Wall Street where analysts were expecting a more conventional offer
at a higher price of $60 or so.
   On the New York Stock Exchange Tenneco's shares were trading at
$50{ this morning, up from $49.875 on Tuesday.
   Olson said Houston-based Tenneco is passing up a ``God-given
opportunity'' to build the strongest balance sheet in years.
   ``Buying back stock may be attractive to some shareholders, but
it doesn't augment the company for the long term,'' Olson said.
   He attributed that buy-back decision to Tenneco's management
being under pressure to ``do something for the shareholders.''
   ``They sold off their crown jewel (Tenneco Oil). That gives them
a great opportunity to go into the next business downcycle with a
strong balance sheet and golden opportunities to acquire companies
in related areas that would be hard hit by any recession,'' Olson
said.
   Tenneco's offer is not conditioned upon any minimum number of
shares being tendered. The only condition, company officials said,
is that Tenneco receive at least $1.5 billion in proceeds from its
$7.3 billion sale of Tenneco Oil. The tender offer is set to expire
at midnight Nov. 28.
   After paying for the stock, the company will use the remainder of
the proceeds to reduce its hefty debt of $8.5 billion.
   With the sale of its oil and gas properties, Tenneco's biggest
units will be the profitable natural gas pipeline and its Case IH
farm equipment manufacturing sector.
   In addition, Tenneco maintains shipbuilding, automotive,
packaging and chemicals units.
</TEXT>
