<2ND_LINE>PM-Employment Costs, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0021,0960</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Employment Costs Rose Faster Than Inflation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 25th graf pvs, Other cities ... to restore names of New
Jersey cities. Also moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employment costs have risen faster than
inflation over the past 12 months, but largely because of soaring
benefit costs primarily from higher Social Security taxes rather
than wage gains, according to new government data.
   Wages in the 12 months ended Oct. 1 rose an average of 3.9
percent, the Labor Department said Tuesday, compared with a 4.2
percent increase in consumer prices over the same period.
   But benefit costs have soared more than 6.7 percent _ more than
double the 3.1 percent gain during the previous 12 months, the
department's Bureau of Labor Statistics said.
   The combined effect of the pay raises and higher benefit costs
sent total employer costs up 4.7 percent in the 12 months ended Oct.
1, compared with a 3.4 percent rise in the previous 12-month period,
it said.
   The steep increase in benefit costs resulted primarily from a
rise last January in employers' Social Security tax rate from 7.15
percent to 7.51 percent, the government said.
   But there also were large increases in health insurance costs the
first nine months of this year, it noted. And for the first time,
the government is calculating lump-sum bonus payments from union
contracts and profit-sharing arrangements as a benefit.
   Previously those bonuses had not been included as either wages or
benefits.
   Non-union employees continued to get bigger percentage pay raises
than union members _ a trend begun in 1983 _ except for blue-collar
workers in manufacturing.
   The Labor Department said wage rates among union members rose an
average 2.9 percent in the past 12 months, compared with 3.9 percent
for non-union workers. In the previous 12-month period, union wages
rose an average 1.7 percent, compared with 3.8 percent for non-union
employees.
   ``This pattern reversed when limited to blue-collar workers in
manufacturing,'' the bureau said, with wage increases in the past
year averaging 3.2 percent for union members and 2.8 percent for
non-union workers.
   Including the lump-sum bonus arrangements that have become a norm
in many labor contracts, especially in manufacturing, total employer
compensation costs have risen the same 4.5 percent for union and
non-union workers nationwide, the bureau said.
   John Zalusky, an economist for the AFL-CIO, called the statistics
``refreshing.''
   ``We expected they were in that range,'' Zalusky said. ``They're
(the government) beginning to show in fact what is really going on
out there in the world, but there still is a good way to go.''
   For example, Zalusky cited the last round of steel industry
contracts in which the union conceded pay cuts to companies then
operating at losses in exchange for a share of future profits or
stock transfers if no profits occurred.
   ``The statistics are now picking up the profit distributions but
not the stock transfers for what essentially is a debt owed
workers,'' he said. ``In the future I expect them to start putting
in the value of stock ownership plans and in the distant future
retraining funds, such as those negotiated with the auto companies.''
   Despite the disparity in percentage wage increases in recent
years, union workers continue to make 35 percent more than non-union
workers _ an average gap of $123 a week in 1987 compared with a gap
of $119 in 1986 _ on a nationwide basis, according to government
data.
   Among white-collar workers, wage increases averaged 4.2 percent
over the past 12 months, compared with 4 percent the previous 12
months, the government said. Blue-collar wages have increased 3.3
percent and 2.6 percent, respectively, over the same two periods.
   The biggest pay gains, 5.6 percent on average, were among
business and health service workers, followed by average increases
of 4.9 percent for professional and technical employees.
   Managers and executives, along with state and local government
workers, have averaged the same 4.7 percent wage gains over the past
year. The average pay increase among private industry workers was
3.7 percent.
   By regions, the biggest pay increases over the past 12 months
have been in the Northeast, 4.6 percent, followed by the South at
3.8 percent. Average raises in the West and Midwest were 3.2 percent
and 2.9 percent, respectively.
   In a separate report, the Labor Department said annual pay rose
an average 4.6 percent among the 101 million workers with jobs in
the nation's 317 metropolitan areas last year.
   Kenosha, Wis., with large pay increases in manufacturing and
construction, had the biggest average increase, up 10.6 percent _
from $18,666 in 1986 to $20,648 in 1987.
   The New Haven-Waterbury-Meriden area of Connecticut and the
Monmouth-Ocean City, N.J., metropolitan areas were next with average
annual pay increases of 8.4 percent last year.
   On the other end of the scale, workers in Flint, Mich., with a
large decline in employment and falling wages in manufacturing,
suffered an average pay loss of 4.2 percent _ from $26,633 in 1986
to $25,514 last year.
   Other cities where average pay fell last year were Anchorage,
Alaska; Anderson, Ind.; Enid, Okla.; Lawrence, Kan.; Lansing, Mich.;
Midland, Texas; Middlesex-Somerset-Hunterdon, N.J.; and Pine Bluff,
Ark.
   Despite the decline, Anchorage maintained the highest average pay
level in the country at $28,486. New York City was next at $28,179,
followed by the Bridgeport-Stamford-Nowalk-Danbury area of
Connecticut at $27,832 and San Jose, Calif., at $27,748.
   Jacksonville, N.C., again had the lowest average annual pay at
$13,246, followed by three Texas border areas:
McAllen-Edinburg-Mission at $13,311, Brownsville-Harlingen at
$14,087 and Laredo at $14,093.
 
</TEXT>
