<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     10-26 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0356</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market lost ground today in an
unenthusiastic response to new evidence of slowing economic growth.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped 8.53 to 2,164.83
by noontime on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 3 to 2 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 493 up, 745 down and
527 unchanged.
   The government estimated this morning that the gross national
product grew at a 2.2 percent annual rate, after adjustment for
inflation, in the third quarter of the year.
   That fell short of most advance estimates, and marked the slowest
pace since the final three months of 1986.
   Wall Street has been looking for evidence of slower business
expansion growth as reassurance that the economy was not approaching
the point of overheating.
   But the details in the latest data did not support hopes for an
improved international trade balance, increased business investment
and a slackening in consumer spending.
   The dollar weakened after the report was issued and so, after a
brief period of hesitation, did stock prices as well.
   Losers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, down ~ at 122; General Electric, down \ at 44]; Eastman
Kodak, down [ at 48}, and International Paper, down { at 47\.
   Bethlehem Steel, by contrast, rose 1\ to 21{ in active trading.
The company reported sharply higher operating earnings for the third
quarter.
   Sears Roebuck, widely rumored in recent days to be considering a
restructuring or other transaction, gained 1\ to 45.
   Wickes climbed 1{ to 9]. Following the recent abandonment of a
$12-a-share management buyout plan for the company, a group of
investors offered to take it over for $11.25 a share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
.62 to 158.25. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .68 at 303.70.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 91.74 million shares at noontime,
up from 77.69 million at the same point Tuesday.
</TEXT>
