<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Earns-GMSubsidiaries     10-26 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Earns-GM Subsidiaries,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GMAC Has Loss, EDS Gains As GM Units Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s credit arm said today an
interest rate pinch cut its third-quarter earnings by 25.5 percent
from a year earlier.
   General Motors Acceptance Corp. reported net income of $241.9
million from its auto financing, insurance and mortgage operations
in the three months ended Sept. 30, down from $325 million for the
third quarter of 1987.
   GMAC said the decline was due primarily to a narrower margin
between interest earned on money loaned out and interest paid to
obtain the funds. Its average cost of borrowings worldwide was 8.41
percent for the quarter, compared with 7.89 percent in the same
period last year.
   Also, GMAC financed or leased 496,000 new cars and trucks in the
United States during the period, a 42 percent decline from a 1987
third-quarter boosted by factory-supported financing incentives.
   GMAC's earning assets reached $90.6 billion as of Sept. 30, up 2
percent from a year earlier, the company said.
   Also reporting earnings today was GM's computer-services
subsidiary, Electronic Data Systems Corp., which said new commerical
contracts helped boost third-quarter net income 17 percent as
revenues grew 9 percent.
   EDS reported third-quarter net income of $95.9 million, or 79
cents per share of the GM Class E common stock that has its returns
based on EDS earnings. That compared with $82.3 million, or 68 cents
a share, in the third quarter of 1987.
   Revenues were $1.22 million, up from $1.13 million in the
year-earlier quarter.
   GM's third major subsidiary, GM Hughes Electronics, was expected
to report its earnings later. GM is scheduled to report its earnings
Thursday.
</TEXT>
