<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BoeingOrder     10-26 0118</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Boeing Order,0125</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EgyptAir Orders 2 Boeing Jets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   EgyptAir, flag carrier of the Arab Republic of
Egypt, has ordered two Boeing 767-300 twinjets equipped for extended
range service, Boeing Commercial Airplanes announced Wednesday.
   The two wide-bodied 767s will be delivered in August and
September 1989, Boeing said.
   In EgyptAir's seating configuration, the 767-300 will accommodate
236 passengers.
   EgyptAir already owns three 767-200s, also extended-range
aircraft.
   Boeing gave no dollar value for the sale, but in the past the
company has said the extended-range 767-300s sell for between $66
million and $72 million.
   To date, Boeing has announced orders for 326 767s from 35
customers worldwide. Of those aircraft, 127 are the longer-fuselage
-300 model.
</TEXT>
