<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Nabisco     10-26 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nabisco,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nabisco Ends Talks With KKR on $20 Billion Buyout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc. said today it has ended talks
with Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. over joining with the investment
firm in a $20.3 billion leveraged buyout of the food and tobacco
conglomerate.
   Following a meeting of outside directors here, Nabisco President
F. Ross Johnson said the group concluded the Kohlberg proposal was
``not in the best interest of the company, its employees or the
diverse communities it serves.''
   Johnson said Nabisco would continue to work with Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc., its financial partner, to ``explore the possibility of
making an offer to acquire the company.''
   Last week the Nabisco management team announced it was
considering offering $75 a share to take the company private, a bid
that would be worth about $17 billion. On Monday, New York-based
Kohlberg said it planned to launch a $90-a-share tender offer for
the maker of such products as Oreo cookies and Winston cigarettes.
   A spokesman for Kohlberg said the firm had no immediate comment.
   Nabisco management, Shearson and Kohlberg have discussed various
combinations of a joint bid, so far without success.
   On the New York Stock Exchange, trading in Nabisco stock was
halted because of an imbalance in buy and sell orders. The last
trade prior to the halt put Nabisco shares at $85.
</TEXT>
