<DOCNO> AP881026-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1500EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   10-26 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0241</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
higher Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade after sinking in six
of the past eight sessions.
   Analysts described the trading as generally featureless.
   ``Ninety percent of the trading today was short-covering,'' said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
Chicago. ``More and more people holding short positions started to
cover as they realized the market wasn't going to break any lower.''
   In a short sale, a trader sells a borrowed security in the
expectation that prices will head lower before he must replace it.
   Wheat futures got some support from a U.S. Department of
Agriculture report that India would purchase 1 million tons of wheat
under the export bonus program, and smaller overnight buys by Japan
and the Philippines may have supported prices as well.
   Some spillover strength, as well as speculation that lower prices
would help stimulate export business, nudged prices ahead in the
surrounding pits.
   On the close, wheat was unchanged to 2 cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.09 a bushel; corn was \ cent
to 2\ cents lower, with December at $2.76 a bushel; oats were
unchanged to 2 cents higher, with December at $2.36{ a bushel; and
soybeans were 6 cents lower to { cents higher, with November at
$7.61 a bushel.
