<1ST_LINE>r f AM-EnronLayoffs     10-26 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Enron Layoffs,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Enron to Lay Off 250</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 250 Enron Corp. employees are being
laid off as part of a reorganization program that will combine
positions in the company's corporate staff and natural gas pipeline
group, the company said Wednesday.
   Enron Chairman Kenneth L. Lay cited intense competition for
natural gas markets coupled with low sales prices as primary reasons
for the staff reductions.
   Affected employees were notified Wednesday, Executive Vice
President Richard D. Kinder said. Some of the reductions will be
effective immediately, while others will occur during the remainder
of the year.
   Enron has about 6,900 employees, including 3,000 in Houston.
   The cuts include jobs at all levels, including officers. Human
Resources Vice President Luther Snow is one executive whose position
was eliminated. The action follows the elimination of about 35 jobs
in Enron Oil & Gas Co., a subsidiary, in late September.
   Kinder said Enron expects the reorganization to save $15 million
a year.
   ``It is not a pleasant thing to do, but you can't operate in this
environment without paying attention to your staff costs,'' he said.
   Some of the affected employeees may be offered other jobs in the
Enron organization. Others will receive severance pay and assistance
in finding jobs elsewhere.
   In addition to the layoffs, the company is negotiating sales of
some oil and gas assets valued at between $200 million and $300
million, Lay said.
   The properties involved are primarily interests in wells and
fields operated by other companies and most sales should be
completed by year's end.
</TEXT>
