<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Oil     10-26 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Oil,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Occidental Profit Up; Coastal Earnings Decline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Occidental Petroleum Corp. said Wednesday that third-quarter
earnings more than doubled because of strong gains in its chemical
unit, while Coastal Corp. said lower crude oil prices drove
quarterly earnings down sharply.
   Occidental's earnings surged 128 percent to $105 million or 38
cents a share in the three-month period ended Sept. 30, compared
with $46 million or 20 cents a share a year earlier.
   The Los Angeles-based company said revenue rose 16.7 percent to
$4.9 billion from $4.2 billion in the 1987 quarter.
   Occidental Chairman Armand Hammer said healthy advances in the
company's chemical operations offset declines elsewhere.
   ``Although Occidental has experienced the detrimental earnings
effects of lower oil prices, which in the third quarter of 1988 were
more than $4 a barrel less than last year, and the loss of our North
Sea oil production, we are pleased to report that our chemical
operations' earnings have significantly increased and have resulted
in Occidental's net income more than doubling compared to the third
quarter of 1987,'' Hammer said.
   Occidental owned the huge oil rig that exploded and sank July 6
in the North Sea, killing more than 160 people in the world's worst
oilfield disaster.
   Falling crude oil prices, caused by an excess supply on world
markets, has hurt earnings and revenue of most major U.S. oil
companies. But some have managed to compensate with gains in
refining and marketing operations.
   For the first nine months of 1988, Occidental's earnings totaled
$295 million or $1.23 a share, up 46 percent from $202 million or 90
cents a share a year earlier. Revenue totaled $14.1 billion, up 11
percent from $12.7 billion.
   Houston-based Coastal Corp. said earnings fell 21.4 percent in
the latest quarter to $9.2 million or 12 cents a share on revenue of
$1.8 billion, vs. $11.7 million or 17 cents a share on revenue of
$1.6 billion a year earlier.
   For the first nine months of 1988, Coastal's earnings rose 10.5
percent to $86.3 million or $1.45 a share, from $78.1 million or
$1.43 a share in the same period last year. The company's revenue
totaled $5.7 billion, up 16.3 percent from $4.9 billion a year
earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
