<TEXT>
   The stock market retreated Wednesday as new
evidence of slowing economic growth failed to catch traders' fancy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 8.18 to 2,165.18.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
624 up, 814 down and 528 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 181.55 million
shares, against 155.19 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those
stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market,
totaled 216.82 million shares.
   The government estimated Wednesday morning that the gross
national product grew at a 2.2 percent annual rate, after adjustment
for inflation, in the third quarter of the year.
   That fell short of most advance estimates, and marked the slowest
pace since the final three months of 1986.
   Wall Street has been looking for evidence of slower business
expansion to provide reassurance that the economy was not
approaching the point of overheating.
   But the details in the latest data did not support hopes for an
improved international trade balance, increased business investment
and a slackening in consumer spending.
   The dollar weakened after the report was issued and so, after a
brief period of hesitation, did stock prices as well.
   Losers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, down 1\ at 121|; McDonald's, down | at 47{; Eastman Kodak,
down \ at 48|; Coca-Cola, down } at 43}, and American Telephone &
Telegraph, down \ at 27].
   Bethlehem Steel, by contrast, rose 1{ to 21} in active trading.
The company reported sharply higher operating earnings for the third
quarter.
