<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-GMSubsidiaries     10-26 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-GM Subsidiaries,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mixed Results for GM Units</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s aircraft, auto-electronics
and computer-services subsidiaries reported third-quarter gains on
Wednesday while an interest rate pinch cut earnings at its financing
arm.
   General Motors Acceptance Corp., the credit arm, said its net
income sagged 25.5 percent for the three months ended Sept. 30
compared with the third quarter of 1987.
   Sales of a new air-to-air missile helped boost third-quarter
earnings 5.3 percent at GM Hughes Electronics Corp., comprising
Hughes Aircraft Co. and Delco Electronics Corp.
   Electronic Data Systems Corp., the computer-services arm, said
new commercial contracts contributed to a 17-percent earnings rise.
   GM is scheduled to report its companywide earnings Thursday.
   GMAC said net income from auto financing, leasing and mortgage
operations was $241.9 million for the three months ended Sept. 30,
down from $325 million in the third quarter of 1987.
   A narrower margin between the interest earned on money loaned out
and the interest costs to obtain the funds was the main cause of the
decline, GMAC said.
   The company said its average cost of borrowings worldwide rose to
8.41 percent in the third quarter, up from with 7.89 percent in the
same period last year.
   And GMAC said it financed or leased 496,000 new cars and trucks
in the United States during the period, a 42 percent drop from the
third-quarter in 1987 when business was boosted by factory-supported
financing incentives.
   For the first nine months of 1988, GMAC's consolidated net income
totaled $930.2 million, down from a record $1,218.2 million for the
same period last year.
   GMAC's earning assets reached $90.6 billion as of Sept. 30, up 2
percent from a year earlier, the company said.
   GM Hughes Electronics Corp. reported third-quarter earnings of
$180 million, or 45 cents a share of GM Class H common stock, an
issue the earnings of which are determined by GM Hughes Electronics'
performance.
   That compared with $171 million, or 43 cents a share, in the
third quarter of 1987. Quarterly revenues were $2.63 billion, up
from $2.52 billion a year earlier.
   Revenue rose as the armed forces built up inventories of Hughes'
Advanced Medium Range Air to Air Missile that recently entered
production, spokesman Bruce McCristal said.
   Revenues were partly offset by research and development costs for
the HS601 communications satellite, a new design that will be
capable of extending solar-power arrays up to 100 feet long,
McCristal said.
   He said a continuing increase in electronic equipment in cars and
trucks kept earnings on the rise at Delco.
   For the first nine months, GM Hughes Electronics reported
earnings of $633 million, or $1.58 a share, on revenues of $8.2
billion, up from $524 million, or $1.31 a share, on revenues of $7.8
billion in the first nine months of 1987.
   Electronic Data Systems Corp. reported third-quarter net income
of $95.9 million, or 79 cents per share of GM Class E common stock.
That was up from $82.3 million, or 68 cents a share, in the third
quarter of 1987.
   EDS revenues were $1.22 billion, up from $1.13 billion in the
year-earlier quarter.
   EDS, which provided GM's information services needs, said it
expanded its commercial computer services to include retailers such
as Riser Foods Inc. in Ohio as well as its international and
governmental customers and financial institutions.
   EDS reported net income of $280.7 million, or $2.30 a share, on
revenues of $3.24 billion for the first nine months of the year, up
from $218.9 million, or $1.80 a share, on revenues of $3.24 billion
in the same period last year.
</TEXT>
