<DOCNO> AP881026-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 1717EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-Autos Bjt   10-26 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Autos, Bjt,0730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Sets 3rd Quarter Earnings Record, But Loses Ground in U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. reported record
third-quarter earnings Wednesday and enhanced its reputation as the
most profitable automaker in the country, although the performance
of U.S. operations declined.
   The No. 2 vehicle producer behind General Motors Corp. earned
$856.3 million or $1.78 a share in the three months ended Sept. 30,
vs. $703.2 million or $1.38 a share a year earlier, a 21.7 percent
gain that made it the best third quarter in Ford's history.
   Third-quarter sales totaled $17.73 billion vs. $15.25 billion, a
15.1 percent gain.
   In the prior four quarters Ford outearned much larger GM. The
biggest U.S. automaker and No. 3 Chrysler Corp. were expected to
report third-quarter earnings Thursday.
   Industry analysts anticipated Ford would continue its string of
impressive earnings gains. For each of the past ten quarters, Ford
has set new earnings records for itself.
   ``My guess is that they will earn $1.3 (billion) or $1.4 billion
in the fourth quarter,'' said David Healy, who follows the industry
for Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. ``In 1987, it was a little over $900
million, so it looks like the next quarter will be up again,
easily.''
   Despite the earnings outlook, Ford's stock price fell 87{ cents a
share to $53.12{ on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Third-quarter auto company earnings usually are lower than other
quarters because of factory retooling to gear up for the new model
year, which historically has started Oct. 1.
   Ford said earnings this past quarter were based largely on strong
overseas sales and not its U.S. business.
   ``We do have a declining (profit) margin in the United States and
that's been the case all year,'' said David McCammon, Ford's vice
president for finance and treasurer. ``The overseas margin has been
increasing because of outstanding results this year in Europe and
also Latin America has come back substantially.''
   He pointed to Ford's performance in Mexico and with Autolatina, a
joint venture with Volkswagen AG in Brazil and Argentina. Ford owns
49 percent of Autolatina and McCammon declined to be specific about
its results.
   However, he said, ``Autolatina went from a substantial loss in
the last third quarter to a profit this quarter.''
   Analyst Ron Glantz of Montgomery Securities Inc. of San Francisco
said, ``I estimate (Autolatina) earned $70 million this quarter
versus a loss of $56 million last quarter.''
   Overall, Ford said it earned $384 million from overseas
operations in the third quarter of 1988, up 249 percent from the
$110 million earned overseas during the period last year.
   In the United States, the company earned $472 million in the
third quarter, down 20.4 percent from the $593 million earned a year
earlier.
   Because of the depressed U.S. results, profit sharing for
unionized workers will decline this year compared with last,
McCammon said. Although he wasn't specific , McCammon said it would
fall somewhere between the $3,700 average per worker in 1987 and the
$2,100 average the year before.
   McCammon blamed much of the U.S. decline on development of new
products, lower earnings by the company's Financial Services Group
and a problem with what kinds of cars were available.
   He said that during the quarter, the company produced 30 percent
fewer, high-profit Thunderbirds than a year earlier, while making
more Ford Tempos and Mercury Topazes, which carry less of a per-car
profit.
   Healy agreed, saying: ``The cost of everything they buy is up. So
that and the shutdown of the T'bird and Cougar had an effect on
their earnings for the U.S.''
   The Financial Services Group, which includes Ford Credit, First
Nationwide, U.S. Leasing and the company's international credit
operations, added 35 cents per share to third-quarter earnings, 14.6
percent less than the group contributed during the third quarter of
last year.
   The company said benefits from a lower tax rate and increased
billings were offset by lower earnings at Ford Credit and First
Nationwide.
   For the first nine months of the year, Ford earned $4.1 billion
or $8.53 a share, up 12.2 percent from earnings of $3.7 billion or
$7.17 a share a year earlier. Sales totaled $60.9 billion vs. $52.9
billion, a 15.1 percent gain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
