<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell Wednesday to its lowest point
since late June as traders reacted to a report of unexpectedly
modest growth in the U.S. economy. Gold prices rose.
   Slower growth reduces the chance that the Federal Reserve will
raise interest rates to cool off inflation, analysts said. Lower
U.S. rates would reduce demand for dollars.
   The Commerce Department said the gross national product, the
broadest measure of the economy, grew at a 2.2 percent annual rate
in the third quarter. The market had forecast a 3 percent to 3.5
percent rise.
   The GNP advance, down from increases of 3.4 percent in the first
quarter and 3 percent in the second quarter of this year, was the
smallest rise since a 1.4 percent increase in the fourth quarter of
1986.
   ``What this does is bring us closer to potentially lower interest
rates,'' said Craig Sloane, a currency analyst at Smith Barney,
Harris Upham & Co.
   The currency market's reaction to the GNP report was unusually
strong, partly because the market was prepared to drive the dollar
down anyway, traders said.
   In contrast, the bond market, which usually rallies at signs of
slower growth, posted only a modest increase.
   In Tokyo, before the report was released, the dollar eased 0.07
Japanese yen to a closing 126.80 yen. Later in London, after the
report's release, it dropped to 125.85 yen. In New York, the dollar
fell to 125.71 yen from 126.80 yen Tuesday.
   The dollar also fell against the British pound. It cost $1.7600
to buy one pound in late London trading, more expensive than $1.7535
late Tuesday. The pound rose to $1.7610 in New York from $1.7515
Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.7750 West German marks, down from 1.7903; 1.5042
Swiss francs, down from 1.5183; 1.1993 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2012; 6.0595 French francs, down from 6.1230; and 1,322.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,333.75.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.7745 marks, down from 1.7860; 1.5065 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5175; 6.0725 French francs, down from 6.1100;
2.0005 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0170; 1,323.50 Italian lire, down
from 1,332.00; 1.1988 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1990.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose $1.24 a troy ounce to close at a bid
$409.76. In London, gold fell to $407.05 a troy ounce from $407.10
Tuesday. In Zurich, it rose to $407.10 an ounce bid from $407
Tuesday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for
near-month delivery rose to $408.30 a troy ounce from $406.40
Tuesday.
   Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $408.15
an ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $406.60 late Tuesday.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a late bid price of $6.21 a troy
ounce, down from $6.25 late Tuesday. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for near-month delivery rose to $6.224 an ounce from $6.221.
</TEXT>
