<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Fruehauf     10-26 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fruehauf,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Varity Ends Acquisition Talks With Troubled Fruehauf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada's Varity Corp. has halted talks on the
possible acquisition of Fruehauf Corp., and the troubled
Detroit-based truckmaker said Wednesday it would explore other
options.
   Fruehauf reported a net loss of $41.5 million on sales of $1.84
billion in 1987.
   Varity spokesman J.R. Nowling said he didn't expect further
efforts to acquire Fruehauf though he didn't rule out discussions
about its Kelsey-Hayes automotive subsidiary.
   Fruehauf has struggled with large debts, high interest payments
and operating losses in its trailer and maritime operations since
managers took control of the company in December 1986 with huge
borrowings in a financial transaction known as a leveraged buyout.
   Fruehauf will continue to explore alternatives including
disposition of all or part of Kelsey-Hayes, its only profitable
unit, Fruehauf spokesman David Hladik said.
   Hladik said he knew of no specific suitors, but even during
discussions with Varity, ``We never closed the door to other
offers.''
   Formerly called Massey-Ferguson, Toronto-based Varity makes farm
and industrial machinery. Fruehauf makes truck trailers and
automotive and maritime products.
   Varity ended discussions with Fruehauf after a review of
Fruehauf's records and assets, Nowling said.
   He declined to elaborate on reasons. Asked if Varity will enter
further negotiations for Fruehauf, he said, ``I wouldn't think so.''
   Nowling said he didn't know if talks were likely regarding
Kelsey-Hayes, which makes auto and truck and industrial parts and is
a leading supplier of antilock brake systems.
   But he said, ``We announced when we initiated discussions in
August that Kelsey-Hayes was our primary interest.''
</TEXT>
