<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp 1stLd-Writethru   10-26 0782</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0807</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Industry Report Fuels Tumultuous Day in Petroleum Futures</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS lead to higher demand levels sted lower. Picks up 2nd
grfa pvs, In other ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures prices finished mostly higher Wednesday
following a tumultuous day of trading set off by a report showing a
sharp drawdown in gasoline reserves and higher demand levels.
   In other markets, livestock and pork futures fell; grain and
soybean futures rebounded slightly after declining for four straight
sessions, and precious metals were mixed in featureless trading.
   Gasoline stocks were considered to be ``the wild card'' in an
American Petroleum Institute report released after the markets had
closed Tuesday. The API report showed gasoline stocks fell by more
than 3 million barrels _ almost twice what some analysts expected.
   That, coupled with a rising demand for the product, pushed the
price of unleaded gas to 54.50 cents a gallon at one point on the
New York Mercantile Exchange.
   ``We're seeing demand of about 8 million barrels a day, and we've
only seen that six or seven times in the last two years ... and not
at all during the period from the late '70s until 1986,'' said Peter
Beutel, assistant director of Elders Futures Energy Group in New
York.
   ``We are back in the land of pre-conservation demand.''
   Still, many traders apparently believe gasoline may be near its
peak for the short term. Not only was there significant
profit-taking Wednesday, but many traders elected to reverse
previous positions, selling gasoline and buying heating oil.
   ``What you saw was everybody heading for the door at the same
time,'' said Jim Ritterbusch, a vice president at Carson Petroleum
Co. in Chicago. ``And the catalyst that set this in motion was the
fact that gasoline appeared so strong.''
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 15 cents to 19 cents
higher at the New York Mercantile Exchange, with the December
contract at $13.41; heating oil was .23 cent to 1.24 cents higher,
with November at 41.5 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was .35
cent lower to .20 cent higher, with November at 51.67 cents a gallon.
   Both livestock and meat futures were lower at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Pork futures were clobbered by a report released late Tuesday
that indicated the number of frozen pork bellies stored in
warehouses was the second-largest ever reported during October.
   ``That put a bearish shroud over everything on the floor,'' said
Chuck Levitt of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago.
   ``Cattle prices are suffering from a small pocket of heavyweight
cattle hanging over the market for the moment,'' he continued.
``They should have moved earlier this summer, but it will only take
a short while for them to get cleaned up and supplies to get tight
again.''
   Live cattle settled .25 cent to .85 cent lower, with December at
73.90 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .78 cent lower,
with October at 81.42 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent to 1.02
cents lower, with December at 41.27 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were 1.58 cents to 2 cents lower, with February at 49.50
cents a pound.
   Analysts said the grain market was in need of fresh news, and
none was forthcoming Wednesday. But declining prices fueled ideas of
renewed export bnusiness and helped lay the groundwork for a modest
rally.
   Wheat futures got some support from a U.S. Department of
Agriculture report that India would purchase 1 million tons under
the export bonus program. The notion that lower prices would
stimulate export business nudged prices ahead in the surrounding
pits.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 2 cents higher, with December contract
at $4.09 a bushel; corn was \ cent to 2\ cents lower, with December
at $2.76 a bushel; oats were unchanged to 2 cents higher, with
December at $2.36{ a bushel; and soybeans were 6 cents lower to 4{
cents higher, with November at $7.61 a bushel.
   Precious metals, meanwhile, finished the day mixed after holding
to a narrow range at the New York Commodity Exchange.
   Prices moved to session highs early when the U.S. dollar fell
because of a lower-than-expected 2.2 percent rise in the
third-quarter gross national product.
   But the lack of follow-through buying, as well the interpretation
that the inflation indicators were not as strong as anticipated,
sent the metals drifiting.
   Gold settled $1.50 to $1.90 higher, with October at $408.30 a
troy ounce; silver was unchanged to 3 cents hgher, with October at
6.224 cents a troy ounce.
   Platinum, traded on the New York Mercantile Exchange, settled 60
cents lower to 10 cents higher, with October at $536.40 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
