<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-Airlines 1stLd-Writethru   10-26 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Airlines, 1st Ld-Writethru,0654</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TWA, Pan Am Post Higher Third-Quarter Profits</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS lede to UPDATE with USAir results; picks up 2nd graf pvs
bg'ng, New York-based TWA ...; ADDS new grafs 19-23 to UPDATE with
USAir; No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Trans World Airlines Inc. and Pan Am Corp. on Wednesday reported
increases in their third-quarter profit from a year earlier, while
USAir Group Inc.'s net income was reduced by merger costs.
   New York-based TWA said its net income in the three months ended
Sept. 30 jumped 54.4 percent to $88 million, or $2.39 a share, from
$57.1 million, or $1.41 a share, a year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue was up 4.9 percent to $1.27 billion from
$1.21 billion.
   TWA, the nation's seventh-largest airline, was taken private on
Monday by its chairman and owner, Carl Icahn.
   Lawsuits against the privatization have been filed by some TWA
shareholders and the pilots union at the airline. In addition, the
union representing TWA flight attendants has asked the Department of
Transportation to block the privatization and freeze the airline's
assets while it investigates Icahn's fitness to continue managing
TWA.
   The TWA pilots union joined the flight attendants' petition, and
the Consumer Federation of America has filed a similar petition with
the DOT.
   TWA General Counsel Mark Buckstein said recently that the carrier
plans to lease or buy about 60 new aircraft to upgrade its aging
fleet, at a cost of up to $1.5 billion.
   In the first nine months of the year, TWA's profit more than
doubled _ to $132.7 million, or $2.89 a share, from $55.2 million,
or 45 cents a share, a year earlier.
   The latest nine-month profit includes a special gain of $49.9
million from a cash payment awarded to TWA in a long-standing
lawsuit against its former owner, the late Howard Hughes.
   The TWA management's suit, originally filed in 1962, alleged that
the eccentric multimillionaire failed to provide the carrier with
adequate aircraft. Although a Delaware court decided in TWA's favor
last year, the payment was not made until the second quarter of 1988.
   Revenue in the first nine months rose 7.77 percent, to $3.33
billion from $3.09 billion.
   Pan Am, also based in New York, said its third-quarter net income
edged up 6.3 percent, helped by continuing improvement in profits
from its Northeast shuttle and Pan Am Express commuter operations.
   The eighth-largest U.S. airline reported that its profit in the
three months ended Sept. 30 rose to $67.4 million, or 47 cents a
share, from $63.4 million, or 45 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue expanded 13.7 percent, to $1.20 billion
from $1.06 billion.
   The company said the growth in revenue was boosted by strong
passenger traffic.
   ``In fact, Pan Am set a new quarterly record for revenue,
surpassing the levels reported during the time when the airline was
operating its Pacific division,'' Chairman Thomas Plaskett said.
   In the first nine months of the year, Pan Am had a net loss of
$21.0 million, widened from a loss of $19.8 million a year earlier.
   The loss occurred despite a 16.9 percent rise in revenue for the
nine months, to $3.18 billion from $2.72 billion.
   Washington-based USAir said its third-quarter profit was trimmed
4.5 percent by expenses related to its acquisitions of Piedmont
Aviation and Pacific Southwest Airlines.
   The nation's ninth-biggest airline saw its net income slip to
$68.5 million, or $1.58 a share, from $71.7 million, or $1.66 a
share, a year earlier.
   The decline occurred despite an 87.3 percent jump in
third-quarter revenue, to $1.48 billion from $790.8 million.
   In the first nine months, USAir's profit fell to $142.2 million,
or $3.28 a share, from $167.9 million, or $4.80 a share.
   Nine-month revenue surged to $4.22 billion from $1.87 billion.
</TEXT>
