<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 2247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Pillsbury     10-26 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pillsbury,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Dismisses Grand Met Takeover Suit, Returns Case To
State Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC is considering appealing a federal judge's
dismissal of its suit to strike down an Arizona law that would bar
its proposed $5.2 billion buyout of Pillsbury Co., an attorney for
Grand Met said Wednesday.
   U.S. District Judge Roger Strand in Phoenix also has denied Grand
Met's motion for a preliminary injunction to bar enforcement of the
Arizona state takeover law in the deal.
   Strand on Monday dismissed Grand Met's Oct. 4 lawsuit that
contended the Arizona law barring out-of-state takeovers of Arizona
businesses holding liquor licenses was illegal because it improperly
hindered interstate commerce and infringed on federal authority over
interstate securities dealings.
   Businesses owned by Pillsbury, the nation's fourth-largest food
company, includ the Bennigan's and Steak and Ale chains.
   Bennigan's has restaurants in Phoenix and Mesa, and because the
restaurants have liquor licenses the state liquor control
superintendant must approve any takeover of them by an out-of-state
company.
   Strand said the federal courts should defer to the state courts
when action at that level is pending, important state interests are
involved and the state proceedings provided ``an adequate
opportunity to raise the federal questions.''
   Philip J. MacDonnell, a Phoenix lawyer representing Grand
Metropolitan, said the company was considering an appeal of Strand's
decision.
   Grand Metropolitan, one of the world's biggest producers of
spirits, has said it would sell off Pillsbury's Steak & Ale and
Bennigan's restaurants because of laws in a number of states
prohibiting a liquor producer from owning retail liquor outlets.
   Grand Met filed its suit the same day it offered to buy Pillsbury
for $60 a share. Pillsbury since then has rejected the offer as
inadequate, and indicated it would present its shareholders with an
alternative to the British food, liquor and real estate conglomerate
by next Tuesday.
   Pillsbury stock closed at $60.62{, up $1.50 a share from
Tuesday's close, on Wednesday in New York Stock Exchange trading.
   The Minneapolis-based company's board of directors reportedly met
on Wednesday, although Pillsbury declined to comment on the reports
and Johnny Thompson, Pillsbury's vice president of public relations,
said the company had nothing to announce.
   Pillsbury also filed a lawsuit Oct. 4, in Maricopa County
Superior Court, claiming Grand Metropolitan's takeover attempt
should be blocked because it violates Arizona's Acquisition of
Control Act.
   Joseph E. Mais Jr., a Phoenix lawyer representing Pillsbury, said
Wednesday that he expects both sides to file motions quickly in the
state case but nothing had been scheduled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
