<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 2337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Caterpillar-UAW     10-26 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Caterpillar-UAW,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Largest Caterpillar Local Says Yes To New Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The largest union local representing
workers at Caterpillar Inc. approved a tentative labor contract
Wednesday, virtually assuring ratification of the three-year deal
covering 17,500 employees in five states.
   Seventy-four percent of the members of United Auto Workers Local
974 who voted in East Peoria supported the tentative agreement while
26 percent opposed it, said local President Tony Green. He said he
could not give actual vote totals for Local 974, which has 10,033
members.
   Caterpillar spokesman Gil Nolde declined to comment on the vote.
   The tentative contract, worked out late last Friday by union and
company bargainers, includes a 3 percent wage increase and lump-sum
bonuses of about 3 percent. It affects workers in plants at 12
cities in Illinois, Iowa, Colorado, Tennessee and Pennsylvania.
   Another major provision is 100 percent job security to 85 percent
of the current workforce.
   Other provisions call for improved pension benefits, early
retirement allowances and night shift bonuses.
   Ratification votes are scheduled this weekend in Pontiac, Ill.,
Aurora, Ill., Memphis, Tenn., and Denver.
   Peoria-based Caterpillar, the world's largest manufacturer of
earth-moving equipment, is piling up the best sales and profits in
its 63-year history. Executives say 1988 could be the most
profitable, eclipsing 1981 when the company earned $578 million.
   The company's union workers now earn an average of $14.61 per
hour, or $30,388 per year.
</TEXT>
